<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLSCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY-UNITED MATCH HAS HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass _ Finally, the sequel has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has waited three years to avenge its 1996 disaster to
D.C. United, one of only two times in franchise history that the
Galaxy blew a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, United captured the Major League Soccer's
inaugural title, scoring three goals in monsoon-like rains and
winds over the final 21 minutes to earn a sudden-death, 3-2
overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Galaxy has become soccer's version of the
Buffalo Bills and Cleveland Indians _ having regular-season
success, but choking when it really counts.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has gone through two coaches and a change of
ownership to get back to the championship. But the latest coach,
Sigi Schmid, was a proven winner during 19 seasons at UCLA, winning
three national titles. And the owner, Denver-based billionaire
Philip F. Anschutz, has given Schmid the luxury of pampering his
team, allowing weekend getaways, and giving Schmid the freedom to
coach without distractions from management.
</P>
<P>
   But it all won't mean much if the Galaxy can't erase the
memories of 1996 and bring Los Angeles its first pro championship
since the 1988 Dodgers won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The weather, expected in the mid 50s and clear, provides a much
better setting than the last time these two met here.
</P>
<P>
   In front of more than 50,000 expected at Foxboro, Mass., for
today's reunion, the Galaxy and United will meet on the same field
where United's dynasty began and where the Galaxy's misfortunes
started.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in the Boston area are hyping the rematch angle with
full-page advertisements, wondering if these two teams can top what
many remember as the best game MLS has ever produced with the '96
final.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Galaxy was the favorite. This time, it is
the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations and stakes are much higher than they were in
'96,'' said Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri. ``That's because of
what D.C. has done in the past. They've been to the final every
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But D.C. knows we play quality soccer as well. We are the two
teams regarded as the best in this country and play the most
enjoyable style for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you look at each of our last games. D.C. pounds
Columbus 4-0, and we take apart Dallas, 3-1. You couldn't ask for
anything better. You have the best team's peaking at the same time,
plus you have that rivalry built up from the inaugural season. It's
a perfect showcase for soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a mutual respect between the two sides. They both have
been the most dominant clubs in their conferences over a four-year
period. United has been in all four MLS championships, winning the
first two before losing to Chicago last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which plays in a much tougher conference, has won
three Western Conference regular season titles and will make its
second trip to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Head-to-head, United leads the overall series, 8-4, and has won
six of the past seven meetings. This year the clubs split their
head-to-head series, with each winning on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sigi turning things around we expected the Galaxy to be
here this year,'' said United defender Jeff Agoos. ``We pretty much
knew if they played the way they could play, it would set up this
big game. They dodged some pretty good tests in the playoffs with
Dallas and certainly the league couldn't ask for a better dream
match-up.''
</P>
<P>
   United coach Thomas Rongen brushed aside the revenge factor.
After United loss to Chicago in last year's championship, he said
both team's will arrive this afternoon with something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The revenge factor doesn't mean anything to us, but it
certainly means something to them,'' said Rongen. ``Certainly our
guys remember the feeling against Chicago last year just as they
remember the feeling of '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a huge disappointment if we don't win this game.
But in a one-game championship with two evenly matched teams,
anything can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
