<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHTERHURT-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY STRIKES IN RING, JOHNSON COLLAPSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ The main event between Andrew Golota and Michael
Grant was delayed Saturday night for the worst of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the semi-main event, a Brooklyn junior middleweight named
Stephan Johnson showed once again how dangerous a profession prize
fighting can be when he collapsed in the 10th round of his USBA
junior middleweight championship fight with Paul Vaden and was
taken from the ring on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was leading on the master scorecard now used in New
Jersey by 1 point at the time, had absorbed considerable punishment
before he finally went down almost on his own at 2:24 of the round
when he staggered backward after being hit by a jab. As Johnson
fell, Vaden nailed him with a final long, left hand and he tumbled
to the floor in a neutral corner.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's neck hit the bottom strand of ropes and he lay
motionless until ringside physicians rushed in and covered his face
with an oxygen mask for more than 10 minutes before immobilizing
his neck and bringing in a stretcher as an obviously concerned
Vaden watched from across the ring, a pained expression on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson never opened his eyes as he was carried out and the
concern for him mounted as his handlers looked on helplessly back
in his locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a bad hit the last one,'' said Dr. Rick Snepar. ``He
looked like he may have seized after he hit the ground. He's still
breathing, but it's shallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Johnson was removed on a stretcher and taken by
ambulance to Atlantic City Medical Center with his wife and fiancee
accompanying him.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his locker room, his handlers stood in stony silence,
not only fearing the worst but knowing they had received a warning
in April when Johnson went down in eerily similar fashion during a
fight in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing happened in Canada,'' trainer Kenny Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   That was against Canadian champion Fritz Vanderpool in a fight
for the little known WBF title. Vanderpool won that fight the same
way Vaden won Saturday night, with Johnson stopped by an 11th round
TKO without being hit flush. But Johnson came back from that to
fight twice more this year and win, including a knockout of Calvin
Moody in October.
</P>
<P>
   But as he lay on a stretcher Saturday night, unconscious and
barely breathing, the memory of his handlers was not of a victory
but of the ultimate defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't stop breathing but the seizure suggested something
major,'' Dr. Snepar said. ``Some form of brain damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
