<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-HEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BURNED BY HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ ``This was personal,'' said the Heat's Tim Hardaway, his
voice very angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very personal,'' agreed Alonzo Mourning. ``We wanted to
shut them up, all the cheering and gyrations when they swept us
last year. That was enough motivation right there. All the
headlines, `Boston owns the Heat.' This is a business, but
(Saturday night) it was personal. We wanted to let them know who
the better team is.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA standings said this was a battle for the Atlantic
Division lead, the Heat vs. the Celtics, but Miami first wanted to
address some leftover business from last season. Personally. And
the Heat delivered the message, trouncing the Celtics, 110-92, in
Boston's last game at the Miami Arena _ the Heat move to a new
venue next month.
</P>
<P>
   Both coaches spoke in coach-speak in analysing the game. ``I
think coming off their big win Friday night they were tired,'' said
the Heat's Pat Riley. Rick Pitino said the game was not a true test
because Miami had had three nights off while the Celtics had played
``four games in five nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was three games in four nights but that mattered
little because Miami (8-2) proved that its fastest start in
franchise history is no fluke. And the Celtics proved . . . well,
that the real identity of this Celtics team is yet to be
determined. Not yet close to Miami, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat in the Heat was clearly evident when garbage time
began late in the fourth quarter and Hardaway and the Celtics'
Antoine Walker crossed paths on the court as subs flooded the
floor..
</P>
<P>
   ``Go home, now,'' Hardaway shouted at Walker. And Walker shouted
back, ``It's a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season's regular-season series sweep of the Heat by the
Celtics was one of Boston's few bright lights. The Heat players
more than remembered the numbers. ``Don't say this was just a
game,'' said Hardaway, which Pitino and other Celtics more or less
said. ``This was more than a game.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three quarters it was a semblance of a game. Rookie
Adrian Griffin scored Boston's first 7 points (and 11 in the first
quarter), Walker was passing the ball and slipping inside for
several nifty baskets (``I thought Antoine player very well,'' said
Pitino) and Boston hung close, trailing, 28-27, after one and 54-49
at the half.
</P>
<P>
   But a horrid stretch near the end of the third quarter when the
Celtics turned the ball over four times on five trips down court
(``They were mainly unforced errors,'' said Pitino) sealed their
fate. A fate that loomed also because the Heat's Dan Majerle did a
magnificent job defending Paul Pierce. Pierce had his first basket
with 5:48 left in the first half and finished with only 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mourning (22 points, 6 rebounds, and 3 blocked shots)
was devastating against the center-deficient Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Portland,'' Pitino said. ``We can't come in against
the Heat and beat ourselves. Our No. 1 dilemma this year is
turnovers and it was once again (last) night. When we run our
offense, we get good shots but when we break our offense we turn
the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley was surpised the Celtics did not unleash their signature
pressing defense. ``They did not pressure us that much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat's Majerle and Mourning certainly pressured the
Celtics. ``Majerle played great defense,'' said Riley. ``Paul
Pierce didn't get many touches. Dan shadowed him and made it a
tough night for Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Celtics didn't help their cause much by turning the ball
over 20 times and getting a measly seven fast-break points (the
Heat had 24).
</P>
<P>
   The Heat's Jamal Mashburn scored 23, buried four 3-point
attempts, and was a force on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first acquired Jamal, I thought we were getting a
post-up player,'' said Riley of the former Kentucky star. ``It
turns out that he's a great up-and-down-the-court player who loves
to slash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
