<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HURRICANES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFLED STARS BLANKED BY HURRICANES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Floyd 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Mike Keane has had enough of the euphemisms and
silver linings and positive outlooks.
</P>
<P>
   After last night's 1-0 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes, the
Stars winger called the just-finished road trip as he saw it. The
view wasn't too good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a \Rhorrible\S road trip,'' Keane said in not-so-pleasant
terms. ``It's almost December, and I haven't looked at the
standings, but I've seen the box scores. Phoenix and LA are winning
and getting points. We aren't. You've got to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars captain Derian Hatcher: ``It's not that early any
more. It's 20 games in, a quarter of a season and we're 8-9-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Stars were below .500 was the beginning of the
1997-98 season when they started 0-1-1. You have to go back to the
1995-96 season to find another .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   The loss that ended that better-than-.500 streak had a familiar
feel _ a well-played game defensively, a defensive error that ended
up in Dallas' goal (Carolina's Paul Ranheim scored at 8:39 of the
second period) and a strong performance by goalie Ed Belfour. It
all added up to a loss because the Stars struggled to generate good
scoring chances and failed to score goals necessary to win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You allow one goal on the road, you've done your job
defensively,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Our problem is
still the same. We're still too light offensively, not near at the
level of determination or sacrifice necessary. ... It's really up
to the individual. Offensive hockey comes from hungriness. When
you're not hungry, you do bad things often. You don't make things
happen. We just don't have the hungriness.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Stars backup Arturs Irbe stopped all 24 of his former
teammates' shots for the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have scored five goals in last four games, including a
downward slide on this trip. After scoring two goals in Washington
on Wednesday, Dallas scored a single goal in Philadelphia on
Thursday and finished with a goose egg against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring struggles aren't anything new, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have scored more than two goals in a game only five
times this season, going undefeated in those games. Meanwhile, they
have been shut out four times this season. They were shut out 10
times all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our second and third chances are really few and far between,
and that's how we're going to break out of this,'' Stars forward
Mike Modano said. ``It's one shot here, one shot there. ... It's
really tough to keep trying to figure it out, day in and day out,
what the problem is.''
</P>
<P>
   The six forwards on the Stars' top two lines have accounted for
25 of their 41 goals this season. Defensemen have scored six more,
meaning the Stars have gotten only 10 goals from the rest of their
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all a little frustrated especially guys on the
third and fourth lines,'' said third-line winger Blake Sloan, who
has a goal and an assist in 20 games. ``If we're able to pop a
couple, that'd alleviate pressure off the top lines. ... I think we
need one to go off a butt or a shin pad, just to get the ball
rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two other teams in the NHL have scored fewer goals than
Dallas _ the New York Islanders (32) and the Atlanta Thrashers
(40). Like the Stars, all of these teams are at the bottom of their
respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Stars players and coaches were preaching patience a couple of
weeks ago, saying standings didn't matter. The goals would start
coming, they said. The victories would follow. The standings would
take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been almost two months, and the Stars are beginning to
realize that scoreless games don't bring victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we know it, January is going to be around,'' Modano
said. ``To keep teams to three, two or one goal a game is great on
our part, but there is a whole other side to the game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
