<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6842 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USCUCLA-LADN     11-21 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCUCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HELPS MORTON KEEP HIS PROMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chad Morton sat atop his teammates' shoulders
Saturday, the reward for keeping a promise: Eight was enough.
</P>
<P>
   The USC tailback was given a hero's ride amid the hundreds of
students celebrating on the Coliseum turf following the Trojans'
17-7 over UCLA before 91,384.
</P>
<P>
   After the decade began with Johnnie Morton catching the winning
touchdown pass against the Bruins, USC had gone eight years without
a victory over its crosstown rival when little brother Chad made
his brash prediction last summer.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday night, no one was doubting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad Morton can predict all he wants if he's going to be
right,'' UCLA wide receiver Danny Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Case closed. The Trojans finally ended years of futility against
UCLA by outmuscling the Bruins. USC had 214 yards rushing; UCLA
managed just 45. And doing most of the heavy lifting was Morton,
who ran for 143 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they had me up there on their shoulders, it's what I've
dreamed of,'' Morton said. ``To be a factor in the game, to be a
contributor and then to be carried off. There's no greater feeling
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a fitting reference to Johnnie Morton's big play in 1990,
he said, ``They're calling us bookends now.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it was one of the uglier games of the rivalry,
befitting a pair of teams that entered the contest with 4-6
records. USC had 16 penalties and UCLA nine. The Bruins also had
five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   But the specter of the streak, and increased scrutiny of USC
coach Paul Hackett, added more emotion to this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bitter taste of last year, the way they rubbed it
in our face affected us,'' Hackett said. ``It was our time. Eight
years was a long, long time. I think the tide is turned and I feel
it will be turned for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But not without some controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trojans were moving the ball up and down the field,
scoring points was a little tougher. Other than a 22-yard touchdown
pass from John Fox to Kareem Kelly in the second quarter, the
Trojans managed only a field goal and led 10-7 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   USC lined up for a field goal on fourth-and-8 at UCLA's 26 late
in the third quarter, when Fox took the snap and rolled to his
right, where he found tailback Jabari Jackson wide open for a
16-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were still unable to score a touchdown and again
lined up for a field goal. But UCLA's Ryan Roques dived into kicker
David Newbury, giving USC a first down, and the Trojans finally
scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they did and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Fox found Kelly in the corner on a 5-yard pass and the freshman
caught the ball and was ruled to have scored a touchdown. Replays
showed his left foot landed out of bounds, but side judge Harvey
Jones ruled it a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know. I looked to the side and saw the ref's
hands go up. I did think it was a touchdown,'' Kelly said.
``Regardless if it was a touchdown or not, we still would have won
the game. Who's to say we wouldn't have come back and gotten a
touchdown anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, referee Jim Sprenger issued a statement to a pool
reporter: ``From where (Jones) was on the field, he saw the
receiver get control of the ball in the air and saw and felt he was
in bounds because he saw his second foot first, but when the
observers came in after the game, they said the first foot hit out
of bounds, and that would make an incomplete pass. That's the way
he saw it and there's nothing that can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo said Jones approached him afterward and
said he blew the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a mistake, but hey, he's human,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   USC also had its own contention. UCLA's DeShaun Foster appeared
to fumble, after defensive end Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed tore the
ball out of his hands, and ran nearly 75 yards before being
tackled. But the officials ruled Foster down on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year for us, let's don't even talk about calls,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (4-7, 2-6) did not lead statistically, but freshman
quarterback Ryan McCann of Agoura High had several opportunities to
pull out a victory. McCann threw three interceptions, however, and
all were damaging. Linebacker Zeke Moreno snared a pass at USC's
8-yard line to snuff out a scoring chance, and free safety David
Gibson caught a tipped pass at the Trojans' 2.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson also picked off McCann with three minutes left to
officially seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have dreamed going out this way playing like this
against UCLA,'' Gibson said. ``This is the best game I've ever had,
ending this streak. It's so important to USC alumni. I feel good
for the guys before us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it makes up for everything. This is the way I
wanted to go out against UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (5-6, 3-5) also sacked McCann six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, that was the best we played since I've been
here the last two years,'' USC defensive line coach Ed Orgeron
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of inspired play that has usually been missing
during all eight years of the streak, and had been absent from many
of this season's USC games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a miserable season, but here's this big beacon at the
end of the season,'' Hackett said. ``This is a monster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
