<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY'S TD BRINGS CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a game that screamed out for a hero, a
touch of drama, a great moment, or something.
</P>
<P>
   It settled for something _ a speck of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's annual USC-UCLA titanic was being reduced to a
forgettable game of ``we can mess up more than you,'' when the
Trojans provided a morning conversation piece with a touchdown that
probably wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Kelly pulled down a 5-yard fourth-quarter pass from
quarterback John Fox in the corner of the end zone for what was
ruled a touchdown, although the freshman appeared to clearly first
land with his right foot beyond the sideline marking.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was obviously out of bounds,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo
said. ``The official told me coming up the tunnel he made a
mistake. Officials are human, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo was careful not to blame the play for the eventual 17-7
loss, but at that point there was a three-point difference in an
odd game of six turnovers and 25 penalties, and it did not seem a
great stretch to imagine the Bruins somehow finding enough offense
to muster another score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, maybe they fumble on the next play,'' UCLA
cornerback Ricky Manning Jr. said. ``Maybe our offense feeds off
that and marches down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe UCLA's streak over USC is at nine, instead of minus-one.
</P>
<P>
   It was Manning who defended Kelly on the end-zone play. Friends
after the two played together in last year's Shrine Game, Manning
said he wasn't sure Kelly had landed out until his teammates told
him after watching a big-screen replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``A touchdown is a touchdown,'' Kelly said. ``It was a
controversial call, but all year we've lost games because of
controversial calls. It ain't nothing. Take it away, and we still
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet instead of a tight three-point game set up for another
possible dramatic finish in this long rivalry, USC had a 10-point
lead that had to appear mountainous to the struggling Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Jim Sprenger said side judge Harvey Jones did not see
Kelly's right foot land out first, but his left catch the edge of
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the observers came in after the game, they said the first
foot hit out of bounds, and that would make it an incomplete
pass,'' Sprenger said. ``That's the way he saw it, and there's
nothing that can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA officials said they were told Jones became confused by the
multiple lines surrounding the end zone. There were yellow and red
lines inbounds, and a white line marked the out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had put USC ahead in the second quarter when he caught a
22-yard bullet from Fox for the Trojans' other score.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained a 10-7 game in the fourth quarter, both teams
taking turns stumbling over themselves.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had tried a similar fade route in the corner of the end
zone in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it too, to Danny Farmer,'' Toledo said. ``He was out
of bounds. They called him out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Farmer: ``They called him in, and called me out. That's the
way it goes sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Manning both went up for the Fox toss, but Kelly
cleanly won the mid-air battle for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get both feet down, because I knew I was close,''
Kelly said. ``When I looked at the replay, I saw my left foot drag.
I didn't see my right foot.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been the foot landing first, and beyond the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Take away the touchdown and who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have scored again,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we were going, we couldn't score anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
