<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TRIP UP THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As thousands of USC fans celebrated on the
Coliseum turf, UCLA freshman quarterback Ryan McCann walked out of
the losing locker room, dropped his bags and opened his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot today; it's just too bad I had to learn it
against SC,'' he said with a quiet voice and glazed eyes. ``I feel
like 90,000 knives stabbed me and ripped me apart.''
</P>
<P>
   A few came from within.
</P>
<P>
   For disgruntled UCLA fans, Saturday's 17-7 loss was about the
touchdown that wasn't. For the discouraged Bruins (4-7, 2-6), it
was about everything else _ the missed tackles and the
interceptions, the dropped passes and the fumbles, the blown
coverages and the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the touchdown that wasn't would never have been if
not for a roughing-the-kicker penalty on UCLA senior Ryan Roques
two plays earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the emotion and it wasn't the effort,'' Bruins
defensive end Kenyon Coleman said. ``We've just got to execute. You
can't make that many mistakes and expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with a makeshift offensive line and a freshman quarterback
making his first start. Not with a condensed playbook designed to
limit mistakes. Not with a porous defense that yielded 430 yards.
And not with an inspired (and talented) Trojans defense fueled by
eight years of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Bruins had no margin for error, yet they cost themselves
21 potential points with three turnovers inside USC's 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes,'' Bruins defensive captain Pete
Holland said. ``There were lots of little fires. It was a microcosm
of the season, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann completed 17 of 29 passes for 204 yards and carried
himself well against USC's relentless pass rush. But he missed
several open receivers and threw three interceptions, including one
at USC's 8 and one at USC's 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had enough time to throw,'' McCann said. ``I just threw to
the wrong guys at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's other crushing turnover came midway through the fourth
quarter. After the blown touchdown call gave USC a 17-7 lead, the
Bruins moved 74 yards in eight plays. On first down at the 7, USC's
Ifeanyi Ohalete slapped the ball from tailback DeShaun Foster.
Bruins tackle Bryce Bohlander pounced, but it squirted away from
under him and Ohalete recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it happened,'' Foster said, hunched over in
his stall in the far corner of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   There were other mistakes, plenty of them.
</P>
<P>
   _Receiver Freddie Mitchell dropped two passes, including a
potential touchdown midway through the second quarter, and
sure-handed Danny Farmer dropped one.
</P>
<P>
   _Tailback Jermaine Lewis' face-mask penalty on a punt return
gave the Trojans great field position (UCLA's 45) from which to
begin their game-clinching touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   _Roques' roughing-the-kicker penalty, with 14 minutes remaining,
gave the Trojans first down at UCLA's 2. A few seconds later,
quarterback John Fox hit receiver Kareem Kelly in the end zone _ or
out of the end zone _ for the decisive touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, it appeared Roques might have been blocked into
kicker David Newbury, which would have negated the penalty, but he
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped where I normally jump, and he hopped into me,''
Roques said. ``I don't think it was a good call. I was way in front
of the holder. He came forward into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the complaints of a dead streak and a lost season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
