r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-T     11-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED MAVS ROUTED ON ROAD BY SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ This was not the way the Mavericks wanted to start
a 16-day stretch with eight of their next nine games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs pushed the Mavericks around as if they
were blocking dummies. With Cedric Ceballos and Steve Nash in
street clothes, and Gary Trent in Cleveland seeking a second
opinion on his strained left hamstring, the Mavericks never had a
chance against the defending NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs got 23 points from backup forward Jaren Jackson and
overwhelmed the short-handed Mavericks, 106-90, before 16,596 last
night at the Alamodome. The Mavericks are 4-7 after dropping their
third consecutive game, while the Spurs improved to 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos missed the game because of the flu. Nash took a
cortisone injection for an injured right ankle after Friday night's
game against Sacramento, and is slated to visit with team doctors
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at quite a disadvantage,'' Mavericks coach/general
manager Don Nelson said. ``We decided to try to take their inside
game away, and left the perimeter open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured if they were going to make \Rperimeter\S shots we
were going to lose. And they did, and we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs had the game well in hand midway through the third
period when they were up, 62-40. The only footnote remaining was
when former Mavericks forward Samaki Walker would make his
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Walker got into the game with 3:08 remaining in the
third quarter, the Spurs were already ahead, 70-46. Walker finished
with four points, eight rebounds and a blocked shot in 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just another game,'' Walker said. ``We came out with a
big win.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the game when you look and see where that `W'
lies, that's got to be the most important aspect for me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, it was virtually target practice as he found
himself wide open for many shots. Jackson made 8 of 19 shots,
including a career-high tying seven 3-pointers in a franchise-high
16 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have enough bodies to go up against them,'' said
guard Erick Strickland, who finished with 14 points and seven
rebounds. ``So, when they made their run there was nothing we could
do about it. We just had to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks trailed, 48-36, at the half. But the Spurs used a
14-4 run to open the third period, with Chucky Brown scoring six of
those points, to open up a 62-40 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have enough firepower, but I thought we competed
really hard,'' said guard Hubert Davis, who had nine points and
seven assists. ``We're all professionals, and the other people that
get to play just have to step up and just play as hard as they
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley led the Mavericks with 19 points while playing 40
minutes. Dirk Nowitzki finished with 16 points and 12 rebounds,
while Shawn Bradley collected 16 points, 10 rebounds and four
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Spurs' Twin Towers of Tim Duncan and David
Robinson were barely noticeable. Duncan did finish with 14 points
and 17 rebounds, and Robinson added seven points and seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But with Brown connecting on eight of 11 field-goal attempts for
16 points, and point guard Avery Johnson hitting 6-of-12 for 12
points, the Mavericks were caught between choosing whether to die
slowly from the outside or the inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough playing like this and starting off on the road with
a bad loss like this,'' guard Robert Pack said. ``Hopefully we can
get a couple of guys back who were not feeling well, and just have
a better effort Tuesday \Rat Houston\S.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
