<SLUG> BC-BKN-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA UNEASY ABOUT RIDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes bright NBA executives can make the most boneheaded
mistakes imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Atlanta Hawks, for example. What in the world possessed
the Hawks to trade a darn good player _ and human being _ like
Steve Smith to Portland for a headache like Isaiah Rider? Hawks
executive Pete Babcock is one of the most respected general
managers in the business, but this made absolutely no sense, Petey.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is Exhibit A on how to be a professional. He comes to work
on time. He used his talents to make the all-star team. He gave his
alma mater, Michigan State, more than $1 million to build a student
center in honor of his late mother.
</P>
<P>
   Good guy. Clean image.
</P>
<P>
   Rider is Exhibit A on how not to be a professional. He's late a
lot of times for practice, games and planes. His ego demands that
the ball always goes through him on offense, or else he thinks
something must be wrong with the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, the Hawks suspended Rider for a game after
he didn't show up for practice. It seems two of Rider's vehicles
were damaged at the hotel were he's temporarily living, and Rider
thought the cars needed his undivided attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had paperwork and stuff to do,'' Rider said. ``It's
unfortunate what happened to my cars. It's unfortunate that I got
suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Isaiah, it's unfortunate that the Hawks thought you were
more valuable than Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Portland threw Jim Jackson in the deal to sweeten the pot for
Babcock. But Mavericks fans remember the day in Salt Lake City when
Jackson chastised guard Scott Brooks for not passing him the ball
in the waning seconds before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   At least now, Babcock is not playing spin doctor. He admits
bringing in Rider was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the deal looking at the worse-case scenario,'' Babcock
said. ``So far, it has been the worse-case scenario. There's no use
sugarcoating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, then we won't sugarcoat it, either. You blew it, Babcock.
Big-time.
</P>
<P>
   Rider has become Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens most challenging
assignment in his 27 years on the NBA bench. And Wilkens isn't
sleeping well these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a point where enough is enough, but we aren't there
yet,'' Wilkens said. ``You can only push people so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect is a two-way street. So you have to have a player who
wants to be helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with all of his trangressions, this past week Rider had to
nerve to say: ``This is not a strong team. That's why you've got to
give \Rthe ball\S to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make me the man like Steve Smith was, or get me out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks will be better served if they heed Rider's words and
get him out of there.
\Nsubheds:QUICK HITS Leon fallout Landon Cox is still fuming at the
Mavericks for what he calls their poor treatment of 19-year-old
rookie Leon Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas did not make a mistake drafting Leon, because he has
the talent to play in the NBA,'' said Cox, who coached Smith at
Chicago's Martin Luther King High School. ``Where they made
mistakes is when they failed to get to know him and find out about
the tremendous problems he's been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ignored him and refused to treat him like a human being.
They just treated him like a piece of meat. They never even called
me for imput or returned my calls to them this summer until
\RWednesday morning\S after this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday night, Smith was taken to Parkland Hospital's
psychiatric ward after allegedly overdosing on 250 aspirin. The
6-foot-10 forward has been released from the hospital after having
his stomach pumped.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the Mavericks showed no sensitivity when it came to
nurturing Smith, who was a ward of the state of Illinois from age 4
through 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas wants ready-made players,'' Cox said. ``But they
weren't ready to give Leon the special attention he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the Maverick organization had a job to play here.
There is teaching going on even in the pros. But these people in
Dallas don't care.'' \Nsubheds:Good ol' boys Jason Williams won't
discount his high school buddy Randy Moss as the next two-sport
athlete. Moss, a wide receiver with the Minnesota Vikings, said
earlier this season he'd like to tryout for the Minnesota
Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew up with Moss in Virginia and the two played high
school basketball together. They're also featured in a national
shoe commericial where highlights of their high-school playing days
are woven in with clips of Williams playing basketball with
Sacramento and Moss playing football with Minnesota. All highlights
are done to the Dukes of Hazard theme song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have got Randy interested in basketball in high school
but this is all him,'' Williams said. ``He loves football. He'd
struggle at first \Rin the NBA\S and maybe have to go to a summer
league and get some seasoning, but he can play. If anyone can do
it, he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think he just gets bored in the off-season and
wants something to do, so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams would rather concentrate on his crossover dribble
instead of crossing over to football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get killed out there,'' said the 6-foot-1, 190-pound
Williams. ``The only position I could play is quarterback and I
couldn't see having all those 300-pound defensive linemen and
linebackers chasing me. I'd get killed.''  &LR; name:Dave Dondoneau
\Nsubheds:Payton's place This past week, Gary Payton became
Seattle's all-time assist leader when he notched his 4,894th
assist. Payton passed Sonics' assistant coach Nate McMillan, with
whom Payton is very close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to pass Nate,'' Payton said. ``I came in the
league with him and he's like a big brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for \Rthe record\S, and I'm glad it was a guy I
really respect and love.''
</P>
<P>
   When McMillan retired from playing last March 24, Payton
presented him with a $30,000 Rolex watch, and the inscription on
the back read: ``Take It Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' McMillan said, showing off his watch. ``It's
love there.''
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT
Riley has once-stifling Heat playing red-hot on offense
The Miami Heat, running?
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so, Pat Riley, say it ain't so.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the team known for it's half-court offense, for
pounding the air out of the ball and firing up a shot just before
the 24-second clock expires, is actually running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Heat is ranked fourth in the NBA in scoring with 105.7
points per game. The Heat topped the century mark in five of its
first six games this season, after performing that feat on only
four occasions during the entire 1998-'99 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking like the old Lakers,'' said Heat point guard Tim
Hardaway, in comparing the Heat to Riley's old run-and-gun Showtime
LA Lakers of the 1980's. ``But we're not a run-and-gun team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a run-and-score team. This is how it's going to be for
the rest of the season. We have the horses _ we always have.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley likes to call his team a ``sneaky fastbreak'' squad.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Riley and everyone with the Heat thought the new NBA
rules would hinder his team's work. The Heat are known as the
toughest defensive team in the league, and the new rules prevents
players from dislodging opponents in the post, and disallows
hand-checking.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat have actually benefitted from the new rules. Alonzo
Mourning is averaging 22 points, former Mavericks forward Jamal
Mashburn averages 19.9 points, and Hardaway averages 17.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   So, what gives?
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as the new rules are going to hurt us defensively,''
said Riley, ``they will help us offensively because we have players
who can go to the basket. We can score.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
