<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FEELING POWERLESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It isn't quite at Defcon 4, but the Kings have a
crisis. Their power play continues to fail, unmasked by a more
disturbing trend of a lack of enthusiasm and lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Showing interest in only moderate portions during the first two
periods, the Kings lost 5-3 to an inferior and obviously less
talented Montreal Canadiens squad before a soldout Staples Center
crowd of 18,118 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time that the Kings have lost back-to-back games
this season. The Canadiens won their third road game of the season
and first since Oct. 14. They also won for the third time since
Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The urgent matter for the Kings is finding an answer to a couple
of puzzling questions.
</P>
<P>
   First, what happened to the power play that was dominating
games? And second, how can bottom feeders Chicago and Montreal come
to L.A. and outwork the Kings?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to swallow, but it's a good sign that it's (22)
games into the season before we did it,'' Kings defenseman Rob
Blake said. ``The passes weren't where they were supposed to be.
The power play wasn't going. That's why we won game early on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why they're losing them now.
</P>
<P>
   The power play, ranked third in the league, misfired on all
seven chances, including a 5-on-3 for one minute. The Kings have
not scored a power-play goal in their last three games, spanning 19
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from that, the Kings also turned off their intensity
switch. They survived to beat Chicago on Tuesday because goalie
Jamie Storr was splendid, but they lost to Phoenix two days later
against a Coyotes club that mucked and battled for three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Canadiens, fresh off a province-embarrassing 6-1 loss
to Nashville, skated with more purpose than the Kings. Andy Murray,
22 games into his tenure as Kings coach, wasn't ready to throw a
tirade but clearly was upset about this effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big thing was to step up and take responsibility,'' Murray
said. ``Everyone was there to get pats on the back when thing were
going well. Everyone should be there to take responsibility now.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who mixed lines in the third period to try to find a
spark, also didn't like his club's intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is not to be a cheerleader behind the bench,'' he said.
``Tonight, it was the coaching staff doing much of the talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times, the Kings cut two-goal deficits in half, but they
never scored the tying goal. They pulled within 3-2 early in the
third period on Marko Tuomainen's one-timer from the slot, but 1:33
later, a silly turnover allowed Montreal to pad its lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kings defenseman Aki Berg had a chance to swat away a bouncing
puck at center ice. Instead, it bounced off the heel of his stick
and Martin Rucinsky broke in alone on Storr, beating the goalie on
a backhander at the 3:40 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense played well for us (this season), but tonight
three of our six defensemen didn't play up to their level,'' Murray
said. ``We scored three goals in our building. We have to be better
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Kings had a chance late. Ziggy Palffy's second goal
of the night, a slapper from the slot, trimmed Montreal's lead to
4-3 with 12:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had a few chances to tie it, but none better than
Donald Audette's opportunity from the right side of goalie Jose
Theodore. With most of the net open, Theodore made the save and the
rebound trickled a few inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to bounce back and our guys did,'' Montreal coach Alain
Vigneault said. ``It is a challenge every day. In a city where
expectations are always very high, we're trying to keep our
sanity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
