<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-21 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. FANS TAKE RIVALRY SERIOUSLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You know what they say: Southern California sports
fans are so blase.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. And God gave us earthquakes to occasionally stir us
from our complacency.
</P>
<P>
   The truth the Houstons and the St. Louises and the New Yorks
don't want to hear is L.A. has pleasant weather and passionate
fans, too.
</P>
<P>
   The proof was in the Coliseum on Saturday, where neither the
threat of rain nor a local football drought of epic proportions
could keep 91,384 people from showing up to watch unranked USC beat
unhallowed UCLA 17-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' victory, their first over the Bruins since 1990,
was shown on network television, all the more reason for Angelenos
to stay inside where it was dry and warm.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there was gridlock on the surface streets surrounding
the Coliseum three hours before the opening kickoff. The cars were
not lined up like pearls on a string because Angelenos are starved
for entertainment or suckers for a matchup of national title
contenders or Bowl-bound teams.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1941, the Trojans (5-6; 3-5 in the
Pacific-10) and Bruins (4-7; 2-6) both came to the game with losing
records. So it wasn't the promise of great football that drew a
near-sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was passion and pride, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   Angelenos feel deeply and truly about our two major college
football teams. Loyalties to one school or the other are like fault
lines running through households, erupting every November.
</P>
<P>
   For USC fans, there had been a whole lot of shaking going on
since 1990, but not a lot of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The losses to UCLA kept coming like aftershocks, one after
another until it reached a numbing eight last year. Back in August,
running back Chad Morton, the heart and soul of the USC squad,
guaranteed a different ending this year.
</P>
<P>
   And so, cheering loudly and carrying a big umbrella, fans
streamed into the Coliseum on Saturday looking to either laud
Morton or mock him.
</P>
<P>
   What they were treated to was college football stripped of the
gaudy accessories _ the Bowl Championship Series rankings, the
Heisman Trophy hype and the like _ that have turned college
football into a sideshow to the main act of educating students.
</P>
<P>
   The 69th meeting of these two schools doesn't deserve a place in
the Getty Museum. It wasn't a masterpiece by anybody's reckoning.
There were 25 penalties and two atrocious calls by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed stripped the football from UCLA
running back DeShaun Foster and carried the ball inside the UCLA
10-yard line in the first quarter, but the Bruins retained
possession after officials ruled Foster was down and the play,
hence, over, when the turnover occurred.
</P>
<P>
   More egregious yet was the call by the side judge, Harvey Jones,
in the second minute of the fourth quarter with USC holding the
ball and the lead, 10-7. Quarterback John Fox lofted a pass to
freshman Kareem Kelly, who leaped to make the catch and landed with
his lead foot a few inches wide of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Jones signaled a touchdown and the score stood even though
replays on the video scoreboard showed Kelly clearly came down out
of bounds. Jones admitted after the game he had made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo said it was a bad call but wisely didn't
bother to plead his case. He would have had a valid protest if the
Bruins had lost by seven or fewer points. But after Jones' call,
the Bruins compounded his error with mistakes of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Foster lost the ball on the USC 7, freshman quarterback Ryan
McCann was intercepted by Trojans' senior safety David Gibson, and
Danny Farmer was stripped after making a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the stage was cleared for a pair of unlikely USC stars. It
was refreshing, in this day and age of the collegiate
student-athlete as NFL star-in-waiting, to see Fox and Morton bask
in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a senior who was lining up at linebacker for most of the
season, threw for 216 yards and two touchdowns and didn't have an
interception (McCann, by contrast, had three). Fox is using his
college experience as a springboard, all right _ to an elementary
school teaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Morton, who is 68 inches of desire, darted and danced for 143
yards on 36 carries and along the way became the third USC running
back this decade to surpass 1,000 yards for the season.
</P>
<P>
   He is too small to join his older brother Johnnie, a receiver,
in the NFL. Indeed, many of the students who streamed out of the
stands and mobbed Morton at midfield after time ran out on the
Bruins' season towered over him.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Nobody on this day stood taller.
</P>
<P>
   By predicting over the summer that the Trojans would win this
game and stubbornly sticking to it in the days leading to the game,
Morton bought himself a few sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nauseous,'' Morton said. ``I couldn't eat. The biggest
thing is, I wanted to back up what I had said.''
</P>
<P>
   When he had done just that, he let the crowd carry him away,
literally. Rapturous fans turned the Coliseum floor into a giant
mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best feeling,'' Morton said. ``It's the feeling you
want to have.''
</P>
<P>
   We doubt any of the players on the No. 1-ranked Florida State
team got any greater high from their win Saturday over their main
nemesis, Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As Gibson skirted police batons and accepted hugs from strangers
in the game's glorious aftermath, he felt humbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you get a realization of how much this game means to
people,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the evidence was incontrovertible: If you build a sports
rivalry, Angelenos will come. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
