<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE ENDS SEASON ON SOUR NOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The six-month odyssey for the Cal State Northridge
football team ended with the hated opposition dancing and pointing
and celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   The emotion the CSUN players carried into the season finale
against Northern Arizona was sapped by the Lumberjacks, who
physically dominated the Matadors in a 30-10 victory Saturday
afternoon at North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's season, which really started in May when the program went
under investigation for rules violations, ended with a losing
record. The Matadors dropped to 5-6 in front of 4,963.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN was 4-4 in the Big Sky Conference. The Matadors were 7-4
and 5-3 in the conference last year and Ron Ponciano was named Big
Sky Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano was fired in July in the wake of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to endure a lot,'' CSUN senior tailback Jaumal Bradley
said. ``This team faced a lot of adversity. Nobody expected us to
do this well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who had a career-high 170 yards in his final
college game, wanted badly to beat the 17th-ranked Lumberjacks, who
solidified their argument for a Division I-AA playoff spot. NAU
(8-3, 6-2) won its fifth consecutive game _ and broke a losing
streak against CSUN at two years.
</P>
<P>
   There is bad blood between the programs, which recruit heavily
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are kind of our rivals,'' said Brennen Swanson, a
senior defensive end who had one sack and ended his career with a
school-record 31{. ``There's some hard feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotion bubbled to the surface during the game, which had 26
penalties (15 on NAU) and a flurry of personal fouls in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, CSUN's interim head coach, was called for an
unsportsmanlike foul after erupting on the sideline in response to
a previous penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a physical game,'' CSUN quarterback Marcus Brady said.
``They were aggressive. I took a lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady was sacked four times and was hit several times after
throwing. He only completed 24 of 43 passes for 200 yards and he
threw three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks, who are third in the Big Sky Conference in
defense, held CSUN to 397 yards, 59 under its season average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, as a unit, (the Lumberjacks) are certainly one of
the top two (defensive teams we've faced),'' Kearin said. ``Man for
man, they have a lot of talent. They changed our philosophy; they
sat back and let us run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes, though, hurt the Matadors more than the Lumberjacks'
defense. Brady said his interceptions, the last of which was
returned by Cedric Jones 79 yards for a touchdown, were all on bad
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's first interception set the tone for the second half.
CSUN trailed 13-10 and was driving on its first third-quarter
possession. But Andre Smith picked off Brady at the NAU 5 and the
drive was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge play for them,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin said: ``That play took the wind out of our sails a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks broke the Matadors with another important play:
Francis St. Paul's 75-yard touchdown reception with 3 minutes, 44
seconds left that gave NAU a 22-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they got the big plays,'' said senior
linebacker Jack Heaslet, who had seven tackles. ``They weren't
manhandling us. It was just the big plays that got us.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN answered St. Paul's touchdown with a gutty drive, which
unfortunately for the Matadors, ended in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   After Brady was sacked at midfield for a 9-yard loss, Northridge
faced a second-and-30 to start the fourth quarter. The Matadors got
exactly 30 yards on the next three plays, including a 1-yard plunge
by DeJuan Gilmore on fourth-and-1. But then the drive stalled on
the NAU 26 and Brady's fourth-and-17 pass, intended for Drew
Amerson in the end zone, was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get a consistent drive,'' Brady said. ``It didn't
feel like we were in sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Brady's frustration was Jones' two fourth-quarter
interceptions. Jones received unsportsmanlike penalties for
taunting at the end of both returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I just gave (NAU) seven points,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   The final minute was also marred by a personal foul. CSUN senior
receiver Terrence Jones was ejected after punching an NAU player on
the sideline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
