<SLUG> BC-BOX-GOLOTA-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT BEATS DOWN GOLOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ How do you say ``no mas'' in Polish?
</P>
<P>
   That's what referee Randy Neumann was wondering when he asked
Andrew Golota if he wanted to continue after he'd been knocked down
at 1:31 of the 10th round in a fight he was leading by five points.
</P>
<P>
   Golota's reply was ``Nyet,'' or something to that effect, and
thus Michael Grant remained undefeated Saturday night at Trump Taj
Mahal, despite proving that he has no idea how to box.
</P>
<P>
   What Grant does know how to do, though, is fight, a point he
proved more thoroughly than he would have liked after Golota
dropped him twice in the first round and knocked him from pillar to
post for much of the night. He unleashed a barrage of punches
midway through the 10th round that stunned Golota.
</P>
<P>
   Golota tried to hold on and the two wrestled for a time before
Grant hit him with a second flurry that ended with a right hand
that sent the big Pole tumbling onto his right shoulder. When he
got up, Golota began wandering aimlessly around the ring like a man
looking for his glasses, his face red, his nose bleeding, and his
heart beginning to shrivel.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked, Neumann pursued him and when he finally caught up
to Golota they had a brief conversation on the subject of
continuing his employment. Golota declined that option and resigned
his position. What he also resigned from was a fight he was leading
by five points, an overwhelming margin that Grant understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the fight, Don (Turner, Grant's trainer) told me, `You
know what you have to do?' '' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   What he had to do to remain undefeated and in Lennox Lewis's
crosshairs was to stop the tiring Golota and he found a way to do
that. For this Grant deserves great praise because he had to
survive a brutal opening round in which he was knocked to the floor
from two jabs and a right hand. After getting up he went down a
second time at the end of the round from an overhand right that had
him on his hands and knees when the bell sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I went down it was a test of my faith,'' said
Grant (31-0). ``He caught me sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost put him to sleep that round and by the end of four
rounds, Golota led by six points on the master card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
