<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MEDICARE22-COX     11-21 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changing HMOs pose problem
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Elinor and Howard C. Poff had heard about the
hassles people go through when their Medicare HMO pulls out, so
they were glad at first that PacifiCare Health Systems was staying
in Warren County. They had no idea their hassles would be worse
because PacifiCare didn't drop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard's not losing his insurance. He's just losing his
doctors,'' Elinor said.
</P>
<P>
   When PacifiCare decided to stop providing its HMO Jan. 1 to
4,000 Medicare beneficiaries in Montgomery and Clark counties, it
also disbanded the physician networks there. ``They said he was
going to have to go to Hamilton or Wilmington or Cincinnati with
all his problems,'' Elinor said. But the Poffs live in Franklin,
near the Montgomery County line, and Howard's glaucoma keeps him
from driving.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans will find themselves in predicaments like
Poff's on Jan. 1, with a Medicare HMO that no longer resembles the
one they joined but without the realistic option of returning to
Original Medicare and buying a supplemental ``Medi-gap'' policy to
fill the many holes in that coverage. Most won't be losing all
their doctors, like Poff, but the American Association of Health
Plans estimates nearly 60 percent of the 6.2 million Americans in
Medicare HMOs will have lower prescription drug benefits and 2.3
million will face increased monthly fees.
</P>
<P>
   The 300,000 whose HMOs are abandoning them at least are
guaranteed acceptance for a Medicare supplemental policy regardless
of health problems _ unless they're on Medicare for disabilities
before they're 65. The seniors are given disenrollment
certificates, as the Poffs and their lawyer are fighting to
receive. All the people in Montgomery and Clark counties had to do
was stay with PacifiCare through Dec. 31 and buy the supplement
before March 3.
</P>
<P>
   Howard needs that guaranteed acceptance. Elinor is healthy and
65, but Howard is 69 with high blood pressure, insulin-dependent
diabetes and past brushes with bladder cancer, a stroke and
vascular surgery. ``No one will take him if they don't have to,''
Elinor said. And no one except another HMO has to take him because
PacifiCare hasn't left his county of residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee a Med-supp policy for everyone who drops
their HMO,'' said Bette Weisberg, regional director of Medicare
HMOs for the U.S. Health Care Financing Administration. ``Can you
imagine how many that would be?''
</P>
<P>
   All three Dayton-centered Medicare HMOs will either raise fees,
reduce benefits or both as of Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare will still offer at least $1,000 in
prescription coverage in two of its three plans, but they cost $70
and $85 a month on top of the $45.50 basic Medicare premium all HMO
members must pay. UnitedHealthcare still charges no premium, but
its prescription benefit is down to $300 a year in Montgomery
County and zero in Clark. Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield dropped
its monthly fee from $39 to $29, but like Aetna and United, it will
charge higher co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not understand what they're giving up when they join
an HMO,'' said Diane Lardie, who directs Ohio's Universal Health
Care Action Network in Cleveland. Many of them gave up an
employer's Medi-gap policy that was better than anything they can
buy now even if they're healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, said Lardie, do people understand Medicare HMOs can change
their rules from year to year. PacifiCare didn't tell the Poffs
that might happen when Howard canceled his supplemental plan to
join Secure Horizons. ``It was a fantastic policy three or four
years ago,'' Elinor said. ``The doctors he dealt with were led to
believe that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry blames Congress for urging companies to
develop Medicare HMOs and then slashing the Medicare budget in
order to balance the federal budget in 1997. ``This program's
future is in jeopardy,'' said AAHP President Karen Ignagni.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA criticizes the HMOs' financial management, citing studies
that show they are still overpaid and noting it will pay them an
average of 5 percent more next year for each Medicare HMO member.
</P>
<P>
   The AAHP is no more comforted by that claim than the apocryphal
statistic that someone drowned in a river with an average depth of
3 feet. It says nearly half the HMO beneficiaries live in counties
where the reimbursement rate will rise by no more than 2 percent,
while pharmaceutical expenses are going up by 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Mutual of Ohio's recent decisions reflect the industry's
trepidation with Medicare. It was authorized to open an HMO in
Cleveland-area counties, but it decided instead to bypass HCFA and
create a discount prescription drug plan, targeted largely to
Medicare beneficiaries without that coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Where HMOs aren't dropping out of counties, hospitals often are
dropping the Medicare HMOs' contracts. ``Cincinnati is undergoing
some very significant changes,'' said Bruce A. Turner, Aetna's
Southwest Ohio general manager. ``We don't get enough from HCFA and
we can't pass enough along to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Aetna is committed to every county of its unprofitable
Medicare HMO for another year because of sentiment in Washington to
reverse at least some of the 1997 cuts
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think everybody would say if something doesn't happen
for year 2001, there are going to have to be dramatic changes in
(fees) and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shortcoming of the Medicare system is that HCFA gives
HMOs less money to cover residents of suburban and rural counties
than those in urban counties. That ``fairness gap,'' as the AAHP
calls it, averages about 13 percent in counties neighboring
Montgomery County and is the reason most Medicare HMO withdrawals
are from outlying counties.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem's response this year was to reduce the rates it pays
physicians and other providers by the same percentages. United
adjusted by offering fewer benefits in outlying counties.
</P>
<P>
   After HMOs canceled their Medicare coverage for more than
400,000 people last January, a recent Kaiser Family Foundation
report said more than one-third suffered declines in benefits,
nearly 40 percent paid higher premiums and more than 20 percent had
to find new doctors. Those hurt most by the withdrawals were
minorities, the under-65 disabled and, as the Poffs would have
guessed, the poorest and the sickest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, 'At your age, you should have this and this and
this,''' Elinor said. ``Well, sure, at one time we did. We had
savings and mutual funds and stocks. But when you're faced with
retirement and medical problems, you have to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the comment, if I'm going to have to be a bag lady, I'm
going to have to move to a warmer climate. It's just too cold here
under the bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
