<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FOREIGN _ FLORENCE, Italy _ When he journeys on Tuesday
to Kosovo, President Clinton will be highlighting one of the
riskiest and most troublesome ventures of his presidency. In
Kosovo, as in neighboring Bosnia, Clinton has sent Americans into
combat, committed troops to a long-term peacekeeping operation, and
spent billions of U.S. taxpayers' dollars to end Europe's bloodiest
conflicts since World War II. His quest to bring peace to the
Balkans, though, is but one of a half dozen loose foreign policy
strings Clinton is scrambling to tie together in his remaining year
in office. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: President Clinton is scheduled to arrive in Sofia,
Bulgaria at about 11 p.m. EST Sunday. The dateline should be
changed to reflect his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International/Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PROTEST _ COLUMBUS, Ga. _ Organizers of the protest
against the School of the Americas are expecting 10,000 people here
for today's ritual, ``crossing the line'' onto the base. (Whitt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Elinor and Howard C. Poff had heard
about the hassles people go through when their Medicare HMO pulls
out, so they were glad at first that PacifiCare Health Systems was
staying in Warren County. They had no idea their hassles would be
worse because PacifiCare didn't drop them. ``Howard's not losing
his insurance. He's just losing his doctors,'' Elinor said. When
PacifiCare decided to stop providing its HMO Jan. 1 to 4,000
Medicare beneficiaries in Montgomery and Clark counties, it also
disbanded the physician networks there. ``They said he was going to
have to go to Hamilton or Wilmington or Cincinnati with all his
problems,'' Elinor said. But the Poffs live in Franklin, near the
Montgomery County line, and Howard's glaucoma keeps him from
driving. Millions of Americans will find themselves in predicaments
like Poff's on Jan. 1, with a Medicare HMO that no longer resembles
the one they joined but without the realistic option of returning
to Original Medicare and buying a supplemental ``Medi-gap'' policy
to fill the many holes in that coverage. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA-DEBATE _ Coverage of the GOP debate at Arizona State
University. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
