<P>
   There is a determination, White House officials say, to try to
lock in what progress has been made so far, before Clinton's
foreign policy operation turns back into a pumpkin in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous amount that we can do over this period,''
said White House National Security Advisor Samuel R. ``Sandy''
Berger. ``Fourteen months is a hell of a long time, particularly
when you're not running for re-election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's foreign policy to-do list includes peacemaking efforts
in the Middle East, Northern Ireland and Cyprus. Add to that the
attempt to expand and strengthen the global trading order.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, moreover, plays out against the even bigger job of
helping to shepherd Russia and China through the immensely
difficult, if quite different, economic, social and political
transitions both of those countries face.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is under no illusion that such work can be completed
before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``In foreign policy,'' said White House spokesman David Leavy,
``it's never done.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, having devoted enormous resources in each of these
areas, Clinton has generated the kind of momentum that has the
potential to lead to achievements.
</P>
<P>
   And, with his prospects for large-scale domestic initiatives in
the months ahead largely compromised by the politics of an election
year, some analysts say foreign policy may hold out the greatest
opportunities for burnishing the Clinton legacy before he leaves
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very impressive in his mediation in Ireland and the
Middle East,'' said historian James MacGregor Burns, author of
``Dead Center: Clinton-Gore leadership and the perils of
moderation,'' a new book examining Clinton's presidency. ``But he
probably needs a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get none soon in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic of analysts concede that Balkans
recovery will take years, if not decades. NATO peacekeepers _
31,000 now, 6,300 of them American _ will remain to keep the peace
as far as anyone can see, and stitching together the economic and
political underpinnings of true Balkans integration with the rest
of Europe could well take a generation.
</P>
<P>
   That point was underscored during Clinton's 24-hour visit to
Greece this weekend, where anti-American protests reached a
crescendo of violence when an estimated 10,000 demonstrators had to
be stopped by police in riot gear using tear gas. But many
demonstrators hurled firebombs and rocks, smashing windows, burning
out shops and banks and wreaking havoc in the heart of downtown
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was aimed against U.S. policy in Kosovo and Bosnia
and the American-led bombing of Yugoslavia, a traditional Orthodox
Christian ally of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China are long-term challenges where progress is
measured, again, in years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-China relations, still strained by differences over Taiwan
and charges of Chinese spying against U.S. nuclear facilities,
appear to be bobbing back from their spring-time ebb, when U.S.
bombers inadvertently destroyed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   White House trade envoy Charlene Barshefsky struck a landmark
deal with her Chinese counterparts last week in Beijing that opens
the way for China's admission to the World Trade Organization, a
goal Clinton has been working on since he took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russia relations, though, have plumbed a new low.
Washington and Moscow are far apart on four key issues: nuclear
arms control; Russia's war in Chechnya; the quest for control of
Caspian oil; and rampant crime and corruption that threatens the
economic transition at the heart of Russia's perilous turn from
Communism to free-market democracy.
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections in Russia next month, and
presidential elections next June, few analysts believe there can be
big movements in Russia over these or other issues between now and
the time Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to grind it out,'' Leavy said, ``and have the
long-term vision that Russia's transition is probably the single
most important foreign policy challenge long term.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the global trading order won't be built in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes for advances in the negotiating round set to begin
in Seattle Nov. 30 for the WTO, the Geneva-based group that sets
the rules and regulations for global commerce. That round is likely
to take three years to conclude, however, long after Clinton has
become a private citizen again.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has real expectations, though, for a resilient
breakthrough on Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, his special envoy for Northern Ireland issues,
former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell, made real progress in brokering a
way forward for Republicans _ Catholics who favor breaking away
from the United Kingdom and becoming part of Ireland proper; and
Unionists _ Protestants who wish to remain a part of the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Far from a final agreement, Mitchell's accord at least maps out
a way ahead on steps toward autonomy for Northern Ireland's
Catholics as called for in the Good Friday peace agreement both
sides signed, with Mitchell's help, a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has devoted time, off and on, to the 25-year-old
Greek-Turkish dispute on Cyprus. While it's been a source of
enormous frustration to him, aides concede, Clinton was heartened
by the agreement last week by both parties to meet for negotiations
beginning Dec. 3 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest foreign policy prize yet within Clinton's
reach is a comprehensive accord on the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat have both committed to laying out an agenda
for negotiations by February, and to completing those talks by
October.
</P>
<P>
   Snags in the process arose as recently as last week, when a
dispute stalled the process of Israeli withdrawals from portions of
the occupied West Bank territory.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the most difficult issues _ the question of
Palestinian statehood and the future of Jerusalem _ remain to be
discussed. Those are expected to be negotiated in the tough months
sure to follow whatever agenda is agreed upon in February.
</P>
<P>
   Berger is convinced, though, that Barak and Arafat both see the
Clinton presidency as offering their best chance for peace.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years and dozens of summit talks on the issue,
Clinton and his foreign policy team are deeply steeped in the
issues and complications with every possible step forward.
</P>
<P>
   And he knows, Berger said, and cares about, the personalities
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president knows Arafat and Barak better than Arafat and
Barak know each other,'' Berger said. ``He can help explain Arafat
to Barak and explain Barak to Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
