<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOREIGN-1122-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS PRESIDENCY WINDS DOWN, CLINTON FOCUSING ON TYING UP LOOSE
FOREIGN POLICY STRINGS
 &HT;    (625&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Italy _ When he journeys on Tuesday to Kosovo,
President Clinton will be highlighting one of the riskiest and most
troublesome ventures of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, as in neighboring Bosnia, Clinton has sent Americans
into combat, committed troops to a long-term peacekeeping
operation, and spent billions of U.S. taxpayers' dollars to end
Europe's bloodiest conflicts since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The sort of genuine reconciliation needed to knit the region
back together, however, remains elusive at best, and Clinton has
his work cut out for him in trying to shore up hard-won gains there
before the forces of conflict can tear them asunder.
</P>
<P>
   His quest to bring peace to the Balkans, though, is but one of a
half dozen loose foreign policy strings Clinton is scrambling to
tie together in his remaining year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Amid talk of a lame duck presidency on the domestic front,
Clinton is geared for an aggressive push to wrap up unfinished
business in a foreign affairs portfolio his administration has put
together over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   There is a determination, White House officials say, to try to
lock in what progress has been made so far, before Clinton's
foreign policy operation turns back into a pumpkin in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous amount that we can do over this period,''
said White House National Security Advisor Samuel R. ``Sandy''
Berger. ``Fourteen months is a hell of a long time, particularly
when you're not running for re-election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's foreign policy to-do list includes peacemaking efforts
in the Middle East, Northern Ireland and Cyprus. Add to that the
attempt to expand and strengthen the global trading order.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, moreover, plays out against the even bigger job of
helping to shepherd Russia and China through the immensely
difficult, if quite different, economic, social and political
transitions both of those countries face.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is under no illusion that such work can be completed
before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``In foreign policy,'' said White House spokesman David Leavy,
``it's never done.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, having devoted enormous resources in each of these
areas, Clinton has generated the kind of momentum that has the
potential to lead to achievements.
</P>
<P>
   And, with his prospects for large-scale domestic initiatives in
the months ahead largely compromised by the politics of an election
year, some analysts say foreign policy may hold out the greatest
opportunities for burnishing the Clinton legacy before he leaves
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very impressive in his mediation in Ireland and the
Middle East,'' said historian James MacGregor Burns, author of
``Dead Center: Clinton-Gore leadership and the perils of
moderation,'' a new book examining Clinton's presidency. ``But he
probably needs a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get none soon in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic of analysts concede that Balkans
recovery will take years, if not decades. NATO peacekeepers _
31,000 now, 6,300 of them American _ will remain to keep the peace
as far as anyone can see, and stitching together the economic and
political underpinnings of true Balkans integration with the rest
of Europe could well take a generation.
</P>
<P>
   That point was underscored during Clinton's 24-hour visit to
Greece this weekend, where anti-American protests reached a
crescendo of violence when an estimated 10,000 demonstrators had to
be stopped by police in riot gear using tear gas. But many
demonstrators hurled firebombs and rocks, smashing windows, burning
out shops and banks and wreaking havoc in the heart of downtown
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was aimed against U.S. policy in Kosovo and Bosnia
and the American-led bombing of Yugoslavia, a traditional Orthodox
Christian ally of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China are long-term challenges where progress is
measured, again, in years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-China relations, still strained by differences over Taiwan
and charges of Chinese spying against U.S. nuclear facilities,
appear to be bobbing back from their spring-time ebb, when U.S.
bombers inadvertently destroyed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   White House trade envoy Charlene Barshefsky struck a landmark
deal with her Chinese counterparts last week in Beijing that opens
the way for China's admission to the World Trade Organization, a
goal Clinton has been working on since he took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russia relations, though, have plumbed a new low.
