<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Nov. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHAOS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Five months after NATO
forces moved in to take control of Kosovo, there is little
electricity and an inconstant water supply, the streets are full of
garbage, traffic is in chaos without working stop lights or police
direction, few cars have license plates, no one has new identity
papers, and the Serb and Gypsy minorities continue to be harassed
and attacked. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Guedermes, Russia) _ Trying to quell criticism
of their grinding military offensive in Chechnya, Russian officials
take journalists on a tour of Chechnya's second largest city. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPACECRAFT (Beijing) _ China announced its first
successful launching and recovery of an unmanned spacecraft on
Sunday, an important step toward their goal of putting humans in
space. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-MISCONDUCT (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ Almost everywhere
Brazilians turn these days, one parliamentary commission or another
seems to be investigating official misconduct. What's more, many of
these commissions are actually yielding results. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-COLDWAR-MUSEUM (Prague, Czech Republic) _ The nation puts
together a living communist museum, so that the younger generation
can learn what life was like during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF-GATES-GIFT _ An American support group for UNICEF
announced Sunday that it has received its largest donation ever, a
grant of $26 million from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation
earmarked for the elimination of tetanus among babies and their
mothers in the poorest nations. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL (Columbus, Ga.) _ At the School of the
Americas, where the Army trains Latin American officers, the Cold
War never ended. In a campus-like setting at Ft. Benning, officers
learn about military tactics, while outside, opponents protest
American military's involvement in Central and South America. Now,
the Army plans to restructure the school to put less emphasis on
things military, but opponents want it closed. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDWATCHER-BLUES (Kiptopeke, Va.) _ That annoying species of
birdwatcher that simply is interested in ticking off birds on a
list. This is where speed counts more than appreciation of birds.
By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   TALKSHOW-PRIEST (Miami) _ A talk show on the Telemundo
Spanish-language network delves into domestic violence, sex
addiction and other issues common to daytime programming. But
``Padre Alberto'' is different in a big way. The host of the
program is a Roman Catholic priest. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENT-WOMEN (Boston) _ Among Concord residents arrested for
domestic assault this year, nearly 39 percent were women. In
Boulder County, Colo., one-quarter of defendants charged in
domestic violence cases through September were women. In Vermont,
similarly, nearly one-quarter of domestic assault arrests this year
have been of women. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TV-SUNDAY (Washington) _ George W. Bush appears on ``Meet
the Press'' to talk about foreign policy. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CLINTON _ In a couple of weeks, when staffers at the Gore
headquarters look out their windows, they'll be treated to a
billboard ad showing their candidate embracing Bill Clinton, with a
quotation of Gore's proclaiming his boss as one of the finest
presidents in our history. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RSI-INJURIES (Washington) _ A look a repetitive-stress injuries,
one of the biggest sources of occupational illness and injury. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-BLIND-TV (Washington) _ The FCC is taking the first steps
toward requiring television to carry narrative descriptions of the
action in TV shows, so that blind people can enjoy TV dramas.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-PROFILE (Washington) _ A profile of Rep. Patrick J.
Kennedy, the Democrat from Rhode Island. By Robin Toner. (With a
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN _ Details to come. By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
