<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, Nov.
22:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   APTED-FILMS (Undated) _ Two highly dissimilar films mark a busy
week for film director Michael Apted. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ Scott Turow is the latest in the
Writers-on-Writing series,
</P>
<P>
   WILDER-ESTATE (Undated) _ The last wishes of Laura Ingalls
Wilder are at the heart of a simmering federal court battle, with a
dilapidated little library in the Ozark Mountains claiming that it
has been deprived of riches from the literary estate of the hugely
popular children's author who wrote the ``Little House'' book
series. By Lynda Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   DARKNESS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews ``I
Remain in Darkness,'' by Anne Ernau.
</P>
<P>
   TOGETHER-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews
``Putting It Together'' at the Barrymore Theater.
</P>
<P>
   TV-APOCALYPSE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Walter Goodman reviews
``Frontline: Apocalypse!'' on PBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-RDP (Undated) _ Latest developments concerning
Microsoft and its legal battles. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN-VODAPHONE-ASSESS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Analysis: In
an interview, Mannesmann's chief executive, Klaus Esser, describes
his strategy for continuing to resist the hostile takeover efforts
of Vodaphone and gives his version of how present events came to
pass. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-POLITICS (Washington) _ When it comes to high-tech,
Republicans and Democrats alike have been falling all over
themselves to try to prove that they are the party most heeding the
call to keep e-commerce booming by keeping government's hands off.
But a close look at legislation pending or passed over the last
year shows that Congress and government have done anything but keep
their hands off the Internet. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-PRICING (Undated) _ E-commerce companies have enough
to worry about when it comes to competitive pricing, as Internet
shoppers can visit price-comparison sites like mySimon and
DealTime.com to search for savings. Now, shoppers do not even have
to click away to another site to find better prices. (The
E-Commerce Column.) By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-MUSIC-MARKETING (Undated) _ Last spring, when the record
industry and computer groups vowed to mount a crash effort to adopt
a technical standard for digitally distributed music, the point was
to get something in place in time for Christmas sales of
digital-music hardware. Guess what? They've missed the deadline. By
Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-CABLE-HOOKUP (Washington) _ Some 18 months after the
issue arose, digital TV makers and the cable industry believe
they've figured out a way to connect the new sets to cable boxes _
almost. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PREPARATIONS (Undated) _ The federal government should get a
respectable report card, with plenty of A's, when the House
subcommittee tracking Year 2000 preparations issues what it calls
its final grades. But one reason things look so rosy is that the
subcommittee has decided not to issue grades for more than 40 vital
government programs, including Medicaid and Medicare. By Barnaby J.
Feder.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A small Internet company is
hoping that the adage about tall oaks growing from little acorns
also applies to cyberspace, as it seeks big results from turning
perhaps the tiniest place on a computer screen into advertising. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-PRICE-HIKE (Undated) _ Following the trend set by the
Coca-Cola Co. that was revealed earlier this month, Pepsico plans
to raise the price it charges its bottlers for concentrate by
nearly 7 percent next year. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Finally, the Internet's growing lack
of credibility among consumers is becoming a cause celebre. Just
last week, two organizations _ one grass roots, the other
representing industry _ announced their intentions to bring some
balance and intellectual rigor to a debate that has been almost
completely lopsided toward unfettered growth at any cost. The
Digital Commerce Column. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-WRITERS-MEDIA (Indianapolis) _ Suddenly, Vince Russo
and Ed Ferraro have become two of the most important people in
television. They are the scriptwriters and directors of
professional wrestling shows. Their celebrity is a sign of how
wrestling, in all its boisterous, adolescent, violent,
blood-stained, sweat-spattered glory, is changing television. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
