<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DARKNESS-BOOK-REVIEW-     11-21 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARKNESS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I REMAIN IN DARKNESS': WHEN A PARENT BECOMES A CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Collectors of the slender, restrained and elliptical books of
Annie Ernaux, which have been critical and commercial successes in
France for a generation, will want to have ``I Remain in
Darkness,'' even though it is a less gripping work than her earlier
works. Ms. Ernaux, a professor of literature who lives outside
Paris, has created something of a genre: the emotionally
minimalist, stylistically uninflected chronicles of a
hypersensitive middle-aged woman examining her own life and those
of her parents. Her work represents a severely pared-down
Proustianism, a testament to the persistent, haunting and
melancholy quality of memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Remain in Darkness,'' capably translated Tanya Leslie (who
has translated six of this author's earlier books), is a collection
of notes that Ms. Ernaux made during the two and a half years of
her mother's final illness. It is a sequel in a way to ``A Woman's
Story,'' an earlier memoir-novel that examined the subtly afflicted
relationship between the author and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   This new book, like Ms. Ernaux's other works, displays an almost
brutal conciseness, an absence of artifice and dramatization as it
relates in brief, narrowly factual fragments her mother's final
years. ``She just sits there on a chair in the living room,'' is
the opening sentence, dated December 1983. ``Staring straight
ahead, her features frozen, sagging. Her mouth not quite open but
gaping slightly, from a distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux sustains this naturalism to the end, interrupting
here and there with commentary on her main theme, which is that in
getting sick, becoming incontinent, losing her mind to what seems
to have been Alzheimer's disease, Ms. Ernaux's mother forced ``an
agonizing reversal of roles between mother and child.'' But, sad as
it is, the idea that an aging person reverts to a kind of childlike
dependency, leaving the former child in a state of guilty mastery
worried about her own inevitable death, is not a thundering
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux's uncompromising lucidity, her unwillingness to look
aside, to prettify or to sentimentalize, are all components of a
striking sensibility. And yet sometimes a rigorous sort of
antisentimentalism becomes a sort of sentimentalism itself. It is
not that one doubts the sincerity of Ms. Ernaux's pain but that her
intentional understatement, the repetition of images without
narrative explanation, becomes itself mannered, solipsistic. The
special quality of her writing is that it leads us in its very
suggestive spareness to a deeper sense of the common poignancy. But
this new book is so thin and undeveloped as to lack the quiet
impact of her others.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux tells us the basics in a short forward, before she
sets down the notes she took as she cared for her mother in her
final years. She tells us that her mother began losing her memory
two years after a car accident from which she seemed otherwise to
have recovered. For a while she lived in a residence for the
elderly, but she was unable to take care of herself there and moved
in with Ms. Ernaux and her two teen-age sons. When that arrangement
proved unworkable, Ms. Ernaux's mother went to the hospital for a
couple of months and then was put into a private nursing home where
she stayed until her death in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   This book reproduces the notes that Ms. Ernaux took during her
mother's years in the nursing home. They are not, she warns us,
``the objective chronicle of a patient's stay in the long-term
geriatric ward,'' but should be read ``merely as vestiges of
pain.'' The recurrent themes, expressed as always in laconic
phrases, are guilt, fear of mortality and the underlying
animosities that make themselves felt as mother and daughter play
out the eternal reversal of roles: ``I clipped her fingernails; she
moaned, despite the fact that I always take great care not to hurt
her. I can feel the sadistic streak in me, echoing her behavior
toward me a long time ago. She still loathes me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux faithfully records her visual impressions, her
sadness, her disgust, the ``foul stench'' of urine and feces, the
wrenchingly comic aphasia of the senile. She sees the woman who
shares the room with her mother resting one hand on her belly, and
Ms. Ernaux remarks, ``It's beyond sadness.'' She bends forward at
one point to check her mother's wheelchair. ``She leans over and
kisses my hair. How can I survive that kiss, such love, my mother,
my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux is inconsolable when, finally, her mother dies. Her
guilt overpowers her, for having put her in the home in the first
place, for having failed to stop her pain, for having been
inadequate in the face of the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   These larger themes, it should be added, are extrapolations from
the wisps of prose that Ms. Ernaux set down in her notes at the
time. She does not interpret or explain, even when she makes some
epigrammatic statement that could use some explanation. ``The
maternal instinct,'' she writes, after reading a newspaper article
on motherhood and infertility, ``is tantamount to a death wish.''
That is certainly a suggestive remark, but Ms. Ernaux's refusal to
explain or annotate it is an example of the extreme minimalism that
she has chosen as her literary principle.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for a line like ``She still loathes me.''
It is not that one wants conventional explanations. The lack of
convention in Ms. Ernaux's shadowed writing is perhaps its chief
virtue. But in the case of this book, something more than that mere
statement would enrich the text without robbing it of the power of
its simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ernaux turns daily life, with its colossal, invisible
struggles, into a kind of epic. She is one of those writers who
seem so unspectacular you feel that anybody could do what she does,
if only they took the time and made the effort. In truth, there is
more genius involved in the recreation of the world in a drop of
water than one might think. This book certainly has flashes of that
genius even as it leaves one breathing a bit shallowly, wishing for
just a bit more air.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   I REMAIN IN DARKNESS
</P>
<P>
   By Annie Ernaux
</P>
<P>
   94 pages. Seven Stories. $18.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
