<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-POLITICS-A     11-21 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-POLITICS-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MAKES AN EASY TARGET FOR LOBBYISTS AND LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to cyberspace, the mantra of
politicians vying for the title of most e-friendly, Republicans and
Democrats alike, has been ``Hands off and go slow.'' Yet lawmakers
have already passed a laundry list of bills that leave the federal
government's fingerprints all over the Internet, and more are in
the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts include inventing rules against the peddling of
Internet addresses, granting legal standing for digital contracts,
proposing bans on the Internet programming known as Webcasts,
prohibiting online gambling and regulating ``spam,'' the junk mail
of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just a partial list of e-era legislation that this
Congress has passed or is considering.
</P>
<P>
   Some are the products of politicians seeking a hot issue. But
others are being promoted by the same companies that originally
insisted on self-regulation or by traditional lobbying powerhouses
and special interest groups taking advantage of Internet fever to
promote laws that protect their niches.
</P>
<P>
   The business groups backing the growing list of bills defend
them as necessary rules of the road for electronic commerce.
Watchdogs, however, see a disturbing anticonsumer trend in much of
the legislation that could have long-term negative effects _ not
only on Internet users but on the very companies that are now
scurrying for new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, digital laissez-faire seems to be applied
arbitrarily. While laws to protect business interests like
intellectual property and digital contracts have been on the fast
track, proposals to lay out basic protections for consumer privacy
online have been pushed aside as unnecessary and contrary to the
need to keep cyberspace unencumbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I characterize it as short-term-advantage thinking with
long-term implications,'' said Jerry Berman of the Center for
Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit group in Washington that aims
to work with industry to establish responsible Internet policy.
``My view is that the Internet is going to get hurt, consumers are
going to get hurt, and since all things come around, different
industry parts of the Internet are going to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Lane, who handles e-commerce affairs for the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, and Harris Miller, executive director of the
Information Technology Association of America, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain rules of the road that we need legislation
to establish,'' Lane said. ``And the rules of the road that are
being created are an incredible empowerment tool for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   And Miller argues that rules governing things like privacy are
not necessary because Internet companies know that their customers
_ with ``just one click of a mouse'' _ will move from a Web site
they do not trust to one that offers them basic consumer
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Berman says that the trend has moved away from true
self-regulation to ``leave it alone _ except for this, except for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company says, `Except for this,''' he said. ``And maybe
that exception makes sense, but it should only be done after
careful scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Berman said, after watchdog and industry groups united
to fight the Communications Decency Act as a form of
unconstitutional censorship, Internet business associations set up
the Internet caucus to educate Congress about the complicated
issues presented by the global network and the need to legislate
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what has happened is a number of these issues have not
gone through the process,'' he said. ``And I am unhappy and
disappointed that regardless of what side the different industry
players are on, they are moving their agendas without this kind of
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one key Internet bill to outlaw so-called cybersquatting
_ the ransoming of .com, .net and .org Internet addresses using
famous names or trademarks _ was worked out largely in closed
meetings and passed last week as an attachment to the omnibus
spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the measure argue that it will give trademark holders
unprecedented rights to Web names at the expense of individuals and
small businesses and that it could have a chilling effect on free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   It could also threaten the authority and credibility of Internet
Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, or ICANN, a still tenuous and
experimental oversight board chosen by the Clinton administration
last year to oversee the distribution of Internet addresses, known
as domains.
</P>
<P>
   ICANN recently established its own rules on cybersquatting, but
the powerful Motion Picture Association of America and other
trademark groups, unsatisfied with the rules, pushed for stronger
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased willingness by lawmakers to put their
names on anything touted as friendly to e-commerce, Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., who championed the first comprehensive
Internet deregulation bill, the Internet Tax Freedom Act, said most
of the Internet legislation pending in the 106th Congress was
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government simply doesn't have the answer at the moment,'' Cox
said, noting that evolving technology could eliminate the need for
rules over domain name disputes and problems like spam.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not to say there is not a distinction between good and
bad laws,'' he said. ``But by and large, as a policy matter,
regulation of the Internet should be put on hold because the
subject of the regulation itself is not yet settled.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But as technology companies increasingly make their presence
felt in Washington, the trend is not likely to go away.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, one of the companies most vocal in calling for a
hands-off approach to the Internet, is pushing legislation that
would force cable companies to open their high-speed Internet lines
to competition. The auction site eBay is pushing a database
protection bill opposed by the rest of the high-technology pack,
which fears that it could limit access to Internet content.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the increasing dissension among high-technology
companies, lobbies like the banking and insurance association are
pushing their own agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Such an alliance earlier this month turned a bipartisan
compromise for giving digital signatures the legal weight of their
ink-and-paper counterparts into a broader law that would eliminate
many record-keeping and consumer notification laws. In the end,
House Democrats who had supported the administration's push for the
narrower bill voted for the broader measure anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was very alarming and pretty surprising,'' said
Margot Saunders, managing attorney for the National Consumer Law
Center. ``Here we had a debate on the House floor for four hours
where the leaders were saying to their colleagues that this bill
hurts all Americans, it does not help electronic commerce. Yet you
had this huge block of middle-of-the-road Democrats completely
ignore what their own leadership was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly a matter,'' she added, ``of everybody being
scared to death to vote against the high-tech industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
