<SLUG> BC-TV-APOCALYPSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`APOCALYPSE!': SO FAR, IT JUST KEEPS ON ENDING AND ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cracked-looking fellow in a sandwich board that announces,
``The End Is Nigh!,'' has served cartoonists down the decades, but
for believers over many centuries the message has been no joke.
With the millennium upon us and a million pilgrims expected in
Jerusalem, once again expectations of Armageddon are stirring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apocalypse!,'' Monday night's absorbing two-hour edition of
``Frontline,'' offers a 2,000-year history of apocalyptic visions,
beginning with the final book of the New Testament, the Book of
Revelation, with its powerful images of a cosmic battle between
good and evil, heaven and hell, eternal damnation and an ascent to
Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Biblical scholars, abetted by reproductions of the nightmarish
imaginings of religious artists, trace the enduring belief in an
end to things to the Babylonian conquest and destruction of
Jerusalem in 586 B.C. During the long exile of the Jewish people,
the Hebrew prophets, influenced by other conquerors, from the
Persians to Alexander the Great to the Romans, contributed to an
apocalyptic literature that resonates in the preaching of Jesus and
John the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's scholars find the Bible sometimes allied with
history, sometimes colliding with it. The Book of Revelation,
written in about A.D. 95, is now interpreted as an attack on Rome
as the new Babylon. Rome responded, in celebration of its own
millennium, with vicious persecutions of Christians. Later,
Christian crusaders killed the Jews in their path. As Norman Cohn,
one of Monday night's droller guides, says: ``The official doctrine
was that all Jews must be converted to Christianity before the
Second Coming. But one way of settling this matter was to kill
them. Then there would be no unconverted Jews left.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th century Martin Luther would turn apocalyptic thought
against the church itself, condemning the pope as the anti-Christ.
One of his disciples, Thomas Munzer, applied the Bible's
description of a struggle between the forces of righteousness and
the forces of evil to the peasant revolts in Europe. The narrator
observes, ``Three hundred years later Karl Marx would transform the
apocalyptic ideas of Munzer into a secular ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Another expression of the prophesied transformation of society
reached America in the Pilgrims' visions of a New Jerusalem. John
Winthrop exhorted the colonists to build ``a city upon a hill,''
and their revolt against Britain was seen as a battle against ``the
beast of the apocalypse.''
</P>
<P>
   The prophetically inclined have periodically proclaimed that the
reign of Christ was at hand. In the middle ages an apocalyptic
thinker named Joachim deduced that from the birth of Jesus to the
end of time was 1,260 years, 80 years away. When the appointed day
finally arrived, he was dead; the world survived.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century William Miller founded a sizable movement
known as the Millerites or Adventists, based on the belief that
Christ's return was imminent. Crowds gathered on Oct. 22, 1844.
When nothing happened, one Millerite recalled, ``We wept and wept
until the day dawned.''
</P>
<P>
   Prophecies of apocalypse, though not as specific as those of
Joachim or Miller, remain current. The Rev. Jerry Falwell tells his
congregations that he believes in the premillennial coming of
Christ. David Koresh's followers apparently believed that they
would end up in Jerusalem. The program ends with the news that the
Israeli police are keeping a close eye on new groups that take a
literal view of the old Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   FRONTLINE: Apocalypse!
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday at 9 p.m. ET (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced and directed by William Cran and Ben
Loeterman; L. Michael White, editorial consultant. A co-production
with InVision Productions and Ben Loeterman Productions in
association with Channel Four Television. Michael Sullivan,
executive producer; David Fanning, senior executive producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
