<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: CUSTOM-DESIGNED MEDICATION; PAINLESS EARRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is it that one type of anti-depressant can lift one
patient's spirits while the same medication leaves his neighbor
jittery and sleepless? Or that a certain asthma drug might
instantly open up one child's breathing passageways, while bringing
no relief to the next wheezing patient who walks into the
pediatrician's office?
</P>
<P>
   The reason lies in our genetic differences. Just as they
determine the color of our eyes, the genes we inherit help
determine how we will react to certain drugs. And as researchers
hurtle toward decoding the entire human genome, companies are
beginning to try to use this information to help tailor drugs to
better fit genetic idiosyncrasies.
</P>
<P>
   Genaissance, a privately held company in New Haven, Conn.,
recently received a patent covering what it considers to be a
fundamental approach to collecting and organizing this information
to better design drugs for populations according to their different
genetic makeups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We break down subpopulations to figure out which people from a
genetic perspective can be predicted, in the case of a given drug,
to have the best response or to have side effects,'' said Gualberto
Ruano, the founder and chief executive officer of Genaissance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Genaissance says, it found that people with a
certain genetic variation do not respond to albuterol, a
bronchodilator drug used to treat asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``A third of the population, you can predict with certainty,
will not respond to this medication,'' Ruano said. ``From the
clinical perspective, it doesn't make sense to give these people
albuterol.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a consortium of 10 pharmaceutical companies
with a similar goal announced that it would develop a map of SNPs,
or single nucleotide polymorphisms, which are essentially small
variations in people's DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Genaissance also relies on SNPs, but organizes them into
haplotypes, which it likens to genetic bar codes that can be used
to identify connections between genetic variations and drug
response.
</P>
<P>
   Ruano said the two approaches were complementary. ``If you don't
know how a drug works, the SNPs approach works,'' he said. ``In our
case, we have a very good idea what the genes are, so we're
literally going to where the action is.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, to use a metaphor, ``Instead of having one big library, it's
like deciding to look only at poetry and collect books by Pablo
Neruda or Robert Frost,'' Ruano said.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of authors, of course, Genaissance is collecting
information on specific genes that have been linked with all manner
of diseases, such as arthritis and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next year, Genaissance says it plans to have
created anthologies, or collections of information, for 2,000 genes
in a wide variety of ethnic populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can harvest as many anthologies as there are people who
represent the planet _ as opposed to creating an entire library
from the genes of just two people off the street of San
Francisco,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While ultimately such technology is likely to be used in the
doctor's office to screen for the appropriateness of certain drugs,
initially it will be used by pharmaceutical companies testing new
drugs. The technology will help them weed out people likely to
develop side effects and identify patients genetically predisposed
to respond well to the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Genaissance received patent 5,972,614.
</P>
<P>
   An Earring Design That's Less Perilous
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Meridyth Mischel Webber, who lives in
Teaneck, N.J., ripped open her ear lobe when one of her earrings
became entangled in her comb. Ever since then, she has spent time
trying to invent an ``ouchless'' earring, and she has received her
third patent covering what she contends is the most important
improvement in earrings since clip-ons were introduced in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   From the front, Ms. Webber's earrings look like normal earrings
(albeit big normal earrings, because they cover the whole lobe).
But in the back, they feature a curved post that resembles an
upside-down coat hook. That post hooks inside the notch in the ear
that is just above the ear lobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My earrings don't pinch or clamp any area of the body,'' she
said. ``They are secure because that notch can hold anything. Plus
the bottom wraps around the back so it can use the lobe as an
anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webber's earrings are for sale at several stores in North
Jersey. She received patent 5,845,518.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
