<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL (Columbus, Ga.) _ At the School of the
Americas, where the Army trains Latin American officers, the Cold
War never ended. In a campus-like setting at Ft. Benning, officers
learn about military tactics, while outside, opponents protest
American military's involvement in Central and South America. Now,
the Army plans to restructure the school to put less emphasis on
things military, but opponents want it closed. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS (Princeville, N.C.) _ After one of the worst
floods in North Carolina's history, Princeville's more than 2,000
citizens, many of whom are direct descendants from the freed slaves
who founded the town, are struggling with choices that will
determine whether their historic town can ever exist again. But
unlike many other residents of North Carolina who are taking the
FEMA buyout offer, many in Princeville consider the offer a ``sell
out'' and are refusing to leave. By Emily Yellin. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   CENTRALPARK-TRANSFORM (New York) _ Two decades ago, Central Park
was a scary, trash-blown ruin that was Exhibit A for those who
claimed New York City was no longer a fit place to live. No more.
It has been replaced with a meticulously groomed park where bronze
preservation specialists each year polish and wax all 50 of the
park's statues. What is far less obvious is how this transformation
happened. Considering the park's location, a large haul of private
dollars helped. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
