<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TOGETHER-THEATER-REVI     11-21 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOGETHER-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PUTTING IT TOGETHER': A VEILED SPIRIT, A HEART UPON THE SLEEVE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: `lite' in 6th graf cq.) 
(nk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the years she ruled as the queen of television
variety shows, from 1967 to 1978, Carol Burnett was a warm spot in
the seas of medium cool. At a moment when comedy kept turning
darker and angrier, Ms. Burnett offered brilliant clowning without
bile, satire without a sneer. Few contemporary comedians have
commanded such undiluted good will, and even today this actress
can't appear on a stage or screen without inspiring an instant
flood of affection.
</P>
<P>
   Now all this warmth is being put to the cause of removing the
chill from the songs of Stephen Sondheim, a composer whose talents
are as intellectual as Ms. Burnett's are instinctive, in the
misconceived revue ``Putting It Together,'' which opened Sunday
night at the Ethel Barrymore Theater. And as experiments in
thermodynamics go, this one is a nonstarter. It's not that Ms.
Burnett, who became a star on Broadway four decades ago in ``Once
Upon a Mattress,'' doesn't have what it takes anymore to seduce a
live audience; she does, in spades.
</P>
<P>
   It's that her tools of seduction are the opposite of Sondheim's.
The composer of such benchmark musicals as ``Company,'' ``Follies''
and ``Sweeney Todd'' writes intricate, introspective melodies and
lyrics with a heart that is vital but also hidden and guarded. Ms.
Burnett has always worn  &UR; her  &LR; heart on the outside, and even at her
broadest and loudest, she reads as both friendly and vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting It Together,'' a reworking of the Sondheim evening
first seen at the Manhattan Theater Club in 1993 (starring Ms.
Burnett's friend Julie Andrews), asks her to be sharp and brittle.
Ms. Burnett can caricature brittleness deliciously, but actually
being brittle is a chore for her. It's like asking a luffa sponge
to function as a razor blade.
</P>
<P>
   While there are moments in the production, directed by Eric D.
Schaeffer, when the Burnett and Sondheim sensibilities coalesce in
shiver-making flashes, they are sadly infrequent. The whole tone of
the show, which strings together Sondheim songs to shape a loose
story of five urbanites at a cocktail party, is out of sync with
its own material. ``Putting It Together'' is perversely determined
to make something lite of the dark bard of the American musical.
</P>
<P>
   These intentions are made clear in the opening moments, which
find Bronson Pinchot, who plays a character called the Observer,
racing down an aisle of the Barrymore dressed as an usher.
Pinchot's mission is to disarm with blithe stand-up commentary
about Sondheim. One example: ``Deep down, even his friends are
afraid that he's going to be cerebral, difficult, complicated,
wordy. ... And at dinner, he is.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a gag reference to Ms. Burnett's being lost in a
taxi, having followed directions given her by Kathie Lee Gifford,
the perky television host who is to substitute for Ms. Burnett at
some performances. The mood is firmly established: This is going to
be an amiable, jokey evening in which audiences can get cozy with
people who show up in People.
</P>
<P>
   What follows sticks fairly close to the form of the Manhattan
Theater Club production, with a few substitutes in the lineup of
songs. Ms. Burnett and the estimable George Hearn portray a rich,
middle-aged and deeply disenchanted older couple; Ruthie Henshall
(the smashing London star, late of ``Chicago'') and John Barrowman
are the sexy, wave-making younger pair at the party. She has
predatory ambitions; he has no discernible character whatsoever.
Pinchot is he who watches.
</P>
<P>
   Singing numbers plucked from shows ranging from ``Merrily We
Roll Along'' to ``A Little Night Music,'' from ``Sunday in the Park
With George'' to the movie ``Dick Tracy,'' the five characters make
love and war with one another before arriving at a spurious finale
of cheerful reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   This is accomplished before Bob Crowley's neon-splashed,
multilevel designs (with theme-heralding projections by Wendall K.
Harrington), which may be meant to evoke the worldliness of William
Hamilton cartoons but feel more like the swinger's playground of a
set for the old ``Laugh-In'' series. The effect is at once cute and
distancing. And as the show proceeds, the performers often seem to
be disclaiming the material they deliver, as if to reassure us that
any hard feelings they assume are only pretend.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, each of them seems to have arrived from a different
show-business universe. Watching them onstage is like looking at a
supermarket tabloid cover in which pictures of different
celebrities have been combined to create the illusion that they
were photographed together. Ms. Henshall provides the same
razzle-dazzle intensity she brought to ``Chicago''; Barrowman
contributes a pretty voice and a pretty face, though little else.
</P>
<P>
   Pinchot, best known for the sitcom ``Perfect Strangers,'' is
winsomely puckish. Hearn, who was a memorable Sweeney Todd, is
gentle, grave and low-key. His reflective version of that fine
ballad of midlife angst, ``The Road You Didn't Take'' (from
``Follies''), comes closer to suggesting a song's original context
than any other number in the show, but he is largely eclipsed by
the avidness of those around him.
</P>
<P>
   The vulpine Ms. Henshall is, as always, compellingly watchable,
but all that Fosse-style legwork seems a bit out of place here.
There's no denying her star quality, and she stops the show with
the gold digger's anthem ``More'' (from ``Dick Tracy''), but her
hard-sell flair is wasted on what is a trifle of a song. When she
and Ms. Burnett square off as Clare Booth Luce-esque rivals in
``There's Always a Woman'' (from ``Anyone Can Whistle''), they are
so mismatched that it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely, in fact, does the presentation here bring out the
best in either the songs or the singers. It was a lousy idea to
have Pinchot, whose forte is light flippancy, to sing ``War,'' a
tense narrative of erotic conflict from ``Night Music,'' while Ms.
Henshall and Barrowman smilingly execute a sexual ballet. The pair
is also bizarrely given the duet ``Unworthy of Your Love,'' which
was strong stuff when sung by characters representing Squeaky
Fromme and John W. Hinckley Jr. in ``Assassins,'' but turns watery
out of context.
</P>
<P>
   The real raison d'etre of ``Putting It Together,'' however, is
Ms. Burnett. Her fans (and I am one of them) will find that she
remains an inspired master of rubber-faced mugging and goofy vocal
inflections. And she has one searing moment of emotional nakedness,
with a ``Ladies Who Lunch'' (from ``Company'') that finds the raw
loneliness at the song's core.
</P>
<P>
   She also pulls off the funniest variation on ``Not Getting
Married Today'' (from ``Company'') that I've ever heard, slowing
down the number's usual breakneck pace to give italicized,
cartoonish weight to every element of a reluctant bride's anxiety.
The moment is entirely Ms. Burnett's, however, not Sondheim's.
Indeed, the composer's full presence is oddly absent throughout
this evening devoted to his work.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING IT TOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   Music and lyrics by Stephen Sondheim; musical staging by Bob
Avian; directed by Eric D. Schaeffer; designed by Bob Crowley;
lighting by Howard Harrison; orchestrations by Jonathan Tunick;
sound by Andrew Bruce/Mark Menard; projections by Wendall K.
Harrington; musical director, Paul Raiman; Carol Burnett's costumes
by Bob Mackie; associate director/choreographer, Jodi Moccia;
general manager, Alan Wasser; executive producers, David Caddick
and Martin McCallum. Presented by Cameron Mackintosh, in
association with Mark Taper Forum, Gordon Davidson, artistic
director. At the Ethel Barrymore Theater, 243 West 47th Street,
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Carol Burnett (The Wife), George Hearn (the Husband), John
Barrowman (the Younger Man), Ruthie Henshall (the Younger Woman)
and Bronson Pinchot (the Observer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-PRICING-AR     11-21 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-PRICING-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING WEB USERS FIND THE LOWEST ONLINE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-commerce companies have enough to worry about when it comes to
competitive pricing, as Internet shoppers can visit
price-comparison sites like mySimon and DealTime.com to search for
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, shoppers do not even have to click away to another site to
find better prices. Several companies have developed a new breed of
so-called agents _ software tools that work with Web browser
software, offering shoppers better deals on whatever merchandise
they happen to be viewing on a Web page. For an off-line analogy,
imagine someone infiltrating the checkout line at OfficeMax and
telling people they can save money on the same products at Staples.
</P>
<P>
   Agent companies like ClickTheButton, DealPilot and R U Sure have
developed software that scans various shopping sites for price and
delivery data, then sorts it (most often by price). In some cases,
the agents also gather information about product availability,
shipping costs and the length of time it takes to receive the item.
</P>
<P>
   Once a user has downloaded software from one of these agent
services, though, the software is activated any time the Web
browser is open. Someone surfing the Web with ClickTheButton, for
instance, sees a bull's-eye icon in the corner of the screen. By
clicking on this icon while viewing a Web page about a particular
product, a price comparison page appears listing competitors'
prices for the item.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while a user was on an Amazon.com page featuring the
book ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets,'' a ClickTheButton
search yielded price information from 15 retailers. Six of them,
including Amazon, offered the book for about $9, plus $3 for
shipping. One site, 1Bookstreet.com, offered the book for $10.77,
with no charge for United Parcel Service ground shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Such results essentially mirror those of shopping comparison
sites, but there are two fundamental differences between the
browser-based services and the shopping comparison sites. First,
the browser-based agents typically monitor a shopper's habits,
thereby allowing the services to make relevant offers at the right
moment. Second, merchants do not have to pay to be included in at
least two of these services _ a significant departure from shopping
comparison sites, which generally charge merchants fees to be
listed in prime positions.
</P>
<P>
   And although one might expect merchants to mount a
counter-assault against technologies that effectively hijack their
sites, Internet retailers have reacted to them with a surprising
air of resignation. ``These things are both intriguing and a little
bit scary,'' said Michelle Rubin, director of affiliate marketing
for the music seller CDNow. ``I think they will become more
sophisticated in the future, to give consumers a fuller picture of
what's important at a store beyond prices. But right now it's a
very freewheeling, competitive environment out there, and it's just
hard to stop stuff like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curry, an Amazon spokesman, was even more sanguine. ``We're
comfortable with people making price comparisons, and qualitative
comparisons as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the current rate of consumer adoption, at least, Amazon
and its competitors may not have much to worry about.
ClickTheButton.com is among the oldest of the bunch, having rolled
out in March. It now has over 100,000 active users, Cheyenne
Ehrlich, the company's chief executive, said in an interview last
week. ``But we just started our marketing campaign this week,'' he
said, adding that the company's goal is to obtain 2 million users
by the end of next March.
</P>
<P>
   ClickTheButton scans information from 233 of the most visited
retailers in six categories: books, electronics, hardware and
software, movies, music and toys. Users download the software _ a
process that takes less than a minute on a 56-kilobit modem _ and
register with the company so it can monitor the user's shopping
habits.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich said the company made money from a few different
sources, including referral fees from some retailers that obtain
customers through ClickTheButton. Given the wealth of data the
company can collect about its users, ClickTheButton could
conceivably gorge itself at the trough of dot-com advertising, but
Ehrlich said it would abstain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take this data in aggregate and maybe tell Amazon where to
price their goods in order to get a certain percentage of people to
move from Barnes &AMP; Noble, but I don't want ads,'' he said.
``Nothing we do will let companies get back to users.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new company, Dash, has a somewhat different approach.
The company takes advantage of retailer affiliate programs, which
pay referral fees to sites that funnel sales their way. Dash
essentially serves as an intermediary: A software tool directs
shoppers to Dash's partner retailers, and Dash collects referral
fees whenever a purchase is made at one of its 100 or so partner
sites. Dash then passes those fees back to consumers with a monthly
check.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when someone is shopping for goods on the Gap.com,
a message will appear on the toolbar at the bottom of the browser
telling users that they can ``save 5 percent when you shop at
J.Crew instead.'' Users can then click directly to J.Crew's site
and shop as they would normally, knowing they eventually will get a
5 percent rebate check from Dash.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, if Gap signs up with Dash, J.Crew and other competitors
will not be permitted to display competing coupons when the user is
on Gap's site. At any time, however, users can click an icon on the
toolbar and view the savings available through competitors in the
Dash network.
</P>
<P>
   According to Daniel Kaufman, Dash's chief executive, the service
capitalizes on both the greed and the fears of merchants. ``The
greed factor is that any company loves the idea of advertising at a
competitor's checkout aisles,'' he said. ``The fear factor is that
if they don't work with us, their customers will see a competitor's
ads. In the end, fear and greed overcomes the negative effect of
paying a discount on every sale.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company earns referral fees from retailers in addition to
what it pays back to consumers, Kaufman said, and by allowing
companies to target users with specific offers. ``If I'm United
Airlines, I can target someone who flies to Orlando four times a
month, business class, on American,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman hastened to add that merchants ``never know who is
getting a message,'' since Dash is the conduit. As with most of the
other browser-based shopping comparison services, Dash posts a
lengthy privacy policy on its site. (Dash hired Jason Catlett, a
well-known privacy advocate, to develop its privacy policy.)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are mixed on the promise these technologies hold.
``Give them credit for the idea,'' said Melissa Bane, an e-commerce
analyst with Yankee Group. ``But the trick here is to get people to
download these things. That's still a real barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Orton, chief strategist for Cognitiative, a consulting firm,
was more skeptical. ``People go to a site for a reason, and to be
sold off of that in the middle of the experience is not a likely
scenario,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman of Dash is predictably optimistic that both consumers
and merchants will warm to this technology. ``This is perhaps the
best way for consumers to capture value when shopping,'' he said,
noting that the service has 20,000 users after just two weeks in
business. As for Dash's relationship with retailers, Kaufman said
partner merchants could enjoy sizable sales advantage over
competitors. ``So we're in a pretty serious love-fest right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
