<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES BIAS LAWSUIT AGAINST CNN 
EXECUTIVE EDITOR IS QUITTING TALK MAGAZINE 
LONGTIME EDITOR NAMED TO HEAD ST. MARTIN'S
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, CNN hired a veteran journalist, Art Browne, as a
senior editor in its New York office. What made the move somewhat
unusual for CNN was that Browne was 59 at the time, had been
unemployed for four years and suffered from a neurological
condition called essential tremor disorder, which caused his voice,
hands and head to shake.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen months later, Browne, after being told that his work had
been unsatisfactory, was fired. He sued CNN last year, contending
that he was dismissed because of his age and his disability.
</P>
<P>
   But last Tuesday, a federal judge in Manhattan dismissed the
suit before trial, saying that Browne had failed to prove
discrimination and that CNN should receive credit for hiring him in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would do disservice,'' wrote Judge John S. Martin Jr. of
federal District Court in Manhattan, ``to the goals that our
anti-discrimination laws are designed to foster if we did not give
substantial weight to the fact that CNN hired Browne with full
knowledge of his age and disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of evidence of discrimination, the judge added,
were he to allow the suit to proceed, ``other companies would, in
the future, be reluctant to follow CNN's example and hire someone
like Browne.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen S. Binetti, a lawyer for Browne, said he had no comment,
but she criticized the decision, saying, ``It's dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge ignored critical evidence that we believe mandated
the denial of'' CNN's motion to dismiss the case, she said, ``and
it's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person was in this business for four decades,'' she said,
``and I find it incomprehensible that as matter of law, a judge
would find that he could not do that particular relatively
low-level job when he had tremendous jobs in the business in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN described the job Browne took in October 1995 as one with
important responsibilities. Browne had had a long career in
television and radio, working as national editor of ABC News in New
York from 1977 to 1981 and later in television news operations in
New Haven, Chicago and Washington. CNN hired him as senior futures
editor, a job that involved planning beyond the day's news for
events throughout the Northeast, CNN said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   But his superiors became dissatisfied with his performance,
giving him warnings, and in one case, removing him from coverage of
the explosion of TWA Flight 800 after he was found to be ``an
impediment to coverage,'' Judge Martin noted in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster his discrimination case, Browne said in legal papers
that CNN had replaced him with a 26-year-old ``who had fewer years
on this planet than plaintiff had doing television news,'' that
almost all of CNN's employees in New York were under 40 and that
his superior made derogatory comments about his disability.
</P>
<P>
   But in rejecting various arguments by Browne that he was a
victim of discrimination, Martin said ``poor work performance is a
legitimate, nondiscriminatory reason to discharge an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   A CNN spokesman, David J. Bittler, would say only, ``We feel the
decision speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Benjamin Weiser
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor Is Quitting Talk Magazine
</P>
<P>
   Editors are leaving Talk magazine and its guiding light, Tina
Brown. First it was the managing editor, then it was a features
editor, and now it is David Kuhn, Ms. Brown's longtime deputy, who
followed her from Vanity Fair to The New Yorker and who has spent
almost a dozen years altogether under her editorial spell.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Kuhn resigned as vice president and executive editor
at Talk magazine. And he is headed for a place where editors also
tend to come and go with some dispatch: the media organization run
by Steven Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Senior staff members at Talk said that Kuhn had been actively
seeking a job outside Talk since September and that when Ms. Brown
hired Robert B. Wallace to be editorial director two weeks ago, a
position above Kuhn, his plans quickly firmed up.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn himself said Wallace's arrival did not prompt his
departure, saying instead that he had been offered an exciting new
opportunity: Kuhn will not join Brill's magazine, Brill's Content,
but instead will head Brill's new Web division, which Brill refuses
to discuss yet but which his magazine's staff members describe as a
commerce site to be introduced in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn said his expectations for Talk remained buoyant, despite
its decided lack of buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely proud of my contribution to Talk, and it was an
amazing launch for a magazine, and I was thrilled to be a part of
it,'' he said. ``Launches are launches, so to say that there was
never a bump would be ridiculous. But what I am going to do is an
altogether different life choice, and involves an area that has
been increasingly interesting to me over the last six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn also declined to discuss just what he was so excited about,
but did offer other clues: As part of his compensation package, he
said he will receive an equity stake in Brill's Internet venture.
``Basically I have a participation in this company that is really
thrilling to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Editor Named to Head St. Martin's
</P>
<P>
   Still recovering from the recall of its George W. Bush
biography, St. Martin's Press last week chose a longtime editor of
its literary list to replace the departed editor in chief, who fled
abruptly saying he was disgusted with the book.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's announced the appointment last week of George
Witte, 39, who got his start at the company, which is owned by
Verlagsgruppe Georg von Holtzbrinck, in 1985 as an editorial
assistant with a graduate degree in English from the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill. More recently, Witte had presided
over St. Martin's literary imprint, Picador USA, as publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see myself doing anything dramatically
different in changing the way that St. Martin's publishes and
acquires books,'' Witte said. ``It all starts with the books that
you buy and I want to be as accessible to the editors as I can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Those editors were naturally flustered when their previous boss,
Robert B. Wallace, resigned on Oct. 26 because he did not want to
be associated with books like ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and
the Making of an American President,'' which was published by the
company's independent imprint, Thomas Dunne Books. St. Martin's
canceled and recalled the book after learning that the author, J.H.
Hatfield, was a convicted felon linked to a car bombing attempt on
his boss. Two days later, Talk magazine announced that Wallace
would be its new editorial director.
</P>
<P>
   Witte takes a much milder view of the entire contretemps: ``I
think it would be very hard to avoid a situation like that. That's
one of those situation where you would be blindsided. We don't
ordinarily do a criminal check on our authors. You try to check
into people's background as best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Doreen Carvajal
</P>
</TEXT>
