<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APTED-FILMS-1100(TRIM     11-21 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APTED-FILMS-1100(TRIMS)-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL APTED: A VETERAN DIRECTOR, DELIGHTING IN OPPOSITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ There are odd juxtapositions in the career of any
filmmaker, particularly one who has been at it as long and
prolifically as Michael Apted. But it's hard to imagine an
alignment odder than the one that has encompassed Apted in the last
few days.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday ``42 Up,'' the latest installment in his popular
and highly regarded documentary series tracing the lives of more
than a dozen British men and woman in seven-year increments, opened
in the United States after a frustrating year during which Apted
searched and searched for a distributor. Two days later this
journeyman director, best known for finely wrought dramas often
featuring female protagonists, offered ``The World Is Not Enough'':
of all things, a James Bond movie, big and expensive and explosive,
full of stunts and action scenes and scantily clad women.
</P>
<P>
   The two don't seem to go together. It's like Abbott and Garbo.
And yet they must go together, or how else to explain Michael
Apted?
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been perfectly respectable, but this could
catapult me into a whole new category,'' said Apted, 58. If nothing
else, he said, if he has two successes at once, especially with
such disparate films, it might change the way some Hollywood power
brokers regard him. ``Can't make money, that Apted,'' he mimicked
with a sneer.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't saying that after the weekend. ``The World Is Not
Enough'' had an estimated weekend box office gross of $37.2
million. This not only put it in first place for the weekend (ahead
of Tim Burton's ``Sleepy Hollow'' with $30.5 million) but also made
it the highest opening ever for a James Bond film and the highest
opening for any movie ever released by MGM. Early box office
numbers for ``42 Up,'' which opened on only a handful of screens,
were not available, but the series has always done respectably in
big cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Apted said, ``could jump-start my movie career,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Apted is tall, slender, disarmingly frank and a bit patrician in
manner. George Plimpton could play him in the movie. The
Buckinghamshire accent has mellowed a bit, probably from 19 years
of living in Southern California. ``I came here to do `Coal Miner's
Daughter,' and I just stayed, actually,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His filmmaking career began in 1964 when, with the backing of
the BBC and Granada Television, he embarked on what he thought
would be a one-time documentary about British 7-year-olds. In ``7
Up'' he drew children from a variety of social classes, interviewed
them about their lives and their aspirations and then photographed
them playing together, their modes of play unconsciously commenting
on their dreams and their classes.
</P>
<P>
   He saw it as a political statement, a commentary on the British
class system, and he was stunned when viewers saw something more.
Seven years later he followed up with ``Seven Plus Seven,''
catching up with the same children, now teenagers. It was an
enormous success in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so slow to realize that it had an appeal outside of
England,'' he said. ``I didn't realize what I had. I thought I was
making a statement about class, but what I really had was a study
about life.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He returned with ``21 Up,'' but not until ``28 Up'' in 1985 did
he get widespread distribution in the United States. Each
successive film has been incrementally more popular, and the series
has grown and mellowed with its subjects, sometimes taking on
almost heartbreaking resonance. By now, his 7-year-olds have begun
to settle into middle age and confront their mortality.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What Apted hadn't realized when he made the first of the series,
he said, was that he would some day require the participation of
those being interviewed to continue it. He neglected to get them to
sign contracts. Even now there are none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I have to go back to them and ask them to take part
again,'' he said. ``I have to put on my used car salesman bit. You
see, they hold all the cards. I want them in it, and I really don't
care what I do to keep them in it. And I always know that if I do
something naughty, they're out of it. So I really do have to
behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the subjects grow through awkward adolescence to
adulthood, some prospering, some not; being able to cut back to
shots of them as children full of young dreams: it has been more
than just a filmmaker's exercise for Apted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I find that I know them all well, and they are like my
family, in a way,'' he said. ``As they are getting older, the
difference in age between us seems less and less important, and the
whole fear of mortality is creeping in. It's really a frightening
thought, what I will do when the first of them dies. It didn't used
to worry me before. But now I have to face it. I only hope I go
first.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Apted said he had kept up with the series, even in years when he
could have been making much more money directing something else,
largely because of the response it had received. He was having a
salad during a round of interviews at the Four Seasons Hotel in
Beverly Hills, promoting the Bond film. Several dozen journalists
had already questioned him that morning, he said, and every one of
them brought up the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says to me, `Why do you still do it?''' Apted said.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly isn't for the money; the amount that he makes on
the ``Up'' series is a fraction of what a director earns on a
big-budget project like a James Bond movie. It is something else
that drives him to push on with the ``Up'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it because every single person I've talked to today has
mentioned it,'' Apted said. ``It's amazing how much people bring it
up. They all say, `How it is going to end?' I tell them, I don't
know. I'll keep going as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Which made his most recent struggle to find an American
distributor for ``42 Up'' so frustrating and perplexing, he said.
(First Run Features eventually picked it up.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody turned it down,'' he said. ``I mean, everybody. I
couldn't understand it. These films always do about a million
dollars. Always. It's as close to a guarantee as you can get. And
the films don't need to be marketed, outside of a few newspaper
ads. They're review-driven. There is no negative cost, just
publicity and advertising, and it's a guaranteed million dollars,
but nobody was interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The films in the series have always had their premieres on
television in England, where ``42 Up'' was shown in the summer of
1998. ``They would say to me, `Oh, the marketplace is too
crowded,''' Apted said. ``Then I think they realized that that Bond
film was coming out, and it might do well to release them close
together. Which I hope it does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In between his seven-year reunions, Apted became one of the most
prolific and versatile directors in Hollywood, though his films
have had spotty box-office success.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, his career breaks into seven-year segments, too.
Between ``7 Up'' and ``Seven Plus Seven,'' he struggled to
establish himself, mostly doing television series in Britain.
Between ``Seven Plus Seven'' and ``21 Up,'' he became a respected
director in Britain, with films like ``Stardust'' (1974) and the
cult favorite ``Triple Echo'' (1972).
</P>
<P>
   Not until between ``21 Up'' and ``28 Up'' did he make the move
to Hollywood, where his first real success was ``Agatha,'' a 1979
drama starring Dustin Hoffman and Vanessa Redgrave (as Agatha
Christie). The same period saw ``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' which won
Sissy Spacek an Oscar in 1980, ``Continental Divide'' starring John
Belushi in 1981 and ``Gorky Park'' in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Then, between ``28 Up'' and ``35 Up'' came a series of uneven
efforts. Sigourney Weaver was an Oscar nominee for his ``Gorillas
in the Mist'' in 1988, and 1991's ``Class Action'' was well
received, but there was also ``Critical Condition,'' a critical and
box office dud in 1987. Between ``35 Up'' and ``42 Up'' he was
never quite able to match the critical successes of his earlier
work. There was ``Thunderheart'' in 1992, ``Nell'' in 1994 and
``Extreme Measures'' in 1996, among others. Then last year came the
call to tackle James Bond, the most endurable series in film
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Apted said. ``I think my agent
put my name up and they called back. I said to my agent: `Is this a
joke? Why would anyone like me be asked to do an action film?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, said the film's producers, Michael G. Wilson and
Barbara Broccoli, is that they wanted a director who could not only
choreograph big-screen stunts but also add dramatic weight to the
story. Pierce Brosnan, in his third outing as Ian Fleming's suave
superspy, particularly felt that the most recent Bond movie,
``Tomorrow Never Dies,'' tilted too far in the direction of one big
action scene after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this one, what I think we all wanted and what I think we
got,'' Brosnan said, ``is a greater attention to story and
character.'' He gives Apted much of the credit for that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Apted said, that initial contact did come as a bit of a
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pierce was really ready to make the series his,''
Apted said. ``He wanted his stuff in it. He said to me: `I want
something to do. Give me something to play.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Brosnan was eager to take more advantage of some of the
supporting players the series had under contract. ``He said, `My
Lord, we have Judi Dench, one of the greatest actresses in England;
let's use her,''' Apted said. Plus, the story line relied more
heavily on the female roles, and Apted had had some success
directing women. ``All of that made sense to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apted said he had never been a James Bond fan. His tastes as a
young man ran to Antonioni and Godard, not Terence Young (director
of the first two 007 films), he said. ``But I know the series'
place in England's cultural history,'' he said. ``I know that
what's being sold is a perception of what England is.''
</P>
<P>
   So all he had to do was reconcile himself to the necessities of
the genre _ ``the action, the babes, that's a given really, when
you get the job'' _ and try to figure out how to make huge and
involving action sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done action scenes before, but I'd never done anything
this huge scale and with so much depending on it,'' Apted said. ``I
worried: How can you come up with these ideas? How can you make
them fresh? And now that we have Austin Powers breathing down our
neck, we have to be very careful. We want to be in on the joke, we
don't want to be the joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately that was something to which everyone was sensitive,
he said, including Brosnan. ``They all live in fear of parodying
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And it all turned out to be a great deal of fun. He wouldn't
mind doing it again, if they ask him back. Now all he has to do is
see whether, in the crowded weeks of the holiday movie season, the
Bond film continues to perform well at the box office. And perhaps
to remind people about that other, little film of his that's out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is quite a moment for me,'' Apted said. ``An
extraordinary opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
