<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MANNESMANN-VODAFONE-A     11-21 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANNESMANN-VODAFONE-ASSESS-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RESCUER BUT NO CAPITULATION, MANNESMANN HEAD SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ As he tries to fend off the biggest hostile
takeover attempt in history, the chief executive of Mannesmann AG
insisted Sunday that he was not looking for a rescue by a ``white
knight'' investor or by German political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter that should be left to the markets and to
shareholders,'' the executive, Klaus Esser, said in an interview
Sunday. ``There should be freedom to make offers. If the offer is
not attractive, the shareholder can decide.''
</P>
<P>
   That may or may not turn out to be the final result. On Friday,
after weeks of shadowboxing, Vodafone Airtouch PLC of Britain
appealed directly to Mannesmann shareholders with an offer to buy
their stock for $127.7 billion, to be paid in newly issued Vodafone
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the battle would control what amounts to a
European transcontinental wireless communications network, at a
time when mobile voice and data services are growing at torrid
rates across the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   But more than money is at stake. German political leaders and
labor unions have already expressed outrage at what they describe
as a crass, ``Anglo-Saxon'' bid to break a major German success
story.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, originally a giant in engineering and automotive
parts, has transformed itself into a powerful phone and wireless
telecommunications company. Vodafone said that it would spin off
the automotive and engineering operations _ as Mannesmann itself
plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Vodafone would also split off the fixed-line telephone
operations into a company with separate stock, while primarily
concentrating on the wireless communications business.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, by contrast, argues that its strategy is based on
integrating the fixed-line and wireless businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And while Esser pleaded Sunday against letting the battle
descend into a brawl over nationality, he also emphasized that his
primary goal for the last year has been to keep his company
independent _ come what may.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from his home in Duesseldorf, Esser said
he had feared a hostile takeover bid from Vodafone since January,
when Vodafone acquired Airtouch Communications of San Francisco in
a deal valued at around $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Airtouch deal gave Vodafone a 35 percent stake in
Mannesmann's German mobile telephone company, D2, as well as a 22
percent stake in Omnitel, the Italian wireless company in which
Mannesmann now owns a controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   Esser said he had wanted at least a ``substantial minority
stake'' in Vodafone's British mobile-phone business and had
proposed expanding their cooperation in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready for a broader cooperation in Europe,'' he said
Sunday. ``They didn't want a broadening of cooperation on a parity
level. They didn't see us as a partner, but as a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's chief executive, Christopher Gent, has told a very
different story. At news conferences, Gent said that Vodafone was
eager to deepen its partnership with Mannesmann but was forced to
turn hostile when Mannesmann reached a deal last month to acquire
one of Vodafone's biggest rivals in Britain, Orange PLC.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the takeover fight marks a key test of Germany's
openness. German companies have made huge foreign acquisitions in
the last year, led by the Daimler-Benz acquisition of Chrysler
Corp. and Deutsche Bank's purchase of Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   But German businesses have remained surprisingly resistant to
foreign acquisition, whether friendly or hostile. If Mannesmann
repels Vodafone with help from political leaders or from other
members of Germany's old industrial club, other European countries
are likely to respond with new barriers against German companies.
</P>
<P>
   Esser said Sunday that German politicians should not try to
interfere with Vodafone's offer, which is entirely legal under
German law.
</P>
<P>
   Esser is in a particularly delicate position, with Mannesmann's
deal still pending to buy Orange, Britain's third-largest wireless
carrier, for about $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And last summer, Mannesmann scored a big victory by lining up in
Italy behind Olivetti SpA's hostile takeover of Telecom Italia.
When Olivetti won control of Telecom Italia, it sold Mannesmann a
controlling stake in the Omnitel wireless network for about $8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Against that wider background, Esser has framed most of his
arguments strictly in terms of shareholder benefits.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, both Mannesmann and Vodafone will begin campaigns to
win the hearts and wallets of Mannesmann shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is offering to pay 240 euros a share, now $247.25, a
premium of nearly 20 percent over Mannesmann's current share price.
Esser will hammer home his argument that Vodafone offers nothing
that Mannesmann needs and that its bid is paltry compared with the
track record of Mannesmann's own shares, which have quadrupled in
value in the last three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vodafone's offer is being made entirely in stock _ something
that Esser has criticized. A German magazine reported at the
weekend that Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was pushing for a new
European directive that would require cash payments. Schroeder had
said on Friday that hostile takeovers ``destroy corporate
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But Esser said he would be opposed to political intervention.
``I don't think we should change the rules,'' he said. ``It should
be left to the market and to shareholders. There should be freedom
to make offers, and if an offer is not attractive, the shareholders
can decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Esser has at least two credibility issues with shareholders. The
first is that Mannesmann's fixed-line telephone business is not yet
profitable and may not be for several years. The second is that
Mannesmann infuriated investors by agreeing to pay what many
consider too high a price for Orange.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Esser also insisted that he was not looking for a
``white knight'' _ a friendly investor or corporation that would
acquire a stake in Mannesmann and block Vodafone from winning
control.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Mannesmann did have ``substantial and
significant'' partnerships with Vivendi SA of France, which
controls that country's second-largest mobile-phone network as well
as other properties around Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that has nothing to do with a defense strategy,'' Esser
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mannesmann chief executive also ruled out a ``Pac-Man''
strategy of making a reverse offer to take over Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely excluded,'' Esser said. ``The Mannesmann
portfolio is better than the Vodafone portfolio. If we did a
Pac-Man, we would make our shareholders end up with the same thing
that Vodafone would have made them end up with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
