<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INTERNET COMPANY OFFERS CUSTOMIZED COMPUTER CURSORS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A small Internet company is hoping that the adage about tall
oaks growing from little acorns also applies to cyberspace, as it
seeks big results from turning perhaps the tiniest place on a
computer screen into advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The company is Comet Systems in New York, which has developed a
proprietary technology for commercializing cursors, the arrows that
point and click their way through the Internet. On Web sites where
marketers have bought ad space, computer users who have installed
Comet software can be offered customized cursors.
</P>
<P>
   The Comet Cursors are colorful miniature billboards in fanciful
shapes that can range from Pokemon characters and Energizer bunnies
to telephone directories and ``Star Trek'' spaceships. They also
come in generic forms with themes like pets, holidays and sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Comet efforts are indicative of the so-called rich media
applications being introduced to increase interest in online
pitches, particularly the banner ads that tend to be as dull as,
well, arrow-shaped cursors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test of any rich-media product is how effective it is at
getting more customers and creating more brand awareness,'' said
Marissa Gouck, an analyst at Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to keep it something special,'' she added,
``because often, the more ubiquitous it becomes, the less effective
it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Research by Millward Brown Interactive, a unit of the WPP Group,
that was commissioned by Comet and sponsored in part by four large
advertisers showed that differentiated cursors can significantly
increase the ability of computer users to recall seeing ad banners
and their desire to click through to read the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me that if the cursor could change contextually with
each site you visit, the advertising impression would remain with
you,'' said Jamie Rosen, recently promoted to chairman at Comet
from president, ``because it's a way of stamping a personality onto
a site.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen founded the company in 1997 with Dean Margolis, the chief
executive, who left during the summer, and Tom Schmitter, the chief
technical officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any new technology, the problem with putting an image in
the cursor space is one of education, getting people familiar and
comfortable with it,'' said Ben Austin, marketing director at
Comet. ``But invariably, every time we show it to people, they
become believers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comet technology is used on more than 55,000 Web sites, by
the company's count, with licensees that include AT&AMP;T Worldnet; the
Comedy Central cable network, jointly owned by Time Warner Inc. and
Viacom Inc.; Mattel; and the Warner Bros. Online unit of Time
Warner. Under an agreement signed last month with 24/7 Media in New
York, a product named the Cometized Banner, which automatically
serves branded cursors when an ad banner is clicked through, will
be delivered across the 24/7 ad network.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns with commercialized cursors have appeared on Web sites
operated by AltaVista, Lycos, theglobe.com and Yahoo, sponsored by
marketers like BellSouth, Energizer and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We incorporated the Comet Cursor into our own site,
Energizer.com,'' said Harriet Blickenstaff, a spokeswoman for the
Eveready Battery Company in St. Louis, a division of Ralston
Purina. ``It captures the fun and surprise of the bunny.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of driving people to the site, the results were
inconclusive,'' she added. ``But we would still deem it successful
because it fits our strategy, our tone, our spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of advertising in yet another Internet space could
generate a backlash among critics of the increasing commercialism
of communications, who could complain, to paraphrase the outcries
of the defeated villains in melodramatic old movies, ``Cursors,
foiled again!''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the nice thing about the Comet Cursor is that the user has
to make an active choice to get it,'' said Beth Suitt, advertising
manager of BellSouth Intelliventures in Atlanta, referring to the
need to download the software, known as a plug-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of an opt-in experience instead of being put in your
face without permission,'' she added. ``That gives advertisers an
opportunity to stick to users' minds without being intrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   The plug-in aspect can be a minus as well as a plus if users are
wary of the time it takes to download the Comet Cursor from sources
like www.cometsystems.com and www.cometzone.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay for the sins of our predecessors,'' Rosen said,
laughing, ``when people see a download and think it's going to
crash their computers.'' But Comet plugs the plug-in process as
brief, lasting less than 10 seconds. (If you try it late on a
Friday, when your computer is choking as colleagues file articles
on deadlines for Saturday, Sunday and Monday, it may take five
minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, by Comet's estimate, 15 million computer users have
downloaded the plug-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a neat little application that improves response rates
for advertisers,'' said Will Margiloff, advertising sales director
at theglobe.com in New York, which has developed promotions with
holiday themes using Comet Cursors. ``We'll continue to use it with
almost every promotion we do going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But can the commercialized cursor become more than just a
promotional ploy?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a gimmicky aspect to it,'' Ms. Gouck at
Jupiter said. ``The approach Comet has is pretty good, but
technology can go only so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some great executions of the Comet Cursor and I've
seen some awful ones,'' she added. ``A lot depends on the creative
capabilities of the advertiser.''
</P>
<P>
   And Comet's technology initially proved more popular with
individual home pages and small-business sites than with marketing
giants. For example, none of the four large advertisers from the
Comet survey have used the technology so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased with the results,'' said Gretchen Briscoe, a
spokeswoman for one advertiser, Procter &AMP; Gamble in Cincinnati.
``The cursor drove awareness and people remembered the brand, but
we've got no plans going forward to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope P&AMP;G rethinks its reticence. Who wouldn't relish the
chance to see a Comet Cursor shaped like a can of Comet cleanser?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 1734EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-CABLE-HOOKUP-     11-21 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-CABLE-HOOKUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE AGREEMENT, SNAGS REMAIN FOR DIGITAL TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The cable television and consumer electronics
industries say they have finally solved a problem that has lingered
for more than 18 months as a serious impediment to digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, because solutions and agreements between these two
industries are seldom wholehearted, the two sides are still sniping
at each other over some of the details.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been agreeing on a way to connect digital cable
boxes to digital television sets, which is necessary if cable
subscribers are to watch the new-style, digital programming.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer electronics industry announced last week that
sufficient agreement had been reached over what sort of connections
should be used for set makers to begin building cable-compatible
digital televisions. The first such sets should reach the market a
year from now.
</P>
<P>
   But TV-set makers are not yet ready to commit themselves to
making all digital television sets ready for cable in the form the
cable industry would like, saying that some consumers may not want
or need that capability.
</P>
<P>
   Digital television offers crystal-clear, high-resolution
pictures and first-quality digital sound _ as well as the
possibility of interactivity and other advanced digital services
that have yet to be devised. The federal government is mandating
the transition to digital TV and hopes to complete it by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The cable-connection debate first arose early in 1998, just
before the start of digital-television services. The industries
realized that after a decade of development costing hundreds of
millions of dollars, this small but vital question had been
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Because two-thirds of the United States' television viewers
subscribe to cable, government officials quickly realized that
unless these people were able to watch digital broadcasts, the
government-mandated transition would fail. So in the summer of
1998, William Kennard, the Federal Communications Commission
chairman, urged the parties to resolve the problem by November of
that year.
</P>
<P>
   When the appointed time came, the industries announced that they
had come to an agreement, and everyone gave congratulations. But
they had solved only part of the problem. They had figured out what
kind of plug they wanted to use. But they had not agreed on a
method to keep viewers from making digital copies of programs that
the programmers did not want copied _ like pay-for-view movies.
Hollywood will not release movies in digital form without such
protection.
</P>
<P>
   It took another year for that debate and others to be settled,
leading to last week's announcement. But even then, Gary Shapiro,
headof the Consumer Electronics Association (formerly known as the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association) complained that the
cable industry was trying to load the agreement with requirements
that his members, the TV makers, do not want.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to broaden the digital divide by forcing
Americans to pay more for every DTV set to get features they may
not want or use,'' he said. Industry estimates place the added cost
of the new connections at $100 or less for each television set.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the sort of plug that will be used. A year ago, the
industries agreed to use a plug that has come to be known as
Firewire and was first designed by Apple Computer. Besides the
video and audio portions of digital television fare, Firewire would
enable the reception of data and other information that might be
part of new types of interactive programming.
</P>
<P>
   Since agreeing upon Firewire, the cable industry has won
agreement from worldwide standard-setting bodies that this sort of
plug would serve as the connector between digital TV and the
digital cable box. The cable industry is requiring its members to
use the plug on all digital boxes starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Green, head of Cable Labs, the cable industry
organization that worked on the standard, said of the dispute with
the set makers: ``We have a pretty wide consensus on this; we
really have addressed the cable compatibility problem. We've done
what we think is right. But if they don't want to use it, they
don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Milbourn, a senior executive with Thomson Consumer
Electronics, maker of the RCA and Proscan brands of TV, said he
assumed cable companies would eventually want to offer a
lower-priced option on their cable boxes, too, ``because cable
would want to market these new services _ not only to new digital
sets but also, more importantly, to the installed base of over 250
million regular TV sets as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
