<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      11-21 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``CRYING: THE NATURAL &AMP; CULTURAL HISTORY OF TEARS'' &QL; 
By Tom Lutz (Norton, $25.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only humans sob. Weeping is a peculiarity of man _ no other
animals are known to do it. And yet we know surprisingly little
about it, other than the obvious (children cry more than adults do)
and the physiological (reflex tears _ those you produce when you
peel an onion _ have a different chemical composition from
emotional tears). Crying is an escape, a physical act that
distracts us from the trauma that has made us cry. It is also, Lutz
tells us, a kind of language, ``expressing not just our distress
but our demands, not just our desire to be understood but our
desire to evade detection. Our crocodile tears can be used to
ensnare, to confuse, to extort, to deceive. Even those tears we cry
when we are alone have an imagined audience. Even in our deepest
moments of grief, we can be well aware of the effect our tears are
having on those around us.'' This vastly researched,
interdisciplinary study of tears is a delight, in the tradition of
Diane Ackerman's ``A Natural History of the Senses.'' Lutz looks at
how philosophers, psychologists, anthropologists and sociologists
have interpreted tears over the years. He looks at crying in art
and literature, film and advertisement. He explores the physical
process of crying and its psychological benefits, as well as gender
issues that it raises (powerful women such as Hillary Rodham
Clinton do not cry in public because it could be read as weakness).
He discusses our changing attitudes toward tears, illustrated by
the fact that Edmund Muskie was run out of the 1972 presidential
primary race for crying in front of reporters, whereas Bob Dole,
who remained dry-eyed for the first 40 years of his public life,
cried many times over the past decade without consequence. Finally,
Lutz poses another puzzle: Even if we think we know why we cry, can
we explain why we stop? ``Tears,'' he writes, ``are the most
substantial and yet the most fleeting, the most obvious and yet the
most enigmatic proof of our emotional lives.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE LADIES AUXILIARY'' &QL; 
By Tova Mirvis (Norton, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This compassionate first novel is the story of the women of an
Orthodox Jewish community in Memphis, Tenn., and their relationship
with a free-spirited woman _ a convert to Judaism _ who comes to
live among them. Batsheva is the widow of Benjamin Jacobs, who has
been killed in a car crash in New York. Hoping to ease her
loneliness and preserve her ties to him, Batsheva brings their
5-year-old daughter to the Memphis community in which Benjamin grew
up. From the start, it's obvious to the other women that Batsheva
does not fit in _ she does not cook or clean, nor does she pay
suitable attention to the modesty of her clothing or to the
dictates of Jewish tradition. But she does bring an understated
self-confidence, a passion for delving into the questions that
religious faith inspires, and a sympathy for the community's young
people, who crave freedom from the obligations to which they were
born. Mirvis tells her story in the collective voice of the Jewish
ladies, a ``we'' that reflects the depth of their traditions, the
vulnerability of those traditions in the modern world and the
oppressive standards that have grown up around them. Mirvis never
loses her compassion for these characters, nor does she ignore the
value of their moral and religious commitments. They are gossipy
and judgmental, yet oddly innocent. And in coming to terms with
their feelings about Batsheva, the women begin to question
themselves. This is a gentle story _ no sex, violence or overt
drama _ written with a deft hand and a sympathetic heart. Mirvis,
who grew up in the Memphis community on which her novel is based,
says her novel is ``emotionally autobiographical.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``MISS MANNERS' GUIDE TO DOMESTIC TRANQUILITY''By Judith Martin
(Crown, $30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The formidable arbiter of taste and tactics turns her eyes to
the home front, where civility often meets the fate of a dead
goldfish. She begins, of course, with the ticklish affairs of the
people of the home front, known as ``The Family.'' This chapter is
so complex, given today's divorce and remarriage statistics, that
New &AMP; Notable had to take notes just to keep up. But Miss Manners
has everything under control. Other headings include ``The Help,''
``The Visitors'' and ``Entertaining the Relatives.'' Our favorite
parts are not Miss Manners' essays on these matters, but the
questions she receives from her gentle readers and the answers she
gives, in which she shows herself capable of gutting a cloddish
correspondent without even a trace of discourtesy. We love Miss
Manners, yes we do. We would suggest, however, that she has written
many books (12); that the overlap is conspicuous; that being
content with one's already considerable fortune is a gracious thing
indeed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A LIKELY STORY'' &QL; 
By Rosemary Mahoney (Anchor, $14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Miss Manners would wring her hands over Rosemary Mahoney.
There is no civility in this memoir (now new in paperback) of the
summer of 1978, when the 17-year-old Mahoney worked as a domestic
for the woman she thought was her idol, Lillian Hellman. Hellman
was irascible, insulting, bossy, cheap and pathetic. Mahoney was a
teenager, and so not much more pleasant than her employer. The
difference is that Hellman is dead and Mahoney is alive to tell the
tale. Neither woman looks good, although it is Hellman who suffers
the indignity of having her 73-year-old body described through the
eyes of an angry young girl. This is what Miss Manners would
whisper in Rosemary Mahoney's ear: Someday, you will be old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can reach Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, viae-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
