<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Monday, Nov. 22, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHAOS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Five months after NATO
forces moved in to take control of Kosovo, there is little
electricity and an inconstant water supply, the streets are full of
garbage, traffic is in chaos without working stop lights or police
direction, few cars have license plates, no one has new identity
papers, and the Serb and Gypsy minorities continue to be harassed
and attacked. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Guedermes, Russia) _ Trying to quell criticism
of their grinding military offensive in Chechnya, Russian officials
take journalists on a tour of Chechnya's second largest city. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-EXTRADITE (Washington) _ A Colombian accused of running
a major heroin- smuggling ring was bundled aboard an American
government plane in Colombia today and flown to the United States,
the first time in nearly a decade that Colombia has turned over one
of its own citizens to stand trial here. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS (Princeville, N.C.) _ After one of the worst
floods in North Carolina's history, Princeville's more than 2,000
citizens, many of whom are direct descendants from the freed slaves
who founded the town, are struggling with choices that will
determine whether their historic town can ever exist again. But
unlike many other residents of North Carolina who are taking the
FEMA buyout offer, many in Princeville consider the offer a ``sell
out'' and are refusing to leave. By Emily Yellin. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   CENTRALPARK-TRANSFORM (New York) _ Two decades ago, Central Park
was a scary, trash-blown ruin that was Exhibit A for those who
claimed New York City was no longer a fit place to live. No more.
It has been replaced with a meticulously groomed park where bronze
preservation specialists each year polish and wax all 50 of the
park's statues. What is far less obvious is how this transformation
happened. Considering the park's location, a large haul of private
dollars helped. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
