<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-SEPARATE-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITE(AT)HOME TO SEPARATE CABLE AND CONTENT DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the headline and grafs 1, 4, 5, 7 and 9 instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(rk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Under pressure from investors to clarify its
business strategy, Excite(AT)Home has decided to draw a distinction
between its Internet access business and its media-content business
by creating a separate tracking stock for the media assets, the
company said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would file the necessary documents with the
Securities and Exchange Commission in the first half of next year
and distribute the new stock in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company was created in May by the merger of Web company
Excite and the At Home Corp., a cable Internet-access company. At
the time of the merger, its stock was trading around $63 but has
sunk as low as the mid-30s in August. On Friday, the shares closed
at $52.3125, up $2.125.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Excite(AT)Home said the tracking stock was meant
to signal that the company saw a difference between the information
content and Internet access portions of its business. AT&AMP;T, which
is Excite(AT)Home's largest investor, has a 26 percent equity stake
in a class of shares that gives it a 56 percent voting stake. AT&AMP;T
has persistently signaled discomfort at the coupling of the content
and cable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an overhang on the stock that is the result of
speculation about the outcome of our discussions on the strategic
direction of company,'' Thomas A. Jermoluk, chairman and chief
executive of Excite(AT)Home, said in an interview Sunday. ``We
believe we have achieved strategic alignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk said the decision was not a precursor to a more formal
spinoff of the media assets into a separate company. In fact, he
noted that SEC rules would preclude such a spinoff for several
years, once the company issued a tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   Excite(AT)Home presently receives 65 percent of its revenue from
its media assets, which includes the Excite Web portal available to
anyone on the Internet; a high-capacity (AT)Home Web portal for
cable subscribers; MatchLogic, a direct marketing company and
Enliven, a multimedia advertising company. The balance of the
revenue comes from subscription fees from cable Internet-access
customers, of which it had 840,000 at the end of the third quarter.
The company's third-quarter revenue of $112.6 million slightly
exceeded analysts' forecasts, and was nearly double revenue of
$57.8 million in last year's third quarter. Excite(AT)Home lost
$498.6 million in the most recent quarter, largely as it took
charges associated with the merger.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, the company expects to see a shift in the balance of
its revenue, with 45 percent coming from the media assets.
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision to issue the tracking stock, reached last
Wednesday, comes against a backdrop of uncertainty and a
fast-changing marketplace for Excite(AT)Home. In 2002, exclusive
contracts will begin to expire with AT&AMP;T, Cox and Comcast, which
until then are obliged to use Excite(AT)Home for the cable-modem
services offered on their cable television systems. Cox and Comcast
each own 8 percent of Excite(AT)Home. AT&AMP;T has already said that it
would consider opening its systems to competing Internet access
providers once the Excite(AT)Home contract expires. AT&AMP;T has faced
a heavy lobbying effort on that issue by a coalition of Internet
access providers, including America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk asserted that the media side of the business was moving
so quickly that a separate tracking stock would put the company in
a better position to react to competitive changes. The tracking
stock, he said, might be used for making acquisitions of other
media businesses without diluting the shares representing the
Internet-access cable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be competitive in the world of the Net we need to
be able to move quickly, and to have a full range of strategic
options,'' Jermoluk said. ``One of the key reasons for the
structure is that it allows us to pursue all options without
diluting the interests of our cable partners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
