<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-2ND-HEADBASHING-76     11-21 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-2ND-HEADBASHING-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECOND HEAD-BASHING ATTACK IS REPORTED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His jaw is no longer wired shut and his shattered
fingers are beginning to move again, but Kent Gasser's face still
bears signs of a merciless beating he survived six weeks ago in
Riverside Park when a stranger bashed his head with a rock in the
middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lingering double vision, a damaged right hand and a
crooked nose, Gasser said he is almost ready to return to his
acting career _ and his job as a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it could have been a lot worse,'' said Gasser, 38, who
spent three days incoherent and unidentified before co-workers
tracked him down at a hospital in Harlem. ``The guy thought he had
finished me off.''
</P>
<P>
   The beating of Gasser has a few elements in common with the case
of Nicole Barrett, the 27-year-old woman who was hit on the head
with a paving stone in midtown last week, but the police are
reluctant to link the two attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Gasser insists that the police sketch of Ms. Barrett's attacker
strongly resembles the man who smashed him in the head and face on
Sept. 30 as he rehearsed lines in the park for an upcoming play.
``I've gone through thousands of mug shots, and this is the first
guy who looks like him,'' Gasser said. ``I will never ever forget
that face.''
</P>
<P>
   But investigators noted that Gasser recalls his assailant as
being more than 6 feet tall; witnesses to the assault on Ms.
Barrett say the attacker was 6 inches shorter. Investigators say
the discrepancy makes it unlikely the two cases are related.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gasser's encounter with random brutality, his painstaking
but steady recovery and his zeal to return to life in New York
offer hints of the road faced by Ms. Barrett, who remained in
critical condition Sunday at Bellevue Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her case is more complicated, because she suffered a brain
injury; Gasser did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those crazy, out-of-the-blue things that's
shaken my life out, but I still love the city,'' Gasser said from
his family's home in Salt Lake City, where he plans to stay until
early January. ``I don't blame New York.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a Thursday afternoon, warm and sunny, when Gasser
strolled from his apartment at Broadway and 151st Street to a spot
in the park where he often went to memorize and recite lines. The
opening of ``The Blur,'' at the Pulse Ensemble Theater on West 42nd
Street, in which Gasser had a leading role, was three weeks away.
It would have been his first off-Broadway role.
</P>
<P>
   The park was relatively empty, but Gasser said he was not
concerned when a man with a lazy eye and 4-inch dreadlocks
approached and asked for spare change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give out quarters all the time,'' he said, ``but I honestly
had no money in my pockets, so I said `Sorry' and kept walking.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, as Gasser entered a more secluded area near
148th Street, his head buried in his script, a rock hit him in the
back of the head. He was dragged into a ditch, he said, and when he
opened his eyes he was face to face with the same man.
</P>
<P>
   The man's expression was full of fury. ``You have five seconds
to change your mind,'' he recalled the man saying, his arm cocked,
the rock poised above his face. Gasser repeated that he had no
money.
</P>
<P>
   Then the beating began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   As he held up his hands to block the first blows, Gasser
remembers seeing his fingers and wrists shatter and go limp. When
he tried to scream, the rock smashed his teeth and jaw, silencing
him.
</P>
<P>
   Unconsciousness followed, although doctors said the pounding
continued for some time afterward. Three hours later, a passer-by
found Gasser's inert body and called the police. He briefly
regained consciousness in an ambulance and sensed the half-dozen
teeth that had collected at the back of his throat. ``I remember
thinking, `I don't want to swallow my teeth,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three days, he remained semiconscious, in critical
condition. After he failed to show up for his job as a waiter at
City Grill, his boss tracked him down at St. Luke's Hospital, where
he had been admitted as John Doe.
</P>
<P>
   Through a series of operations, his face and hands have been
reconstructed. Eight metal plates and 29 screws keep his features
in place; still other hardware fuses together his splintered hands.
``I'm really screwed up,'' Gasser said with a laugh. At other times
during the conversation, however, he was overcome with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, after weeks of intravenous feeding, Gasser's jaw
was unwired, enabling him to speak and eat solid foods again.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He's dealing with a lot of anger and depression, but thank
heaven he doesn't have any neurological damage,'' said his sister,
Linda Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his health problems, Gasser has financial ones related to
the attack. He has no health insurance and faces more than $50,000
in medical bills. His play, ``The Blur,'' opened and closed without
him, but his boss at the City Grill has promised to hold open his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they have no leads and have yet to find any
witnesses. The attack received no media attention. Gasser is
convinced he will spot his assailant one day. ``It's not just
revenge I crave,'' he said. ``I just want to stop him from doing
this to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits to feeling jumpy on the street but is eager to return
to the city he adopted two years ago, when he and a group of
friends from the University of Utah started a small theater company
in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's life,'' he said of the attack. ``You have to roll with
the punches and do the best you can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
