<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7023 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS-ART     11-21 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS OF TOWN FORMED BY SLAVES PONDER HISTORY, FUTURE AFTER
FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.D., Ill.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ When a group of newly freed slaves here
wanted to form a community of their own just after the Civil War,
they had to take whatever land they could get. In 1865, that was a
snake-infested, mosquito-ridden swamp in a flood plain along the
southern side of the Tar River in eastern North Carolina. It was
land that the white people in Tarboro, on the northern side
of the river, did not want.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, those former slaves had built a town so
viable that they petitioned the state to recognize it as a legal
entity. In 1865, Princeville became the first town in the United
States to be chartered and governed solely by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Now the more than 2,000 residents of Princeville, many of whom
are direct descendants of its founders, are struggling with a
dilemma more extreme than any other this town has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   Their storied community was washed away in September by the
worst flooding in North Carolina's history. Now they must choose
whether to return to the now uninhabited land and rebuild, or
abandon forever the place where their ancestors first experienced
full U.S. citizenship. The impending decision has those who would
accept a federal buyout of the town at odds with the many who
believe that doing so would betray the cherished legacy of their
forebears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge we are facing in Princeville,'' said Rep. Eva
Clayton, the Democrat whose district includes the town, ``is how to
keep its legacy and make it viable in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of places similarly devastated by floods in recent
years have accepted government buyouts of all or part of their
towns. Grand Forks, N.D., was one, along with Valmeyer, Ill., and
Kinston, N.C. Federal Emergency Management Agency officials have
already received word from at least 45 city or county governments
affected by the floods in eastern North Carolina that they intend
to apply for federal buyouts.
</P>
<P>
   In all, officials estimate, the flooding caused $1.2 billion
worth of structural damage across the state. Of the 6,000 buildings
that the federal agency estimates were damaged beyond repair
statewide, about 600 are in Princeville.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Princeville officials reported that only 75
people had signed up so far. The town has given its residents,
about 40 of whom are white, a Dec. 16 deadline to submit
applications. After that, city leaders will decide whether there is
enough interest to apply for the buyout. The town government must
make a formal application before any individual applications are
considered. If the town decides against a buyout, no residents will
be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   For Glennie Matthewson 2nd, 55, a lawyer and former Princeville
mayor, leaving is not an option. His great-grandmother was a slave
and one of the first residents of Princeville.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our ancestors built this town they were seen as uppity
blacks, with the audacity to talk about incorporating their own
town,'' Matthewson said. ``That is a hell of a legacy. The deeper
the roots the harder the fight, and the more resistance you're
going to get to taking the town from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Princeville, Delia Perkins, 57, lost her home in
the flood, but she too remains firm about returning. She works full
time as a teacher's assistant in the Edgecombe County School system
and receives $250 a month to serve as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers,'' she said, ``I would have said from Day
1 that we will rebuild, no doubt about it.'' But she added that she
believes the town government must consider all its options.
</P>
<P>
   Some question the wisdom of rebuilding. Marcia Wheeler, 43, a
mother of two, says she has no plans to return _ ever. ``I wouldn't
want to go through this again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the buyout, the Federal Emergency Management Agency would
purchase property for what appraisers estimate was the market value
the day before the flood. The buildings would be removed and the
open space deeded back to the town, but it could never be built on
again.
</P>
<P>
   If the town decides to rebuild, money from a federal buyout will
not be available and the town will seek money from other government
agencies and private sources. The mayor estimates the cost of
rebuilding to be at least $80 million. Central to the effort would
be reconstruction of a dike that controls the Tar River. That cost
is estimated at $300,000 and would be paid for by the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The levee was built in 1965, a century after the settlement of
the area. It was designed to protect the town against the kind of
flood estimated to happen only every 300 years. That levy afforded
enough protection to negate the flood-plain status of the town in
official terms. And it is what allows the town to even consider the
option of returning to the same site.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Davison, mitigation director of the emergency management
agency, said the U.S. Geological Survey issued a report this month
saying the recent flood was well in excess of a 500-year event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a biblical kind of flood,'' Davison said. ``The risk
is so remote that we don't regulate against it, just as we don't
protect against meteors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Tar River began its rampage on Sept. 16, as the result of
the 20 inches of rain dumped on the state by Hurricane Floyd. On
the day it spilled over the dike, it had reached 48.5 feet above
sea level. Early the next morning the town was evacuated. The river
crested at 53 feet above sea level, and the town remained under
about 14 feet of water for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When residents were allowed to return, they were shocked to see
houses that had floated off their foundations and landed on top of
cars. Precious family photographs, keepsakes and heirlooms were
lost. Many houses had been condemned. More than 200 coffins
dislodged from the town cemetery were found floating around the
town. None of the original slaves' graves were disturbed _ perhaps
because they had been dug deeper than more recent graves.
</P>
<P>
   And even today, two months after the deluge, the damage is
strikingly evident in the deserted town. Mud-caked clothes hang
from trees. The water has gone and most of the facades of houses
are still intact, but their insides have been stripped bare to
remove destroyed furniture and rotted drywall.
</P>
<P>
   That is the case at Linda Whitest's home on Walston Street in
the heart of Princeville. Her one-year-old house was destroyed by
flood waters. Across the street, her grandmother's house, where Ms.
Whitest, 49, grew up, was destroyed. Next door to her grandmother's
house, her mother's house was also ruined. The homes are all
situated on land handed down from Ms. Whitest's great-grandfather,
Frank Walston, a son of slaves and the man for whom the street was
named.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago I said there is no way I'm going back, I was so
devastated,'' Ms. Whitest said. ``But then I thought about it, and
I said, why should I give up what my ancestors had worked so hard
to leave us? It would be like Princeville never existed, like it
had just been erased away.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthewson said moving the town even a few blocks away is
unacceptable to most residents. ``My ancestors' energies and
efforts and resources went into that specific property in
Princeville,'' he said. ``Those are the streets I played in, the
trees I climbed. You take the town and move it anywhere else, then
you've severed me from my actual roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the flooding, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Al
Sharpton both visited the town, as did President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was Valley Forge,'' Sharpton said, ``imagine what
America would be doing. We preach black pride. Here's an example of
a city that has faced a major disaster. I think it's incumbent upon
black America to use its economic and political resources to try to
restore that city.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with other flood victims, the displaced residents of
Princeville are living either with friends or family or in the
temporary trailer park set up by the emergency management agency in
nearby Rocky Mount. The trailer park, just around the corner from a
women's prison, is officially named New Life Fountain Park.
Residents call it FEMA City.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Black, 35, a construction worker, has been living at the
temporary site since it was opened about seven weeks ago. He said
he plans to return to the Princeville property passed down to him
by his ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people took that swampland and made a town out of it,''
Black said. ``It would make us look real bad to let it go now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
