<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. UNITED ARE CHAMPIONS AGAIN, BEATING L.A. 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Two defensive blunders by the Los Angeles
Galaxy was all D.C. United needed Sunday to capture its third title
in the four years of Major League Soccer with a 2-0 victory before
44,910 at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was an afternoon full of misfortune for the Galaxy, who also
lost the championship game to United in the league's first season.
But United was the superior team for the most part, playing with
abundant confidence, and the team was rarely threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes into the game, the Galaxy lost Robin Fraser, the
league's defender of the year, who broke his collar bone in a
footrace with Roy Lassiter near the sideline, forcing Coach Sigi
Schmid of the Galaxy to make drastic adjustments in his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a couple of mistakes that led to goals,'' Schmid said,
``but take nothing away from D.C. United. They're an outstanding
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's defensive play was nowhere near the quality it
displayed during the regular season, when it allowed 29 goals in 32
games, becoming the first team in the history of the league to
allow less than a goal a game. The defense was disorganized Sunday,
and Kevin Hartman, the league's goalkeeper of the year, was even
worse than his defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Galigiuri, who scored the goal 10 years ago that sent the
United States to the 1990 World Cup in Italy, its first Cup
appearance in 40 years, failed to clear the ball after a save by
Hartman in the 19th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Moreno, the deadly United striker, leaped on the ball and
beat Hartman from close range for his fifth goal in the playoffs
this season and 10th in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have still won even if Fraser was there,'' Moreno
said after the game. ``We came here determined to win. We were the
better team and we felt the Galaxy had to play a very good game to
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy committed several mistakes on defense, but none was
bigger than Hartman's during injury time before intermission.
Hartman had two chances to clear after a back-pass by Steve Jolley,
who took Fraser's place. Hartman scuffed the ground on his second
attempt, allowing Ben Olsen of United to collect the ball and
deposit it into the empty net from 22 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen did plenty of constructive work on the right side of
United's midfield and was voted the game's most valuable player,
although Richie Williams, the indefatigable defensive midfielder of
United, also had an excellent game.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive Williams shadowed Mauricio Cienfuegos, the
Galaxy's playmaker, so effectively that the Galaxy never found a
rhythm offensively. Tom Presthus, United's goalkeeper, was forced
to make just one save.
</P>
<P>
   United came into the game as the league's most productive team
and played with the composure and confidence of a champion. With
Marco Etcheverry conducting from the center of the midfield, all
United's components worked effectively on offense, while the
defense was anchored by Eddie Pope and Calos Liamosa.
</P>
<P>
   United continues to set the standard in the four-year-old
league. This was its fourth trip to the championship game and the
only time it lost was last year, to Chicago in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific to have a dominant team,'' said
Commissioner Don Garber. ``There will be teams shooting after them
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   CORNER KICKS
</P>
<P>
   The league decided earlier in the day to put into effect in this
game one of the rule changes it will enforce next season. The clock
runs from zero to 90 minutes and the official time was kept by the
referee, Tim Weyland, while a fourth official determined the amount
of injury time added at the end of each half. ... With his goal,
Jaime Moreno became the league's leading scorer in the playoffs
with 28 points from 10 goals and eight assists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
