<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE LEGISLATORS TRY TO PEP UP DEBATE BY EMULATING BRITAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The prime minister is at the podium, struggling to field
a series of increasingly challenging questions from the leader of
the opposition. Jeers are rising in crescendo from the Parliament
floor, and the few spectators allowed in are on the edge of their
seats, fairly straining for a view.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, known as question time, has been adopted straight
from British politics. On the surface, just two weeks into its
existence, it still may seem like a jolting innovation to some in
the often soporific world of the Japanese Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Of course that was the idea _ arrived at jointly by the
government and the opposition _ from the start: that the Parliament
of the nation where consensus is so highly valued that trenchant
comment had become an endangered species needed some serious
reinvigoration. And what better way, it was thought, than a dose of
old-fashioned, British style confrontational debate?
</P>
<P>
   From technology to popular culture, Japan is well known for its
facility for borrowing from other countries. Its Parliament was
modeled on those of Europe, and foreign models inspired most of
this country's modern institutions.
</P>
<P>
   What is less widely known abroad is how assiduously Japan
reshapes whatever it borrows, molding everything from Chinese food
to American words to fit within the nation's rather narrow comfort
zones. And as it is already turning out, question time is no
different.
</P>
<P>
   So there was Yukio Hatoyama, the leader of the opposition
Democratic Party, standing tall and tugging at his shirt cuffs for
dramatic effect demanding an explanation from Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi about why policemen have not been arrested in a provincial
corruption case.
</P>
<P>
   Was this the most compelling question to begin the second
edition of the new, weekly 40-minute debate? Perhaps not, but it
was an improvement over Hatoyama's first try, a week earlier, when
the nation's eyes were bracketed on him as he began the new
spectacle by asking Obuchi what he had eaten for breakfast that
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt confrontation, it seems, does not come any more easily to
Japanese politicians than it does to ordinary Japanese, whose
national language is a maze of well-practiced protocols and polite
indirection. But to be fair, Hatoyama eventually warmed to his
subject in the 26 minutes accorded him.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Obuchi temporarily suspend unpopular tax payments for a
national nursing care system just as elections are nearing,
Hatoyama asked. And how was it that the conservative governing
party, the Liberal Democrats, had gone into coalition recently with
a party widely seen as the creature of the country's largest
Buddhist organization?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening because you share a desire to be ruling
parties, not because you have agreed on any policies beforehand,''
Hatoyama said. ``And you should be ashamed of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning up the heat further, the opposition leader handed Obuchi
a three-year-old pamphlet from the prime minister's own party that
denounced the Buddhist-affiliated party as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning heavily on his podium, Obuchi replied weakly: ``Around
that time that was the mainstream view of the party. But after that
we have had some twists and turns.''
</P>
<P>
   If that exchange furnished a touch of drama, for those taking
part it almost certainly involved little surprise. In the
incestuous world of Japanese politics _ again, as in the society at
large _ few things are avoided so carefully as surprise.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians' staff members in the United States are
responsible for trying to prepare their bosses for every possible
question in advance, in Japan the opposition has courteously
submitted its questions to the governing party two days in advance
of question time.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same thing happened to a foreign journalist when he
arrived for an appointment with a government minister here
recently. A staff member handed him a list of questions that he
suggested be used in the interview. The minister agreed only
hesitantly to answer some others.
</P>
<P>
   What is the purpose of holding a debate at all, one might ask?
Still, the new system might be seen as an improvement over the
traditional parliamentary debates here in which bureaucrats
prepared the questions for both opposition and governing parties,
and then sat and answered them solemnly in testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Question time here is meant to remove some of the immense power
from a bureaucracy discredited by 10 years of economic drift. And
it is intended to give elected politicians more of an air of
involvement in running the country instead of just counting money
and votes.
</P>
<P>
   Although formally democratic, Japan has been a virtual one-party
state for decades, with Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party making
few concessions until its monopoly on power was broken in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, few voters feel strong party affiliation. And many of
the country's political leaders look longingly toward the West,
where stable two-party systems are common and political identities
run deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old one-party system has collapsed, and the new party
system hasn't yet emerged,'' said Gerald Curtis, a professor of
political science at Columbia University who specializes in Japan.
``In the meantime, what can differentiate one party from another in
a society that isn't rent by deep cleavages, whether class or
primordial issues like ethnicity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by copying the British in organizational terms doesn't
mean that you can copy them in terms of free speech and wit and the
skills of parliamentary debate, and that is what question time is
all about. What we are left with is personalities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
