<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT DOMINATES HINGIS TO CAPTURE CHASE CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Public floggings may be illegal, but that's just what
Lindsay Davenport inflicted on top-ranked Martina Hingis Sunday at
Madison Square Garden. Davenport wielded her racquet like a deadly
weapon in a shockingly one-sided 6-4, 6-2 victory in the final of
the Chase Championships, and Hingis, who usually thinks her way out
of intimidating situations, never came close to escaping this one.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old Hingis, the defending Chase champion, had tears
in her eyes when she and Davenport clasped hands across the net
after Davenport's brutally efficient victory, her third consecutive
drubbing of Hingis this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just an awesome way to end the year,'' said a jubilant
Davenport, who forced Hingis to surrender with three aces in the
final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up today I really just wanted to go for my shots,
go for my winners and be the one who was dictating, and I was able
to do it all,'' the second-seeded Davenport said. ``I mean, to beat
Martina four and two is pretty great; it's pretty hard to do it any
worse than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, this year's Wimbledon champion, added: ``I keep
accumulating a lot of big titles. For people who said I may not be
mentally strong enough, (this is) definitely proof that you can
change things around. When I was 20, I really seemed to turn my
career around, and the last three years have just been
phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's outcome was a reversal of last year's Chase final. Then
it was Davenport who ended the year with the No. 1 ranking but
Hingis who pocketed the $500,000 winner's check. Davenport's
victory Sunday, in her third Chase final, improved her record
against Hingis to 9-7 and prompted a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have to be afraid of anything right now,'' said
Hingis, whose season included an Australian Open title and
appearances in the finals at the French and U.S. Opens. ``I mean,
she's been injured and she came back out great. Right now I always
could consider her as a top player on the tour. Maybe I was more
consistent over the year, but she was just playing better at this
tournament. Probably that was like her best match against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said it could have been her best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would definitely say it was one of the best ones I've played
in my career, I'd like to think ever,'' she said of a performance
that included nine aces, 36 winners, 12 unforced errors and
conversions on 4 of 7 break chances. ``The whole match, I just
played the way I wanted to play, aggressive and going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport made an exasperated Hingis scramble from corner to
corner for the duration of the 61-minute debacle. The first game of
the match foretold the mauling to come: pushed to break point,
Hingis lost on a vicious forehand drive from Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth game, when an equally vicious crosscourt backhand
on her second break point gave Davenport a commanding 4-1 lead,
Hingis was struggling to control her frustration in front of 14,563
spectators. She hurled her racquet toward a courtside trash can,
plopped down in her changeover chair and buried her face in a
towel. After that brief spate of venting she recomposed herself and
cut Davenport's lead to 4-3, but her hopes of a comeback began and
ended there.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-minute second set resembled a match between a flyweight
and a heavyweight more than a sanctioned bout between the world's
two top female tennis players. Hingis held serve in the opening
game, but her 1-0 lead proved ephemeral. She whiffed on a 98 mph
ace from Davenport in the second game, dropped her serve in the
third, and seemed reluctant to leave the safety of her changeover
chair and absorb the remainder of the punishment her opponent had
in store for her. In the seventh game Hingis dropped her serve at
love to trail, 5-2, and after that she simply stood on the
baseline, eyebrows arched in disbelief, and watched the aces sail
by.
</P>
<P>
   ``My serve was great; everything was great,'' Davenport said.
``Now I have a couple of months to catch her. I'm looking at, maybe
April, I can reclaim the No. 1 ranking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
