<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HAMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN FREES AND EXPELS 4 JAILED HAMAS LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Ending a three-month standoff, King Abdullah of
Jordan freed four imprisoned leaders of the militant Palestinian
movement Hamas on Sunday and hours later placed them on a private
jet bound for the Persian Gulf state of Qatar, Jordanian officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty more lower-level Hamas activists will be freed from
prison soon and permitted to remain in Jordan, officials in Amman
said. But they said that Hamas offices in Jordan, which the
government closed by force in August, would not be allowed to
reopen. Officials in Qatar later said that they, too, would
prohibit the Hamas leaders from carrying out any political
activities in their country.
</P>
<P>
   The expulsion appeared to give Abdullah's government a clear and
relatively cost-free victory in its confrontation with Hamas, which
it accused of engaging in clandestine paramilitary training and _
more worrisome for the monarchy _ of penetrating local
fundamentalist opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Jordanian officials adamantly denied that the crackdown
had been conducted at the behest of Washington or Israel. But they
acknowledged that the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, had asked
Amman to take action against what he saw as a dangerous source of
rebellion against his peace negotiations with Israel. The Hamas
office in Amman had openly urged the sabotaging of peace talks with
terrorist attacks inside Israel.
</P>
<P>
   When reports surfaced on Saturday about a possible expulsion, a
Hamas spokesman in Gaza, Ismail Abu Shanab, said the action would
provoke ``a serious deterioration in the relationship between
Jordan and the Palestinians,'' more than a million of whom live as
refugees in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hamas headquarters in Gaza had already quietly agreed to
cease open political activity in Jordan, officials in Amman say.
And leaders of the Muslim Brotherhood, Jordan's largest opposition
party, which loudly championed the cause of the Hamas leaders,
declined to criticize the expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   The four Hamas leaders expelled were Khaled Meshal, the chief of
the Hamas politburo; Ibrahim Ghoshesh, the local Hamas spokesman;
and two other key politburo members, Abdul Aziz-al-Umary and Sami
Khatter.
</P>
<P>
   The government first issued arrest orders for Meshal and
Ghoshesh when they were traveling in Iran in August. But in what
was seen as a deliberate challenge to the government, they flew
home, and were promptly arrested. Aziz al-Umary was arrested two
weeks ago in what was read locally as signs of new pressure on
Hamas.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah told reporters in Amman last month that the fate of the
imprisoned Hamas leaders would be decided ``in the courts.'' But he
made it clear that he preferred to avoid a long public
confrontation with the movement. Equally, though, the Jordanian
government could not afford to back down once it publicly accused
the Hamas leaders of offenses that were tantamount to treason.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Jordanian officials portrayed the Hamas office in Amman
as a renegade operation with seemingly closer ties to Iran than to
the Hamas headquarters in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   And they remain angered at the way that Meshal was elevated to
heroic status among many local Palestinians by his survival of a
botched Israeli assassination attempt several years ago. Their aim
has been to remove the Hamas leaders from the scene permanently but
quietly, without creating ``new martyrs,'' one official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZECH-COLDWAR-MUSEUM-     11-21 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-COLDWAR-MUSEUM-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CZECHS REMEMBER IRON CURTAIN'S BAD OLD DAYS WITH CARDBOARD
`MUSEUM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Ten years after the Velvet Revolution,
which quickly ended 40 years of totalitarian rule here, Prague
residents found themselves back in grim communist reality during
the weekend, complete with interminable lines in shops, abusive
police officers, arrogant bureaucrats and brainwashing propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least for one day. As part of last week's anniversary
celebration, the revolution's former student leaders organized an
Open-Air Museum of Totalitarianism to remind their fellow citizens
of the former regime.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, a small cardboard village erected overnight on
Wenceslaus Square, embodied the conditions that people used to hate
and ridicule in private but accepted in public. All day Saturday,
large crowds braved freezing temperatures and waited patiently to
get a taste of the old times.
</P>
<P>
   There was the half-empty fruit stand stocked with rotten
oranges, the cheating butcher selling steaks under the counter, the
abrasive post-office clerk who just would not produce the right
rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think you are doing here, huh _ disperse!''
shouted one of the men who walked around dressed in communist
police uniforms. ``Public gathering is illegal. Don't you know
anything?'' he yelled, waving his truncheon at the laughing crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bananas?'' the fruit seller asked. ``No, comrade, try
tomorrow. Here, why don't you get these Cuban oranges instead?'' He
slapped one tiny moldy orange on the scale, pushing it down with
the other hand. ``That's a pound and a half, 15 Czechoslovak
crowns, please.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the next stand, a military instructor showed people how to
wear their gas masks and to protect themselves against attack by
Western imperialists.
</P>
<P>
   At another booth, visitors crowded around the meat shop, empty
except for a pig's head sitting next to a plaster bust of Klement
Gottwald, Czechoslovakia's first communist president and an ardent
Stalinist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death to Gottwald!'' one customer shouted merrily. The butcher
looked around in mock horror and said in a hushed voice: ``Out of
my store! I don't know you, I never heard you. Out. Out!''
</P>
<P>
   At the next booth, an office, visitors could pick up an
application for Communist Party membership or fill out a request
for hard currency, should they dare to ask for permission to travel
to a non-socialist country. A pale clerk with a red tie was
stamping the forms next to a paper plate with cigarette ashes and
the remains of a hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Red was everywhere. There were red posters, red Soviet flags,
red jackets on books with titles like ``The Leading Role of the
Communist Party in the Modern Czechoslovak Socialist State'' and,
of course, the red star on the hats of police and People's Militia
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internationale'' and other hits of the socialist era
sounded in the background, repeatedly interrupted by two girls
representing Socialist Youth reciting celebratory poems about the
Soviet Union, workers and the brave soldiers who fearlessly
defended beautiful socialist Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' said Jan Halouska, 18, a student from Prague.
``It reminded me how we used to have to march in those gas masks at
school. It's good fun now, but when I remember those days when I
was a kid it gives me goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors said people should be reminded more often of the
absurdity of the previous regime, so they would cherish freedom
more.
</P>
<P>
   Bibiana Klimesova, 60, from the eastern town of Pardubice, said
similar shows should be organized in every town and village. If
people remembered the past, they wouldn't vote for the communists
now, she said, referring to the recently increased support for the
Communist Party in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Czechs outside Prague got a dose of the old regime as well.
Czech TV's second channel broadcast a 24-hour compilation of old
socialist programs, so viewers could tune in to ``Festival of
Political Songs,'' ``Let's Learn Russian'' and a television movie
called ``A Skirt, but a Green One,'' about a talented secondary
school student who gave up her boyfriend and opposed her parents to
be able to attend a military university.
</P>
<P>
   Gaps between shows were often bridged with still shots of
wallpaper patterned with playful kittens or an image of the Prague
Castle.
</P>
<P>
   The program was also shown in Slovakia, the country that formed
half of Czechoslovakia under communism before it split peacefully
on Jan. 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at these programs again, I wondered how I could
ever have watched them without throwing up,'' said Fero Fenic, the
creator of the television project. ``We tend to idealize those
times now and keep forgetting what they were really like.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Watching the smiling crowds pouring into the Museum of
Totalitarianism, its main organizer, Jan Bubenik, said, ``For me,
it's a look through a vale of tears. We can laugh now, but it sure
wasn't funny 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
