<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-RUMORS-NYT &LR;      11-21 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RUMORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN DISCOUNTS REPORTS OF WHISPERING CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said Sunday that he was
not personally aware of any whispering campaign by fellow senators
to suggest that his war experience in Vietnam had left him too
emotionally unstable to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., the national co-chairman of
McCain's bid for the Republican presidential nomination, has said
that such an effort is clearly under way, McCain said he had no
real evidence of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no direct information except hearsay that this kind of
thing is going on,'' McCain said in an interview with the
television journalist Bob Schieffer on the CBS News program ``Face
the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain repeatedly sought to make light of the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Bob, you have to be half nuts to run for
president,'' McCain said. ``So I accept the charge. I don't know
anything about it. Of course, you hear rumors, you hear things that
are said, you hear quotes in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm sorry this has happened. I have many close and dear
friends in the Senate, and people who I have known and served with
for many years, who I'm sure spring to my defense regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer noted that the newspaper columnist Elizabeth Drew had
identified several Senate Republicans, including supporters of Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, who she maintained were spreading the
rumors about McCain. Those senators have denied the contention.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said, ``I take them at their word, and there's no reason
for me not to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, McCain has surged in polls of voters
in New Hampshire, which has the first Republican presidential
primary. Some surveys put McCain and Bush, the Republican
front-runner, in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain has also been dogged by questions from reporters
about whether he has a problem with his temper. McCain has accused
the Bush campaign of promoting those inquiries, a charge that
Bush's aides emphatically denied.
</P>
<P>
   Some of McCain's associates have said that his opponents were
trying to insinuate that the isolation and torture that McCain
endured as a prisoner of war had left permanent psychological
scars.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer asked McCain whether there was anything in his
background that disqualified him ``from being president, in a
psychological sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Bob,'' McCain replied. ``And the fact is that I'm a far
better man for having had the experience that I had. I learned the
meaning of friendship, and comradeship and love and compassion, and
learned many of my own failings, which continue to this day.''
McCain said that he would release his medical records soon but that
the process was being slowed by the sheer volume of documents, a
legacy of the torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far we've got about 350 pages,'' McCain said. ``It's an
orthopedic surgeon's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's relationship with fellow Republicans has occasionally
been a tense one, strained by his maverick positions on such issues
as overhauling campaign finance laws, which he strongly supports.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that on Sunday, he said, ``I have excellent
relationships with most people on both sides of the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that, like Bush, he believed that most American
financial aid to Russia should be suspended until Russia ceases its
attacks on the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said he shared Bush's opposition to gay adoption and
gay marriage. But he said he had met with a gay Republican group _
something Bush has not done _ because ``We are an inclusive party,
and we should maintain the principles of Abraham Lincoln.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
