<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWDEN DRIVES A BUS WITH ONE STOP TO GO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ He sat on a bench in the front of the locker
room looking every bit of his 70 years. Sweat trailed down the side
of Bobby Bowden's face. Half dressed kids 50 years younger talked
to the television cameras, baby-faced trainers gathered up soaked
uniforms from the floor while men and women toting notebooks
stepped around him.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State coach had his arms crossed and had the
perfectly implacable look of a retiree waiting at a bus stop
beneath a palm tree en route to whiling away an afternoon. For 34
seasons, Bowden has found a post-game perch to wait for ``his
boys'' to dress and hit the bus.
</P>
<P>
   On 303 occasions, the coach has been pretty satisfied waiting on
his team, knowing they played well enough to win another game. On
this Saturday night, Bowden's Seminoles dispatched Florida, 30-23,
on the Gators' Florida Field in front of a record bloodthirsty
crowd of 85,747.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rivalry game between two schools located two hours
apart. It is a game that contrasts personalities and generations:
the mercurial Steve Spurrier, a star quarterback and 1966 Heisman
winner at Florida, versus the country cool Bowden who, in his
telling combines feed-store wisdom with tactical maneuvers learned
from the great military generals of his boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a game that for the fifth time in seven years decided
which team got to play for college football's national title. For
the second year in a row, it is the 'Noles who are now 11-0 and
have been ranked No. 1 since before the season kicked off.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that the bus Bowden is now waiting for will
pull up to the New Orleans Superdome on Jan. 4 so the Seminoles can
play in the Sugar Bowl and win the coach his second national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty darn special,'' said Bowden from his bench, where
he was happy to talk to anybody who wanted to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in Bowden's 24 seasons at Florida State, the Seminoles
have finished the regular season undefeated only to lose bowl games
and the championship: in 1979 against Oklahoma in the Orange Bowl
and in 1996 against the Gators in the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting to those games with a perfect record is an
achievement. Ask 72-year-old Joe Paterno, whose Penn State Nittany
Lions, after holding the No. 2 ranking for nine weeks, have lost
three in a row. Or the third year coach at Notre Dame, Bob Davie,
whose team won't even play in the postseason after losing to Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps unlike any previous season, Bowden desperately wants
to finish this one with victory No. 304 and a championship. For
one, he is the only coach at his own dinner table that has never
won them all. Son Tommy, now the coach at Clemson, went 12-0 last
year with Tulane. Son Terry, now a television analyst, finished
11-0 at Auburn in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm proud of them, but dadgum, I'd like to get me one of
those,'' said Bowden, repeating one of his stock answers.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason is that Bowden believes this is the best team he
has ever coached. Back in August, before a down was played, he said
as much, then listed the reasons. ``Forget the 20 or 25 NFL
prospects everyone likes to point to,'' Bowden said. ``Sure we are
talented, but this is a mature team. We got Chris Weinke _ a
27-year-old quarterback. I'd like one of those every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got Pete Warrick _ a senior who is going to graduate and
who can do anything on the football field. We got old Sebastian
Janikowski kicking for us and he's not only good, you can't rattle
him. I'd be disappointed if we didn't win them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Florida on Saturday, the coaches' preseason assessment
unfolded like he called it. Weinke threw an interception that was
returned for a touchdown to give Florida a 16-13 lead, but then
Weinke responded by driving the Seminoles the length of the field
for a tying field goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was one kicked by Janikowski from 54 yards, his third of the
day. And Warrick, who played with thunderous reminders about his
misdemeanor guilty plea and two-game suspension for taking deeply
discounted clothes, never let the crowd at The Swamp get to him. He
caught nine passes for 90-yards and ran for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But the best team of Bowden's coaching career has also tested
him _ on the field with tentative efforts against Georgia Tech and
Clemson, off it with the Warrick episode, as well as the drug
possession arrest of defensive back Tay Cody. To a fault, Bowden is
unwaveringly loyal to his players.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is generally well thought of among his peers, though he
has absorbed his share of criticism. Early this season, for
example, in the middle of the Warrick and Cody affairs, Virginia
coach George Welsh icily observed that the wheels of justice grind
slowly, if at all, in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the Florida State players recognize that this
has been a difficult season for their coach. In the locker room
Saturday night, linebacker Brian Allen indicated that winning the
Sugar Bowl went beyond fulfilling their own dreams of a national
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some wonderful things happen this season along with
some not so wonderful things,'' Allen said. ``The bad things are
our fault. We owe coach Bowden something better.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in front of the locker room, Bowden brushed off such talk.
His boys were almost dressed and it was almost time to go. He was
reminded again of what Spurrier had said in his post-game
conference. That Florida State ``wasn't as good as it used to be.''
The old coach suddenly looked younger than his 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're undefeated,'' he said smiling. ``He ain't.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
