<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOO     11-21 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTING WAR SCHOOL FOR FOREIGNERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass.)  (ART ADV:  Photos  are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT BENNING, Ga. _ In a small classroom inside a pink building
on this historic Army post, Maj. Pablo Friedrich is learning the
art of war.
</P>
<P>
   A bearish marine from Colombia, he will spend nine weeks here
studying tactical manuals translated into Spanish from the books
used by American officers. Then he will return home as deputy
commander of a marine battalion in Cartagena, rejoining Colombia's
civil war against guerrillas and drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he returns as a more professional soldier infused with
American military values or as one trained to wage a more efficient
war of repression is the question at the heart of a roiling
national debate over this training center, the Army's School of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, thousands of protesters led by a Roman
Catholic priest gathered at Fort Benning's main gate just outside
Columbus for the annual protest to demand the closing of the
school, the nation's main training center for Latin American
military and police officers for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a funereal procession of 3,100 protesters marched onto
the post, led by several dozen dressed in black robes and white
masks and carrying wooden coffins they said represented those
killed by graduates of the school. In a peaceful, carefully
choreographed confrontation, the Army stopped them after nearly a
mile, put them on buses and drove them off the post. Fifty-four
protesters were detained and given citations barring them from Fort
Benning for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't teach democracy anywhere by training the military,''
said Joe Morton, a white-haired 63-year-old professor at Goucher
College in Baltimore, moments before he boarded a bus at the post.
``Students who come here are going to go back to their countries
and shoot people like us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Secretary of the Army Louis Caldera announced plans
to make significant changes to the school's curriculum in hopes of
muting growing opposition, especially in Congress, which nearly
voted to close the school this fall. If the protests were an
indication, though, the plans failed to win over the most fervent
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to transform this school,'' the Rev. Roy L.
Bourgeois, the priest who has organized the opposition, told the
protesters on Saturday. ``We are here _ and we need to make this
clear _ to close this school.''
</P>
<P>
   But a visit to the school and the protests suggests that this
has become a debate about how the United States will work with
Central and South American militaries after the tumultuous,
sometimes violent engagement of the past, when Washington
overlooked abuses in the name of fighting leftist insurgencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has become an abstraction to the people out
there,'' the school's commandant, Col. Glenn R. Weidner, said on
Friday, as the first protesters assembled at Fort Benning's main
gate.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera and other officials have strongly defended the school
and its mission, which they say is to promote modern, professional
militaries that respect democracy and human rights. Caldera said
the changes would enhance that, training Latin American officers to
cope with today's problems, from drug trafficking to natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are legitimate security interests that they have,''
Caldera said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said the school's critics are ``willfully ignorant,''
slurring the reputation of the Army with accusations that the
school has encouraged violence against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't teach American soldiers to violate human rights,''
Caldera said, ``and we don't teach soldiers of any foreign
countries to violate human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has become so polarizing, the oratory so extreme,
that it overshadows the teaching that actually goes on inside the
school, located in the old headquarters of the Army's Infantry
School, an elegant three-story building on manicured grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Panama in 1946 and relocated here in 1984, the school
still offers purely military courses in skills like basic combat
and flying helicopters. But since the end of the Cold War, its
focus has shifted. Its catalog now includes courses on computers,
medical care and more mundane matters of organizing a professional
military. Students today spend more time in the classroom than on
Fort Benning's firing ranges.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich, whose father was a German U-boat sailor who
immigrated to Colombia after World War II, arrived with four
captains from his country and another from Mexico for a course on
how to plan a defense against a hypothetical invasion. Consulting
Army manuals and scrawling with markers on maps and charts tacked
to the wall, they plotted each step of the ``battle'' with
occasional nudging from their Army instructor, Maj. Jaime F.
Llinet.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich said the course was valuable, exposing him to the
latest in American war tactics. ``We believe it is the most
advanced doctrine in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its history, the school has trained 61,000 students from 23
countries. Today, only students from Cuba, Nicaragua and Haiti are
ineligible. The State Department pays students' expenses and
screens applicants for accusations of abuses. The school trains
about 800 students a year in courses that last from two weeks to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   In noncombat classes, as many as a third of the students are
civilians, like Maria Gonzalez Vila, a lawyer with Uruguay's
Ministry of Defense. She just completed a five-week course called
Resource Management. Under Caldera's plan, the school would
increase slots for civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Army has also added training on human
rights. The busiest lecturer on the staff of 288 is the
soft-spoken, erudite Army lawyer who teaches international
humanitarian law, Maj. Antonio Raimondo.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who come for as little as two weeks receive eight
hours of lessons on human rights. The officers who attend the
yearlong ``Command and General Staff Course'' sit through 40 hours.
There is also an annual ``Human Rights Week,'' which in February
will include a case study of the American massacre at My Lai during
the Vietnam War and a tour of Andersonville, the notorious
Confederate prison camp, whose commander was the only officer
hanged for war crimes after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Weidner said the graduates who went on to commit abuses were the
exceptions. By the opponents' own count, he said, only 300 to 500
of the school's 61,000 students have been linked to atrocities, in
some cases years after they attended short courses. Those few, he
added, are the ones who did not learn the lessons taught here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel betrayed by them,'' Weidner said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics view the emphasis on human rights _ like the proposed
changes _ as an obfuscation. The school's core is and will be
military training, they say, perpetuating the militaries'
disproportionate role in Central and South American democracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the reform line before,'' said Heather A. Dean, a
protest organizer. ``And while they have made some reforms, the
bread and butter is still combat training.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The protests at Fort Benning began 10 years ago with only a
handful of opponents, led by Bourgeois, a Navy veteran who has been
deeply involved in Latin American causes since serving as a
missionary in Bolivia in the 1970s. Since then the protests have
grown, even as the crimes committed by the school's graduates
recede into the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for them to say when it is time to forgive,''
Bourgeois said of the Army's insistence that the school has moved
on from its Cold War role.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 5,000 people attended the November protest.
This year, the Columbus police estimated that there were 8,000, the
largest gathering of people in the city since it played host to
women's softball in the 1996 Olympics. The protest has become such
an event that the city's tourism bureau this year helped arrange
hotel accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   To the school's instructors, the placards depicting blood and
graves and invariably referring to the ``School of the Assassins''
have become uncomfortably personal attacks. Several singled out
remarks by a leading congressional critic, Rep. Joe Moakley,
D-Mass., who last week dismissed the planned changes as ``putting
perfume on a toxic dump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is a trash dump, then I'm the trash,'' said Llinet,
the instructor. A 19-year veteran, he pointed defiantly,
defensively to a patch on his shoulder that he earned for serving
in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an assassin,'' he added. ``I'm a good old Army guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Llinet, who served as a military trainer in Venezuela, said he
agreed with some of the protesters' underlying concerns. He spoke
of ``social injustice'' in Latin America, particularly the economic
disparities that leave the poor mired in hardship and the elite,
often including the militaries, in control.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the school's training served a valuable purpose by
promoting regional stability, encouraging democracy and minimizing
the possibility of American military intervention, the very thing
the protesters oppose most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we don't have to send American forces to Latin America
because of the students who came here,'' he said. ``If we close the
school, maybe we're going to have to go back to the interventionist
policies of Teddy Roosevelt, because when there is a security
threat in Latin America, you know we're going to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
