<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITTING ENDING FOR A FOUL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four quarters as a metaphor for 11 games: Riddled
by injuries and lacking leadership, the UCLA Bruins on Saturday
sputtered through the last leg of a forgettable trip.
</P>
<P>
   A season that began with one of the most embarrassing events in
school history (the handicapped-parking scandal) ended with the
first loss to USC in nine years. Talk about a sandwich with bad
meat and rotten bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sick feeling,'' Bruins senior safety Joey Strycula,
his words echoing through a fast-emptying locker room after UCLA's
17-7 loss to USC. ``Things just didn't go our way. Last year, the
ball bounced our way. This year, it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The errant call that gave USC the clinching touchdown was a
fitting end to the Bruins' lost season. Perhaps it was simply the
scales tipping to USC for the first time since 1990. More likely,
it was the last, unforgiving act of cosmic justice for a team that
had 11 players charged with exploiting the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to Saturday's defeat than a blown touchdown
call, just as there was more to the season than humiliating
headlines and two-game suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a difficult season for all of us,'' senior receiver
Danny Farmer said. ``It started last year with (All-American left
tackle) Kris Farris leaving, then the handicapped parking. A lot of
things didn't go our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries and inexperience at quarterback and on the
offensive line, the Bruins struggled all season to sustain drives
and score points. They never got easy touchdowns, never gave their
defense a chance to rest, never gave the opponent a reason to fret.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was no different. The Bruins couldn't run (45 yards),
they couldn't block and they couldn't catch against a stingy USC
defense. They had three plays longer than 30 yards and they
committed five turnovers _ three inside USC's 10 yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries, suspensions and inexperience, the defense
spent the season on the brink. It played well against Oregon and
Washington, poorly against Stanford, Oregon State and Arizona. The
Bruins were fundamentally better than last year but less talented.
They got no help from the offense, they got little help from the
senior class and they never recovered from the absence of starting
cornerbacks Jason Bell, who missed nine games because of a painful
heel, and Marques Anderson, who was suspended for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was no different. The Bruins played hard but couldn't
stuff USC's self-destructing attack. They yielded 214 rushing yards
and would have allowed more than 17 points if not for the Trojans'
red-zone ineptitude. UCLA's third-down defense, last in the
Pacific-10, was porous once again: USC converted nine of 22
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It was a predictable performance. After an anguishing season and
an emotional victory over Washington the previous week, the Bruins
simply didn't have the manpower, much less the firepower, to keep
their city-series winning streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't one thing, it was a little bit of everything,''
defensive end Kenyon Coleman said. ``It's been happening all year,
and because it's a lot of little things, it's hard to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Even against USC. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
