<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN OCCUPIED CHECHNYA, ORDER WITHOUT ALLEGIANCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add photo note)   (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia _ As the Russian army closes in on Chechnya's
besieged capital, Grozny, it is using a fresh strategy: promising
Chechens that their bedraggled towns will be spared a relentless
bombardment if they surrender to Russian forces, then attempting to
secure loyalty by restoring services like gas and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But this month's capture of Gudermes, Chechnya's bleak but
strategically important second largest city, shows it is one thing
to scare Chechen civilians into submission, and quite another to
win their allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   City residents wander muddy streets past decaying buildings,
which are still pockmarked from the shells and bullets of
Chechnya's 1994-96 war. Many seem exhausted, and frustrated that
Islamic militants who are based in this breakaway Caucasus region
reignited the fighting by invading neighboring Dagestan in August.
Nevertheless, these people view the Russians as an occupying Army.
</P>
<P>
   As the clap of Russian artillery fire rumbled through the hills
on Gudermes' outskirts, Sergei Kuznetsov, a 19-year-old Russian
private, talked about the problem that his army faces in trying to
pacify Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the war is necessary to fight the terrorists,'' he said.
``But sometimes I don't know what we are doing. During the day, the
people in Gudermes smile at us and bring us goodies. But at night,
they are out there shooting at us. I don't know who we are
protecting from whom.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager to show that they are bringing stability to Chechnya,
Russian authorities took a first group of foreign correspondents to
Gudermes and to meet some of the soldiers who seized the city on
Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The visit revealed the high stakes at play in this war, which
has increasingly infuriated Western donors and led to sharp
exchanges last week at a 54-nation European security conference.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading the Chechens that a Russian occupation offers the
best hope for a peaceful life is central to the military's strategy
of blunting Western criticism and maintaining its hold on Chechnya.
That way, the military can repatriate the 200,000 refugees who have
fled and discourage further guerrilla warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours spent in Gudermes, a city that appears to have
survived its capture largely intact, suggest that winning over the
Chechens will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Germans occupied the Soviet Union, the Soviets called
them `the fascists,''' said Alisof Kolymanovich, a 44-year-old
former tractor operator. ``Well, we call the Russians, `the
fascists.' If you could talk to everyone in the villages you would
see that 70 percent are against them being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Splayed across the hillsides outside the city, Russia's 247th
regiment laid down the withering artillery fire that helped the
army seize Gudermes and to chase militants out of several nearby
villages. The unit's affable commander, Yuri P. Em, an ethnic
Korean, is an earnest spokesman for the Russian cause.
</P>
<P>
   He noted proudly that Gudermes fell without much of a fight.
Russian forces blockaded the city for two weeks and pounded its
outskirts with artillery and rockets.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chechen fighters fled, the city's leaders, including
Sulima Yamadaev, a Chechen field commander, negotiated an agreement
to turn the city over to the Russians, the colonel said. It is the
sort of conquest the Russian military would dearly like to repeat
as it drives toward Grozny, the stronghold of many rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are tired of war,'' Em said. ``We have more of
a dialogue with the people than during the last war and are getting
good results.''
</P>
<P>
   But the militants have clearly not given up the fight. Near
Gudermes, the constant boom of Russian artillery and Grad rockets
echoed in the distance. The local fighters are said to have taken
up positions in Argun, some 20 miles from here, and in Grozny, 30
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya still has verdant fields and hills. But the countryside
is battle terrain, too: Its land is scarred by trenchlines,
checkpoints of sandbags and bricks and the treadmarks of armored
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Em said his men's morale was high. They have been told the war
will be over soon and that they will receive as much as $1,000 a
month, a small fortune for a Russian soldier.
</P>
<P>
   But the soldiers said they have not received any money yet. A
soldier earns 810 rubles ($32) a day in combat and 20 rubles ($4) a
day otherwise, and none seemed to know how much of their service
will qualify for combat pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not tell us much,'' said Vladimir N. Degtyaryov, 20,
as leaned against his howitzer. ``They give us two orders: `shoot'
or `stand down.' Then we have a lunch break and shoot again. They
don't tell us where we are going or what we are going to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the soldiers appear to be the hardened veterans Russian
authorities have said they are sending into Chechnya. Many are 19
or 20 years old, and have never seen combat before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the army for 15 months, serving quietly in Stavropol
and then one night we were mobilized and sent here,'' said
Kuznetsov, the 19-year-old private. ``But we have had three months
of shooting and shooting. I really want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gudermes is an eerie, edgy place, peopled by women, children and
gaunt men who look much older than their years.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities are making a visible effort to restore some
semblance of a normal existence, including schools and medical
services.
</P>
<P>
   Gas service _ important to survive the winter _ was restored on
Friday. And Anatoly B. Chubais, the former Kremlin aide who heads
Russia's electrical monopoly, swooped through the city Sunday to
announce that electrical power would also be supplied soon.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chubais who turned off the power when the Russian
military campaign began in September, saying that the impoverished
Chechens had not paid their bills.
</P>
<P>
   As Russian armored personnel carriers prowled the streets and
helicopters fluttered overhead, residents gathered in the city
center to greet Chubais and Nikolay Koshman, the Russian
government's representative in Chechnya _ and to talk to the
journalists brought in for the event.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd mingled peacefully, if unenthusiastically, with the
Russian troops who patrol with AK-47s and maintain strict control,
imposing an evening curfew and requiring Chechens to queue up for
permits each time they want to pass through checkpoints on the
city's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   In these contacts with lower-level soldiers, enmity can surface,
some residents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senior officers understand everything,'' said Osman
Chukayev, a 46-year-old construction engineer. ``But some of the
soldiers are different. I can show a pass from a colonel at a
checkpoint and they might say, `You can't come through. I don't
care who signed it.' And at night some of the soldiers start
shooting. They must be drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   A 24-year-old construction worker who gave his name only as Musa
was more menacing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Russian troops walk around in groups of five and
they don't have any problems,'' he said. ``But as things become
more normal, they'll start walking around in pairs. Then people
here will deal with them and they will be quietly taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Others insisted they were not looking for any more trouble. They
are weary of the kidnappings that have made Chechnya a largely
lawless and unsafe place for outsiders since the last war ended in
1996, leaving the region's status unsettled, and are glad that
Gudermes, at least for now, is no longer a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel myself a citizen of Russia,'' said Larisa
Bashayeva, a spirited 29-year-old woman. ``My relatives were killed
by Russian planes. But three years ago there was something to fight
for. Now there is nothing left. Only the religious fanatics are
going to fight this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
