<HEADLINE>
TITANS DEFEAT STEELERS, 16-10 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ There were 3 minutes 15 seconds left, the
Pittsburgh Steelers had the ball at their 9-yard line and trailed
the Tennessee Titans by 16-10 at Adelphia Stadium Sunday.
Pittsburgh, with no timeouts remaining, was a 91-yard drive away
from seven points to win it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Steelers might as well have been 91 million miles away.
</P>
<P>
   A Kordell Stewart pass for 3 yards. An incomplete pass. A pass
for 9 yards and a first down. A sack by rookie end Jevon Kearse for
a 2-yard loss. And then an interception by defensive end Kenny
Holmes. Five plays. The Steelers moved from their 9 to their 19 and
crashed. Game over. No thrilling drive, no drama, no comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh offense seemed ill equipped to provide it. It was
smacked silly for most of the afternoon by the Tennessee defense in
the Titans' victory, which pushed them to 8-2 and dropped
Pittsburgh to 5-5. Tennessee controlled the one-on-one battles,
stopped running back Jerome Bettis, made Stewart look troubled on
the game's biggest plays and made Pittsburgh look like a shaky team
in danger of not making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make the big plays when we needed to and we put
ourselves in a hole on third and second downs,'' said Bettis, who
rushed for 88 yards, including 35 on one early first-quarter run.
``They were pretty tough. The bottom line is the team over in the
other locker room outplayed us. It's frustrating. We have to keep
scratching and get some wins. We can run the table, and we've got
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh scored a touchdown on its first possession and added
a field goal with seven minutes left in the game. In between, the
offense labored. This was Pittsburgh's fifth game in which it
scored 17 or fewer points. And this loss comes on the heels of its
embarrassing defeat last week at home to the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee scored touchdowns on its first two drives _
quarterback Steve McNair ran for 2 and 3 yards _ and that proved
enough to handle the Steelers and to continue the Titans' amazing
streak. They have won 12 consecutive division games. Tennessee's
last loss in the AFC Central was on Sept. 27, 1998, to
Jacksonville. Sunday's victory was also the franchise's fourth
straight over Pittsburgh, the first time it has accomplished that
since this series began in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting closer,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher said. ``We
talked about playing in different phases and I saw improvement in
every area from this team today. We're in a situation where we just
have to keep going. I saw a lot of good things out there today.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw Tennessee jump ahead by 14-7 at halftime and then gain a
safety in the third quarter to lead by 16-7. McNair, only a few
weeks removed from back surgery, took punishing licks on his
scoring runs but continued to play efficiently. Safety Marcus
Robertson made 11 tackles and played a tenacious last line of
defense. Kearse continued to create chaos for the Steelers'
offense. The Titans' defense made five sacks, their offense did not
allow one and their special teams allowed only 4 yards on returns.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans are streaking. The Steelers are sinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's telling us, `You guys don't have this, you guys
don't have that,' when in actuality we have as much talent as
anybody else,'' Pittsburgh linebacker Levon Kirkland said. ``We're
out there with a team who hasn't lost but two games. They are a
top-ranked team in the AFC and we stuck right with them to the very
end. We've just been hearing that we can't do it for so long and
believing the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win all six to close. We can do that and be in
the thick of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Not without scoring more points. Pittsburgh needs its offense to
make more timely, game-swinging plays. It needs fewer penalties (11
Sunday), and a lot of breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want guys thinking that the season is over,
because we're not losers,'' Pittsburgh safety Lee Flowers said.
``We have too much talent to be losers. We did not believe that
we'd be in this situation in the preseason. We thought we'd be a
lot better off. We have two options: we can either give up the rest
of our games or come out and play with some pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride is not the issue. It's points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to come in and win with their defense,''
Titans running back Eddie George said. ``But balance wins in this
league.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
