<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: SPREWELL PLAYS HIS ROLE TO PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The profanity tumbled from his mouth
unfailingly, until the final horn blared and his team had won. Some
of it was tossed in the direction of belligerent courtside fans,
some at the players assigned to guard him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out there,'' said Antawn Jamison, the Golden State
Warriors forward. ``I haven't seen anyone go off like that in a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell, the mercurial New York Knicks guard, was less
a basketball player on Saturday night than he was a vulgar
talk-show guest, summoned to boost sagging ratings. The Arena in
Oakland swelled with people who either loved him or loathed him and
felt nothing in between.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's play was all over the map, but he deposited a
malicious dunk in the fourth quarter of the Knicks' 86-79 victory
over the Warriors _ his first game against the coach he choked two
years ago and the franchise he contends let him down.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was asked, after scoring 14 points but missing 11 of 17
shots and swearing up a storm, whether he thought he had behaved
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I had fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell avoided the glance of P.J. Carlesimo, his former coach.
He glared into the stands and toward the Warriors' bench after each
shot he made. He was good in his role. Very good.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Dennis Rodman nor Bill Laimbeer _ not even a youthful
Jesse Ventura _ could have played the villain this convincingly.
Spewing vulgarities one moment, charming reporters the next, one of
the N.B. A's best-known players kept climbing the charts less than
a year after his exile from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's detractors thought he showed no class by not making
up publicly with Carlesimo, by showing up everyone in the building.
His supporters equated the Knicks' victory with vindication for all
the supposed emotional anguish he had been through. They hollered
for him and against him.
</P>
<P>
   And they watched. They all watched.
</P>
<P>
   In Woody Allen's movie ``Celebrity,'' the most telling and
amusing scene involves a Jerry Springeresque free-for-all. Onstage,
white skinheads and black activists angrily collide. Backstage, in
the privacy of the green room, the warring factions politely
discuss their preferences in bagels _ proving that it is all about
sweeps week.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell comes from a New York director's cut, but not the one
you might think. He is less one of Spike Lee's defiant and
persecuted black men than he is straight out of Allen's
imagination: a Zelig willing to play whatever role society gives
him.
</P>
<P>
   There were two defining moments of Saturday's game: Sprewell
having his shot and his body sent to the floor by Warriors center
Adonal Foyle, and Sprewell throwing down that fourth-quarter dunk
and posing in front of the Golden State bench.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell caused so many visceral reactions. He exchanged taunts
with fans and trash-talked with players; he pounded his chest,
flexed his torso, scowled and swore for nearly two hours. Even an
unassuming Warriors rookie was taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took it a little bit too far,'' Damon Jones said. ``It's OK
to come out and play hard and let guys know you're in the building.
But I think he could have tuned it down. My opinion means nothing.
But personally, I would have liked to see him come out and shake
P.J.'s hand and show a little bit more class out on the floor. Cut
down the antics and play basketball. His antics seem to take a
little bit off his game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not only about the game for Sprewell. All week, he acted
like an emotionally wounded kid whose team had been run off the
court, vowing revenge. He came back with a new and more talented
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston knocked down jumpers; Chris Dudley and Marcus
Camby put back missed shots. As the Knicks built a 20-point
first-half lead over an inferior team, Sprewell was not by himself
against the world anymore. He pumped his fist at the end, his
romanticized retribution on the playground complete.
</P>
<P>
   He had won, and all that many of his peers could do was shake
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all gets old after a while,'' said Terry Cummings, the
38-year-old Warrior who jawed with Sprewell at one juncture. ``You
got to get past that. I even said that to him on the floor. It
can't be fun when you're that angry. You can't do what you love to
do, and that's just to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what Sprewell thought of his advice. ``He said he
was all right,'' Cummings said with a rueful smile. The veteran
laughed at the sound of his own words, the way a man laughs when he
knows someone is unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   Home or away, no matter where he plays, Spree is on Broadway now
_ an entertainer apart from the famous franchise for which he
plays. He is becoming Rodman, minus the tattoos and with many more
skills. A celebrity, waiting in the green room to rescue sagging
ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
