<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VOTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE STRUGGLE FOR THE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Nov. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Now that Congress has adjourned, and the presidential campaign
is heating up, it is worth noting some shifts in voter attitudes.
These adjustments do not seem obvious to Republican congressional
leaders in Washington. They remain wedded to their anti-government
approach of tax cuts above all. They are also at a low ebb in
public confidence, according to a spate of recent polls. These
surveys affirm the conventional wisdom that national elections are
in the main a battle for control of the political center. But they
also show that the center contains new combinations of voters whose
loyalties are not firmly tied to either party.
</P>
<P>
   The polls demonstrate that while Americans are wary of
government, they no longer rage over its excesses. Good times are
surely the driving force behind the current mood and a general
impulse toward generosity and social concern. The word ``liberal''
is still one that many voters resist, but the automatic opposition
to government intervention in the lives of Americans espoused by
Ronald Reagan and central to the strategy of Newt Gingrich and Tom
DeLay appears to have run its course, even among some
self-identified Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A recent comprehensive voter survey by the Pew Research Center
shows that a newly strengthened bloc of Republicans, about a third
of the party, leans toward more government involvement in the
environment, education, health and helping the poor. In fact, even
many ``populist'' Republicans who care about social issues like
abortion and school prayer are not necessarily anti-government in
other areas that affect the middle class. That helps explain why
Gary Bauer, the Christian-right candidate, favors more regulation
of health maintenance organizations. It also helps explain why Gov.
George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain, the leading Republican
presidential contenders, are doing little to espouse the 1980s
Republican agenda still pushed by Trent Lott, the Senate majority
leader, and House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds advantageous for the Democrats, but their claim to a
redefined center is not automatic. According to the Pew survey,
Gore is falling short among conservative Democrats turned off by
President Clinton's personal behavior. These are the old so-called
Reagan Democrats, many of them religious family people won back by
the president in the last two elections. But now they are upset
about the president's behavior and not convinced that Gore shares
their concerns. Bill Bradley does about as well as Gore against
Bush, but he also is having trouble winning support among Reagan
Democrats. His apparent strategy of running to the left of the vice
president on some issues could hurt rather than help him on that
score.
</P>
<P>
   This attitudinal unrest is working against congressional
incumbents in both parties. For all this era's prosperity and
contentment, voters are oddly unhappy with the posturing of their
leaders in Washington. After being turned off by the impeachment
scandals and the pummeling that both sides carried out one year
ago, the voters seem to have found the fiscal confrontations of the
last year equally unedifying. As the campaign accelerates, they
seem to want moderation in political approach and personal conduct
worthy of respect. The candidates who embody these qualities seem
more likely to succeed than at any time in the recent past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      11-21 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
In early August, everything seemed right at Texas A&AMP;M. Nearly
everyone was picking the Aggies to repeat as the Big 12 South
champions. In some quarters, there was talk of a possible run at a
national title.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aggies coach R.C. Slocum, always the realist, inserted this note
of caution.
</P>
<P>
   Do not, Slocum warned, focus only on the 16 starters the Aggies
were returning from their 11-3 season. Do not, he said, overlook
what the Aggies lost.
</P>
<P>
   As the season unfolded and unraveled, it was clear the Aggies
missed the likes of linebackers Dat Nguyen and Warrick Holdman,
safety Rich Coady, tight ends Dan Campbell and Derrick Spiller and
guards Cameron Spikes and Rex Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   On the field and off, those Aggies were the heart and soul of
the team that upset Nebraska and Kansas State on the way to the Big
12 championship. This year, the lack of leadership seemed to be one
of the major problems that prevented Texas A&AMP;M from capturing a
third straight Big 12 South title.
</P>
<P>
   During times of adversity, leaders are expected to step forward
and lead. It's unlikely many college teams have faced the sort of
adversity the Aggies will when they play at Kyle Field on Friday.
The memory of the Aggie Bonfire collapse and the death of 11
classmates and a former student remains fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the fact the game is between archrivals, it didn't
figure to have much meaning this year. The Longhorns already have
locked up the Big 12 South title. But now the Aggies, who endured
criticism that they were too soft after losses at Texas Tech,
Oklahoma and Nebraska, get a final chance to show their resolve
and, at the same time, honor the memory of their deceased brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people gave their lives to help build a bonfire to
support us,'' said A&AMP;M quarterback Randy McCown. ``We want to match
that effort when we go out on the field. Those people have
supported us so many years, the biggest thing we could give back to
them is a victory over Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown is a senior who stands for what is good about being an
Aggie. He tried his best this season to make this his team. He
played through a painful shoulder separation and poured his
intelligence, emotions, ability and toughness into an attempt to
shore up the Aggies when the season went south in October.
</P>
<P>
   The words of caution spoken by Slocum as early as the Big 12
media gathering in early August began looking prescient even as the
Aggies were winning their three non-conference games. Even when
healthy, their offensive line lacked the experience and depth of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   When left tackle Shea Holder suffered a season-ending knee
injury in the third game of the season, a series of reserves
shifting around the line eventually limited the Aggies' ability to
run the football.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that, there were red flags about the Texas A&AMP;M
offense. The Aggies have had a season-long inability to score in
the first quarter _ they didn't manage an offensive touchdown in
the opening 15 minutes until Game 10 against Missouri. They
couldn't punch the ball into the end zone once inside the red zone,
too often relying on field goals.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to diversify their offense by throwing more, the
Aggies somehow lost the ability to run the ball _ a traditional
staple in their attack. Not until the 10th game of the season did
an Aggies back gain more than 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum's coaching also came under attack. In a 21-19 loss at
Texas Tech on Oct. 4, the Aggies seemed unprepared to stop Red
Raiders running back Sammy Morris, who came out of dry dock and
rushed for more than 100 yards. After that lackluster loss, the
national championship dreams were history.
</P>
<P>
   Home victories over hapless Baylor and Kansas appeared to right
the ship, but the next three weeks were perplexing. The Aggies went
to Oklahoma and were embarrassed 51-6. Privately, the Oklahoma
coaches were amazed the Aggies didn't make defensive adjustments as
the onslaught raged on.
</P>
<P>
   After that loss, Slocum plainly addressed the team's lack of
leadership. Again, he spoke of the talent last year's seniors took
with them _ six ended up playing in the NFL _ and their ability to
pick up everyone around them by making big plays at the right
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have six players off this team go to the NFL,'' said
Slocum. ``We lost a lot of talent. It's been a concern that no one
has stepped up and filled in the leadership role.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown did his part. In a team meeting the day after the
Oklahoma game, he and several other seniors called for solidarity
among the Aggies. McCown told the team he wanted to know who was in
the boat and who wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   McCown was at the helm. Though he suffered a separated left
shoulder against Oklahoma, he played the next week in a 21-3 win
over Oklahoma State. After the game, McCown broke down and cried
while addressing the media. After a week of hearing how he wasn't a
leader and how the Aggies were on the verge of falling apart, the
win had drained his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was stunning. With their season on the line,
the Aggies went to Nebraska and were blown out again, losing 37-0.
The Cornhuskers gave the Aggies every chance to pull off an upset
with first-half fumbles and mistakes, but the Aggies couldn't
block, couldn't run and, after a spirited early defensive effort,
couldn't tackle.
</P>
<P>
   In consecutive Big 12 road losses, the Aggies were outscored
88-6. The revamped offense wasn't clicking. The Wrecking Crew
defense was wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   And the day after the Nebraska loss, all hell broke loose in a
team meeting, pointing up that at least one Aggie didn't want to be
in the proverbial boat any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Dante Hall, the Aggies' leading rusher the last
two seasons, and Slocum engaged in what sources say was a testy
exchange that began when Slocum admonished Hall for repeatedly
parking his car in a no-parking zone on campus. Hall was said to
have made a remark that angered Slocum, and the coach told Hall to
leave the meeting, kicking him off the team.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had been unhappy much of the season. With subpar blocking
by the line and fullback Ja'Mar Toombs, his numbers had suffered.
He wondered aloud about the blocking earlier in the season, which
did not win friends in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   A back injury and ankle injury cut into his playing time. Hall
was expected to be one of the Aggies' leaders this year. Instead,
he missed the final two regular-season games and whatever bowl the
Aggies will be invited to.
</P>
<P>
   This much is clear: The Aggies won't play in a major game as
they did last January when they lost to Ohio State in the Sugar
Bowl. In August, they had designs on the Sugar Bowl again, where
this year's national champion will be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Those dreams vanished in three road losses in a six-week span.
This week's game against Texas initially was to have been merely a
test of the Aggies' ability to regroup after a disappointing
season.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's Bonfire tragedy, it will provide one final
chance for the leaders to step forward and guide a team that will
bring a scattershot of emotions onto Kyle Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
