<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINAL GOAL FOR GRETZKY, AND IT'S A BEAUTY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ When it comes to Wayne Gretzky, there is always room
for another honor. On Monday night here, not far from his hometown
of Brantford, Ontario, Gretzky will be accorded the greatest honor:
enshrinement in the Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The icing on the cake,'' is how the 38-year-old Gretzky
described his induction while speaking during the first
intermission of the Rangers' 4-3 overtime loss to the Maple Leafs
on Saturday night. ``It's something that tops off the whole
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who was honored in a pregame ceremony Saturday, retired
last spring after 21 professional seasons, 20 in the National
Hockey League, the last three of which he spent with the Rangers.
He won the Hart Memorial Trophy, awarded to the NHL's most valuable
player, nine times, eight of them consecutively, beginning with the
1979-80 season.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Lemieux, the last player for whom the mandatory three-year
waiting period for induction to the Hall of Fame was waived, ended
Gretzky's stretch in the 1987-88 season. So Gretzky went out and
won the Conn Smythe Trophy, awarded to the most valuable player in
the playoffs, for the second time in his career in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest playmaker of his time, Gretzky won the Art Ross
Memorial Trophy, for leading the league in scoring, 10 times,
including seven in a row, beginning with the 1980-81 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky retired either having set or shared 61 records, and he
had four Stanley Cup championship rings with the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, after visiting with his former Ranger
teammates, Gretzky called the four cups the highlight of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we won, we were so young that we didn't realize what we'd
really done,'' Gretzky said, referring to the stretch in the 1980s
when Edmonton won four cups in five years. ``When you're 23 years
old, you think you're going to do it every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pocklington, who was Edmonton's cash-strapped owner at the
time, sold Gretzky to the Los Angeles Kings after the 1988 finals.
Surprisingly, Gretzky said that was not the most disappointing
moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was reality of life,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest regret?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stanley Cup final we lost with Los Angeles,'' Gretzky
said, referring to the Kings' surprise run in the spring of 1993,
which culminated in a five-game series and another cup for
Montreal. ``That was probably the biggest disappointment of my
career. By then, I had gotten to a stage in my career where I
really understood the makeup of talented, great teams. I understood
we weren't a great team, but we'd pulled it together at the right
time. And then we got beat three games in overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky would never see the finals again.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Gretzky came to another cup was the 1996-97 season,
his first with the Rangers, his last playing alongside Mark
Messier. That season, the Rangers advanced to the Eastern
Conference finals. The following off-season, Messier departed via
free agency after a bitter contract dispute. The Rangers have not
been to the playoffs since.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Gretzky said in a televised interview that he would
have come back for this season had the Rangers acquired Pavel Bure.
On Saturday, Gretzky attempted to explain just what he had meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more or less because there was so much talk about Pavel
coming to the Rangers,'' Gretzky said, referring to all the rumors
before Bure was traded from Vancouver to Florida last Jan. 17. ``My
experience playing with the Rangers was nothing but wonderful. My
comment was made on the basis of, if Pavel came to New York, I
probably would have felt more loyalty to the organization to play
another year. If they were going to bring in a guy like that to
play with me, there would have been more pressure on me to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said he had no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even have my skates,'' Gretzky said. ``They took my
skates to the Hall of Fame. If I would have taken them home, my dad
would have probably stolen them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gretzky admitted, ``I miss it a great deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
