<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MORE OPEN IMF  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Nov. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Michel Camdessus, the self-assured but often criticized managing
director of the International Monetary Fund, announced his
retirement earlier this month and already a handful of European
officials are busy choosing his successor. French, German and
British officials regard the appointment as theirs to make despite
the fact that managing directors make decisions that decide the
fate of taxi drivers in Indonesia, small shop owners in Ecuador,
taxpayers in Thailand and farmers throughout sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the decision is up to the fund's executive board,
which is dominated by the Western industrialized countries but at
least includes representatives from everywhere else. But the
board's role is shaping up as largely ceremonial. The fund's
managing director is too important to be chosen in secret by a few
self-selected European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The fund comes to the rescue of countries in financial distress,
offering billions of dollars of loans if they adopt stringent
economic reforms. It currently oversees about 50 such programs in
Latin America, Africa, the former Soviet Union and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the fund's programs often cause needless economic
pain. The fuicted its intervention in Asia in 1998 would
lead to a quick turnaround. Instead it led to economic collapse,
though Asia now appears to be on the mend. Many of the countries in
sub-Saharan Africa remain buried in debt and poverty despite two
decades of fund-supervised economic reform. In Russia and Brazil,
the fund wasted billions of dollars, and delayed reforms, by
propping up currencies. In both cases, the currencies collapsed
anyway. The fund claims, perhaps correctly, that these countries
would be in even worse shape if they had not had its assistance. It
also points to several countries from the former Soviet Union that
it has helped move to markets.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's policy prescriptions affect people around the world.
It decides whether to bail out Ecuador or let its economy slide. It
decides whether Korea should defend its currency in the face of a
looming depression by doubling interest rates. It decides whether
to crack down on insolvent Indonesian banks, throwing the economy
into a tailspin, or to prop up possibly corrupt or bankrupt
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these decisions, says Joseph Stiglitz, chief economist
of the World Bank, puts different groups _ workers, small shop
owners, bankers or foreign investors _ at risk. Because economists
often can provide no clear answers, the managing director has
leeway to decide which groups get bailed out first or at all. The
question that hangs over the current selection process is whether
the decisions the fund made that temporarily crushed Asia's
economies would have been made the same way had the managing
director been publicly accountable to a wider audience than just
his fellow finance officials.
</P>
<P>
   The process clearly needs to be broadened. One prominently
mentioned plan for opening up the process, proposed by Jeffrey
Sachs of the Harvard Center for International Development, would
have the fund's board appoint a panel of outside experts to
nominate qualified candidates from around the world. The candidates
would then publicly state how they would change fund policy. Would
they back flexible or fixed exchange rates? Would they continue to
have the fund ride herd on dozens of countries each year? After
hearing the candidates, the board would vote publicly.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other ways to accomplish the same goal of opening
the fund's deliberations to public scrutiny and forcing candidates
to state for all the world to hear how they would handle the
managing director's responsibilities. The IMF's recent history
shows that the managing director has become too powerful to be
selected in secret any longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
