<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-KENNEDY-PROFILE-ART-N     11-21 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIELDING THE KENNEDY NAME FOR THE GOOD OF HIS PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Mass., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every once in a while, Rep. Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., says, he shows up to address some Democratic fund-raising
event out in the country and the people awaiting him smile politely
and ask, ``When is the congressman getting here?''
</P>
<P>
   His detractors, in fact, have long delighted in calling him
``congressboy.'' Just 27 when he was elected to the House from
Rhode Island, Kennedy at 32 still has the look of the young advance
man who arrives to make sure that the room is nicely packed before
the real Kennedy arrives. But Kennedy has a grown-up job these
days, as chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He and his mentor, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority
leader, are leading a drive to win a Democratic majority in the
House next year. To do that, the party needs money, lots and lots
of money, and Kennedy is happily raising it. No qualms, no doubts,
no complaints about the dirty business of fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to devote all my time, energy and assets, which
include the family name, toward retaking the House,'' Kennedy, the
youngest of three children of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said
last week, very much ``on message'' as he perched on the edge of a
chair in the Rayburn Room, just off the House floor. ``And I'm
absolutely convinced that I'm using my family name to its best ends
_ and that is to promote an agenda that my family fought for and
died for in service to this country. And I feel spiritual about it.
I really feel that I am a vehicle for my family's legacy of public
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Given those beliefs, Kennedy said, the constant fund raising is
just ``part of the crusade, the mission.'' The ``attempt to curtail
corporate money and soft money is the noblest of causes,'' he said,
but he is playing by the current rules of the game. The Democratic
campaign committee raised $17 million in the first six months of
this year, $9 million of which was ``soft money,'' the unlimited
contributions that corporations, unions and individuals can give
for ``party building'' rather than money given in support of an
individual candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy invited some of the biggest contributors _ those who
gave $100,000 or more _ to a day-and-a-half retreat at the family's
compound at Hyannis Port, Mass., this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, an independent group that tracks campaign finance, said,
``Whether it's Patrick Kennedy being able to pull this stuff out,
or business people acting in their own interests, it all adds up to
more money for the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is the downside of being a Kennedy in politics? The
assumption that he would never be here without the name?
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy laughed. In fact, he said, it's easier to be a Kennedy
in politics than anywhere else. ``Hey, it's out on the table. I'm
here because of it. You know what? I get certain perks and
advantages because of it. And you know what? My responsibility is
to make the most of it, and that's what I hope to do. It gives me a
certain freedom. I get to josh with my colleagues about it. It's
the opener at all my events _ `I'm sure I'm in this position at the
ripe age of 32, and it had nothing to do with my last name.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he struggled to come to grips with the name as a
teenager, when he underwent treatment for substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I suffered from terrible anxiety and depression over
how to reconcile who I was to a very public family that I believed
had expectations for me, that I felt some personal obligation to
fulfill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I had a lot of sorting out to do, on top of my adolescent
years, which invariably are just crazy years for any young person
anyway. I had a lot on my plate, and I got caught up in drugs and
alcohol _ it was an alternative to getting treatment _ and because
of my hitting a wall with that I was able to get treatment. And the
whole world of figuring out these issues and resolving these
dilemmas opened up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who is single, was 21 when he first ran for office,
ousting a longtime Democratic incumbent from the state Legislature
with the help of a big-spending campaign. He won his House seat in
1994, the Republican landslide year, while his father was
struggling for his political life in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many, Patrick Kennedy decided last year not
to run for the Senate, for the seat held by the retiring Sen. John
Chafee, a Republican, who has since died. Kennedy said he had no
regrets about the decision, although his father liked the idea of
serving together with him. As it is, Kennedy said, he has lunch
with his father once or twice a week, but ``the House is going to
be my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt appointed him to the position of campaign committee
chairman, and if the Democrats pick up the handful of seats
necessary to make a majority next year, Gephardt will be speaker
and Kennedy will have a very powerful mentor _ not to mention a
seat on the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we retake the House and I retake my seat on the
Appropriations Committee, I'm going to be on track at a very young
age to gaining some real power on the most powerful committee of
the United States Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But first comes a year of political struggle. ``It's going to be
white hot,'' Kennedy said. ``I don't see a more contentious battle
politically, even in a presidential election year, than the battle
for control of the House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
