<HEADER>
A7116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ORGAN-TRANSPLANT     11-21 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IMPEDING FAIR ACCESS TO ORGANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Nov. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert have engineered another delay of important reforms to the
nation's system for distributing donated human organs for
transplants. The delay would prevent new regulations from going
into effect until next year, giving opponents of the reform more
opportunity to organize efforts that could postpone the new rules
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans attached their rider to a package containing two
bills, one that would allow disabled people to work without losing
Medicare benefits and another that would extend certain tax
credits. These are highly popular bills that President Clinton is
expected to sign.
</P>
<P>
   The rider would hurt patients who are in the greatest medical
need. About 62,000 Americans are now waiting to receive organ
transplants, and 4,000 die each year while waiting. For nearly five
years, the Clinton administration has been trying to improve the
current allocation system, which directs donated organs to patients
in the local area before they are offered regionally. This means
sicker patients often have to wait longer than healthier ones
simply because of where they live.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposed regulations would revamp the
system to allow broader organ sharing across wider regions and give
medical criteria more weight. The United Network for Organ Sharing,
a private organization that coordinates distribution nationally,
has fought the new regulations, even though the group would be
given authority to design the new allocation system. Many small
transplant centers have lobbied vigorously against any change,
fearing a reduction in their supply of locally donated organs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Congress issued a one-year moratorium on the reforms.
The new rider would further delay them by 90 days. That means the
regulations would not go into effect until after Congress returned
from its holiday break, giving opponents a chance to extend the
effective date yet again. The two leaders realize that Congress
would be less likely to undo rules that were already in place when
it came back to work. For that reason, the administration had
agreed to a shorter delay that would push off the effective date to
early January, before Congress returns. That compromise is in the
omnibus budget bill. Unfortunately, under procedural rules, the
Lott-Hastert rider is expected to override that compromise.
</P>
<P>
   There has been lengthy public debate on this issue. The system
needs to be made more rational and less dependent on geography. The
longer Congress blocks reform, the greater the chance that lives
will be lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-21 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SOFTER SIDE OF STEINBRENNER
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in category ``s'')  
(rk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Psst. The New York Yankees aren't going anywhere. Not
to New Jersey. Not to the West Side. A glittering new 21st-century
stadium will blossom in the Bronx, where the greatest tradition in
all of sports will continue. Bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner was sitting in the lounge of the Regency
Hotel, reflecting, reminiscing. At 69 he is the principal owner of
the undisputed best team in baseball, and he is not just loving it,
he seems to be cherishing it. His eyes are on his legacy. The man
who managed to get himself banned from baseball not once but twice,
who feuded with Yogi Berra and Billy Martin and Reggie Jackson and
anybody else who came into the neighborhood, is turning into a
class act, and an emotional one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Fans have picked up on this. A few days after the Yankees won
the World Series, Steinbrenner dropped by the Post House, an East
Side steak house, for lunch. As he walked toward his table in the
back, the patrons began clapping and soon the restaurant was filled
with applause. The same thing happened a few days later at the 21
Club.
</P>
<P>
   A few things are at work here. First, Steinbrenner is better
behaved. It took a long time, but some projects are tougher than
others. Second, the current edition of the New York Yankees is more
than just a great team. In its character and personality, it's an
almost perfect reflection of the denizens of New York City in the
late '90s _ decent, ambitious, hard-working, diverse, resilient,
tough and collectively triumphant. More than is usual, New York
fans see themselves in these Yankees. When Joe Torre, that ultimate
father figure, went down with cancer, much of the city held its
breath, and more people than you might imagine prayed.
</P>
<P>
   By season's end, with a World Series sweep having silenced the
obnoxiously chanting, tomahawk-chopping Atlantans, the Yankees
players, the owner, the manager and an extraordinary number of fans
were weeping.
</P>
<P>
   I had heard there was no crying in baseball. One might have
thought that would be especially true of New York. One might have
been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who you are,'' said Steinbrenner, ``in this city
you've got to be a battler to get anywhere. And this team embodies
that. You have your manager finding out in spring training that he
has cancer. And we had Darryl Strawberry and his problems, and him
coming down with cancer. And during the year we had three of our
young players lose their fathers. But the team stayed focused. This
team had more heart than any team I've ever had. And I'll tell you,
I think this city is like that, which is why New York right now is
probably the hottest place in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When Steinbrenner, a shipbuilder from Cleveland, took over the
Yankees in 1973 it was a raggedy outfit that hadn't won in ages. He
promised he would be a hands-off owner. ``What a lie that was,'' he
said. ``I come in one day and they're talking about how tough times
are and there are fresh flowers on every secretary's desk. Every
day they did that. I said, `How much does this cost?' It was
running us thousands. I said, `Cut it out!'''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. ``I got involved,'' he said. He talked about the
team losing Joe DiMaggio this year. He talked about his father, who
was a top student and champion athlete at MIT, and he spoke
movingly about Billy Martin, whom he hired and fired so often it
made New Yorkers dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Billy died he was still my friend and he was still on my
payroll. He was with me two days before he died. As a favor to me,
he read `The Night Before Christmas' at this big Christmas concert
I do for underprivileged children. We had dinner together. We were
very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was killed in a truck accident on an icy road in upstate
New York on Christmas Day, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Steinbrenner if he would assure New Yorkers that the
Yankees weren't going anywhere, that they would stay in the Bronx.
It was obvious what he wanted to say. But he said he's still
negotiating. Later, people very close to Steinbrenner said very
definitely that he would never take the team out of New York.
</P>
<P>
   No one would rule out a move to the West Side, but I am
convinced that it won't happen. The once and future home of the
Yankees is in the Bronx. Meanwhile New Yorkers have the great joy
of watching a team that is perhaps the greatest ever. It's George
Steinbrenner's gift to a city that has been very, very good to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
