<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PATRIOTS     11-21 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS MANHANDLE BLEDSOE, BEAT PATRIOTS, 27-17 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nobody had to alert the Miami Dolphins' defense Sunday
to the perils of facing a quarterback like the New England
Patriots' Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such a great arm and he's so big,'' Dolphins middle
linebacker Zach Thomas said. ``He just sits in there and he usually
hits teams big when you can't get any pressure. But when you get
pressure, it doesn't matter how good your quarterback is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins indeed mounted pressure Sunday. Thomas was speaking
after Miami's 27-17 victory over New England before 74,295 at Pro
Player Stadium, a game in which the Dolphin defense had five
interceptions. Miami moved to 8-2, while dropping New England to
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to him early and he started getting a little rattled,
started letting the ball fly,'' cornerback Sam Madison, who had one
of the interceptions, said of Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who was sacked four times, readily acknowledged his
part in the Patriots' downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball's in my hands, it's my responsibility to take
care of it, and when I turn it over five times, we got no chance,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the interceptions of Bledsoe came in the fourth quarter,
the first with Miami nursing a 24-17 lead. He threw in the flat
only to have the 6-foot-6-inch defensive end Jason Taylor in better
position to catch it than the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Miami possession at the Patriots' 21. Seven plays
later, with 3 minutes 11 seconds left in th Olindo Mare
kicked a 23-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots still had some faint hope, but that evaporated with
Jerry Wilson's interception with 1:05 left.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which gave Miami a sweep of the teams' two games
this season, left the Patriots with a two-game losing streak and
the Dolphins crowing about being able to overcome last week's 23-3
loss to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't continue to lose ground like this,'' Patriots coach
Pete Carroll said. ``This was an enormous opportunity for us to get
back in one game, but we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson said: ``In our division, you have
no room for error. I think our entire football team really laid it
on the line this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory could have been costly. Damon Huard, who has a 4-1
record as the starting quarterback since Dan Marino suffered a neck
injury, had to leave the game late in the third quarter with a
broken nose. Miami led at the time, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by the journeyman Scott Zolak, who spent eight
seasons with the Patriots before being waived by the Jets this
season. Zolak took the collar as a passer, 0 for 4, but the
Dolphins relied primarily on the rookie running back J.J. Johnson,
who ran for 106 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's neck injury has healed enough so that he can resume
practice on Monday, and he has a chance of starting on Thanksgiving
Day at Dallas, Jimmy Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dan can't play and I have to play Thursday, I'll be fine,''
Huard said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left, Huard did throw two touchdown passes, both to
wide receiver Oronde Gadsden.
</P>
<P>
   Miami fell behind early in the game when Terry Allen scored on a
6-yard run. A trade of field goals left the visitors ahead midway
through the second quarter. That's when Gadsden cashed in on his
first touchdown, a 4-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 10-10 in the third quarter, Gadsden
leaped high to seal a 3-yard touchdown catch, and Miami kept the
lead the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Johnson's 1-yard run expanded Miami's margin to 14 points,
but late in the third quarter, Bledsoe put a scare back in the
Dolphins with a 68-yard touchdown connection with wide receiver
Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe kept firing in the final quarter. He finished with 15
completions in 34 passes for 201 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Dolphins tied for first with Indianapolis
in the American Football Conference East, with Buffalo a game and a
half back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough division,'' Miami defensive end Trace
Armstrong said. ``I really think it's going to be won by the team
that's got the most mental toughness. We plan on being that team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
