<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudd's 16-year streak of at least 1 win ends
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ Ricky Rudd got a top 10 finish in the No. 10 Ford
(he was seventh) in Sunday's Napa 500, but his streak of having won
at least one race a season ended after 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was more relieved than disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I'm just glad it's over with,'' Rudd
said.
</P>
<P>
   His next order of business is an auction in a couple of weeks to
sell the equipment for his race team, which lost its sponsorship.
His days as an owner-driver will end next season when he drives the
No. 28 Ford for Robert Yates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operating off three hours of sleep a night for the last couple
of months, trying to get our stuff together for the auction coming
up, I'm just glad it's over,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it would've ended on a winning note, but we went down
swinging. We tried hard, but just were unable to come up with a
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather cooperates
</P>
<P>
   Partly sunny skies, 70 degrees. Was this really Atlanta Motor
Speedway in November?
</P>
<P>
   Last year's race ended past midnight because of day-long rains.
The spring race at AMS has been plagued by cold and rain. But
Sunday was a Chamber of Commerce day, and the drivers appreciated
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to come here and have a nice day to race in,''
Rusty Wallace said. ``It's a great race track and a neat facility,
but it's just got terrible weather. It's got too late of a race and
too early of a race (March). This race probably needs to be a
couple of weeks before Homestead. Homestead, we're guaranteed good
weather so we love it. Everybody's wanting to have the last race
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was nice; it stayed pretty consistent all day long
and made for a good race and easy to adjust on the course,'' Steve
Park said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty neat racing in the sunshine here,'' Jeremy
Mayfield said. ``Jeff Burton and I were talking before the race
that it's been awhile since we didn't have rain here.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's last lap
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan was greeted with a standing ovation as he circled
the track on a farewell lap before the start of the race. It was a
final tribute to Irvan, who was forced to retire from Winston Cup
after suffering a career-ending wreck at Michigan last August.
</P>
<P>
   Decked out in the M&AMP;M's racing uniform, Irvan drove a Pontiac
Grand Prix show car around the track at about 50 mph. Irvan, who is
still recovering from a concussion, was accompanied in the car by
two racing officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie _ good job, you didn't wreck,'' joked Jay Frye, Irvan's
former team manager.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan was congratulated by other race teams as he parked on pit
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to thank all the race fans who have supported me
through the years,'' Irvan said. ``The sport has gotten so big, and
I was happy to be a part of it in the day and time I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farewell lap was real emotional for me. This was really
nice for Atlanta Motor Speedway to honor me with this.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a gas
</P>
<P>
   Braves third-base coach Ned Yost enjoyed himself filling in as
second gas man for Dale Earnhardt and the Richard Childress Racing
Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are good friends of mine,'' said Yost, who worked
the last seven races of the 1994 season during the baseball strike
and got the call for the NAPA 500 when the regular crew member
couldn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Yost was also a second gas man for Neil Bonnett. Unlike his
baseball job, Yost doesn't have to wave the driver around or pass
along any signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just pick up the heavy gas can without dropping it and give
it to the first gas man,'' Yost said. ``It's an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   No Waltrip retirement
</P>
<P>
   Travis Carter, co-owner of the No. 66 Ford, said on Sunday that
he is not taking seriously the comments Darrell Waltrip's made
about retiring immediately. Waltrip, who failed to qualify for
Sunday's race, told a TV station he may not return for season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been brought to my attention that (Waltrip) made the
statement, but it is not something that I'm (personally) aware of
and I don't know if it has been discussed internally,'' Carter
said. ``That might've just been a reaction out of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, a three-time Winston Cup champion, failed to make the
field five times in the final nine races. He announced in July that
next season will be his last. Kmart, the team's primary sponsor,
has already begun heavily promoting Waltrip's farewell season,
which is dubbed ``Victory Tour 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got plans for Darrell to be back,'' Carter said, ``so at
this point, that is what we expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's fan day
</P>
<P>
   The annual Bill Elliott Fan Appreciation Day is scheduled today
in Dawsonville, Ga. It takes place from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. at Bill
Elliott Racing in Dawsonville. The event is open to Fan Club
members only, and as many as 10,000 people have showed up in recent
years. Elliott will sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't call it an `open house,' '' said Dixie Price,
president of the Bill Elliott Fan Club. ``The last time that
happened, about 65,000 people over-ran Dawsonville.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte chief change
</P>
<P>
   Gary DeHart is expected to be hired as the crew chief for Terry
Labonte next season. He will replace Andy Graves, who is expected
to leave Hendrick Motorsports within the next month. The personnel
move would be a reunion for Labonte and DeHart, who teamed to win
the 1996 Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte finished out of the top 10 in Winston Cup points for the
fifth time in his 22-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Moment to forget
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Spencer started his 300th Winston Cup race on Sunday, but
it won't be fond memory. Spencer blew a right tire on lap 80 and
collided into the outside retainer wall. The No. 23 Ford, which
briefly caught on fire, did not return to the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for my crew and I feel bad for myself,'' Spencer
said. ``We had a way we (wanted) to close it out 1999. It was my
300th start and it would've been a fitting end to our relationship
with (sponsor) R.J. Reynolds and Winston. But it wasn't meant to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer will remain with the No. 23 team next year, but has yet
to find a new primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader, who finished 19th, made his final appearance on
Sunday with U.S. Tobacco Company, which ended a 19-year
relationship as a team sponsor in Winston Cup. In honor of the
Skoal Racing team, each driver signed the hood of the No. 33 Chevy
before the race.
</P>
<P>
   M. Waltrip hospitalized
</P>
<P>
   Michael Waltrip suffered a slight concussion in a four-car wreck
at turn four on lap 199. Rescue workers had to cut the roof off the
No. 7 Chevrolet to remove Waltrip, who was conscious. He was
released Sunday night from Atlanta Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
