</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte lams AMS laps
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ Bobby Labonte's victory in Sunday's NAPA 500 was
not surprising to many Ford and Chevrolet drivers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Labonte was driving a Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   For the third Winston Cup race in a row, a Pontiac was parked in
victory lane. Labonte won at Atlanta Motor Speedway, breaking a
two-race winning streak by his Joe Gibbs Racing teammate, Tony
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's No. 18 Pontiac dominated the race, leading 147 of 325
laps and crossing the finish line by 2.43 seconds in front of
runner-up Dale Jarrett, the 1999 Winston Cup champion. It was a
sensational accomplishment, considering Labonte performed poorly in
qualifying and was forced to take a provisional to start all the
way back at 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, it was a great weekend for us, (but) it didn't
start out like we planned, that's for sure,'' Labonte said. ``We
had a great race car from beginning; we just started 37th. We just
couldn't get hold of (the car) in qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac posted nine victories this season after a winning a
total of six in the four previous seasons. Pontiac drivers won two
pole positions and three victories in the final three races.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chevrolet drivers have complained that Pontiacs have an
unfair advantage with their rear spoiler-configuration. The whining
reached an all-time high when Pontiac drivers swept the top five
qualifying positions last week at Homestead, Fla..
</P>
<P>
   Only three Pontiacs started in the top 10 on Sunday. The other
manufacturers viewed the qualifying results with skepticism since
NASCAR said Pontiacs will likely undergo changes for the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't I tell you Friday that this was going to be another
Pontiac show, just like the two previous races,'' said Jimmy
Fennig, crew chief for Ford No. 6 driver Mark Martin. ``They've got
the real package; that's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   Said No. 1 Chevrolet driver Steve Park: ``NASCAR might need to
look at the rules to kind of even things up. (With Labonte)
starting last, coming back up and winning the race, I think the
Pontiacs were sandbagging a little bit this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who finished second in the Winston Cup points standings
behind Jarrett, was offended by the accusations of a Pontiac
conspiracy in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody here that thinks I want to
qualify bad, because my record all year has really been good in
qualifying up until Friday night,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sandbagging, (and) I've never sandbagged in my life.
(NASCAR) slapped my hand at Pocono (last July) for winning by nine
seconds. I'll slap their hands if they say that. (NASCAR) screamed
at me before to slow down because I was running away with it. I
can't explain. I've never sandbagged in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was the only Pontiac driver to finish in the top 10 on
Sunday. Ford No. 12 driver Jeremey Mayfield lost a duel with
Jarrett in the final 12 laps to place third.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent Pontiac controversy, Labonte has a history of
success at Atlanta. He has won four of the last seven Winston Cup
races at the 1.54-mile quad-oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``This showed the character of this team,'' said Jimmy Maker,
the No. 18 crew chief. ``You never give up. You don't ever give up.
The championship was out of our reach coming into Atlanta, and we
had only one thing that could make it a good weekend here -- try to
win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning his fifth race of the season, Labonte held off Mark
Martin for second place in the final points standings. Stewart is
fourth, while Jeff Burton edged out Jeff Gordon for the final spot
in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the winner of the last two events at Atlanta, trailed
Burton by two points entering Sunday's season-ender. Gordon blew
his chances of finishing in the top five when he blew his engine on
lap 181.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah, I'm glad to end up fifth in the standings, but I
would have rather raced (Gordon) for it,'' Burton said. ``I hate
that he had mechanical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who was fifth on Sunday, is the only other driver than
Labonte to win a race from a provisional starting spot. Burton
started 38th and won at New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
