u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-TAMPA-COX     11-21 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-TAMPA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last-minute collapse: Atlanta drops to Tampa Bay 19-10
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY _ Long after Sunday's game was over, Winslow Oliver
sat at his locker under Raymond James Stadium with his head buried
in a towel.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, a reserve running back, felt like his Falcons team
should have won. He also felt responsible for the 19-10 loss to a
Tampa Bay team that didn't score an offensive touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa (6-4) got its touchdown on defense, when a ball ricocheted
off Oliver's hands to Bucs cornerback Donnie Abraham, who returned
it 47 yards for a touchdown with 27 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse,'' Oliver said. ``It was a catchable ball. I
don't know if I was trying to run (too early) to get the first down
before I even got the ball. Sometimes it comes down to one or two
plays, and we can't seem to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gramatica, a rookie, was the hero for Tampa Bay. He hit
four field goals, including a 53-yarder with 58 seconds left for a
12-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That came after the Falcons (2-8) passed up a chance at a
54-yard field goal attempt in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But this loss wasn't about second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   It was about failed execution, on third down, where the Falcons
converted their first five on the way to a 10-0 lead and an 89-0
rushing advantage in the first quarter. But that was it for the
offense; Tampa outgained Atlanta 239-80 after that. Unable to
handle the Buccaneers blitz, Atlanta failed on its final nine third
downs.
</P>
<P>
   The end came when Oliver mishandled the pass, setting off a wild
celebration from the Bucs and their 65,158 fans.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Falcons were guaranteed yet again of never
having back-to-back winning seasons -- in 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh time in 10 games, the Falcons managed just one
touchdown, an 8-yard run by wide receiver Tim Dwight that was set
up by Eugene Robinson's interception.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had a meager 92 passing yards, and wide receiver
Terance Mathis was held to one catch for 6 yards. The defense gave
up 239 yards, and allowed the Bucs to convert only 5-of-16 third
downs. But they were big conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa's first field goal came in the second quarter, when facing
third-and-9 from their 13, Jacquez Green caught a 47-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   On the Bucs' next possession, Tampa quarterback Trent Dilfer
passed for one first down on third-and-5, sneaked for 1 yard on
fourth-and-1 and scrambled for 19 yards on third-and-13.
</P>
<P>
   That drive reached the Atlanta 8 and ended with Gramatica's
26-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The first key play in the fourth quarter was another
interception by Abraham, on third-and-4 at the Falcons' 41, on one
of the few plays the Bucs tried to cover Mathis one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   That interception set up a 50-yard field goal by Gramatica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are big plays,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``We constantly
are not making them, and the other team is.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
