<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glimpse of Gretzky worth trip to Hall
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Not even Santa Claus can upstage Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   As Toronto staged its annual Christmas Parade Sunday, fans of
all ages ignored Santa for a chance to get a glimpse of the Great
One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look Dad, it's Wayne,'' yelled Matthew Campagna, 5, of
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Gretzky was on a television monitor, answering
questions from about 150 randomly selected fans who crammed into
the Hockey Hall of Fame the day before induction ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always hope you might get lucky and be one of those
picked,'' said Matthew's father, Claudio. ``This happens only one
time and there is only one Wayne Gretzky.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who retired seven months ago with 61 NHL records, will
be inducted tonight along with former referees Andy van Hellemond
and Scotty Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   A player is supposed to have to wait three years after
retirement. But officials didn't hesitate to make an exception for
Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame has been packed since it opened its mammoth
``Wayne Gretzky: The Legend'' exhibit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It covers 2,300-square feet and includes everything from
Gretzky's first skates _ worn when he was 2 years old _ to the net
that caught his record-setting 802nd goal. There is even an old No.
9 Atlanta Knights jersey worn by Gretzky's youngest brother, Brent.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky received a standing ovation Saturday night before the
first Hall of Fame Game, which matched his old New York Rangers
against the Toronto Maple Leafs. The induction ceremony will be
carried live across Canada, as well as on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bobinski, who was wearing an Edmonton jersey and No. 99
hat, got up at 5 a.m. Sunday in hopes of being picked for the fans'
forum with Gretzky. He wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he still loves Wayne,'' said his girlfriend, Linda
Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   Fans got to ask Gretzky questions for more than a half hour and
took pictures of him in front of the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   A question from a young girl generated the most laughs: ``Is
there any record you don't hold?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' replied Gretzky, breaking into a broad smile.
``Penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
