<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     11-21 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS TURNS SPIN DOCTOR TO MEND IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A casual sports fan was asked whether she had heard of Fernando
Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the name,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighter out of Oxnard?'' she was reminded. No reaction
from her. ``IBF junior middleweight champion?'' No reaction. ``One
of the sport's rising stars?'' No reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighter accused with four friends of beating a man in a
suburban Santa Barbara home in July?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, THAT'S Fernando Vargas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Such is Vargas' image as he awaits his fate in the pending case
_ he could face jail time _ and prepares to defend his title
against Ronald ``Winky'' Wright on Dec. 4 in Lincoln City, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   That he's known as much for the alleged beating incident as his
accomplishments in the ring disturbs Vargas, but he provides a
positive spin as he tries to move on with his life and career,
which could include a big-money bout with Ike Quartey in April.
</P>
<P>
   He's confident he will be vindicated when the truth comes out
and expressed frustration that ``I'm guilty until proven
innocent.'' At the same time, he admits he made a mistake and
learned a valuable lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I maintain full innocence and, hopefully, everything will be
cleared up,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I blame myself and no one else for putting myself in that
position,'' he added, referring to the fact he unwisely went alone
to the home of a casual female friend.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas and four friends are charged with beating Santa Barbara
resident Doug Rossi there. However, Vargas' attorneys insist that
witnesses cannot place Vargas in the room at the time of the
alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas also claims that HE was beaten up by Rossi and another
Santa Barbara resident, Anthony Arria, who apparently was the
former boyfriend of the woman Vargas went to visit.
</P>
<P>
   After he was beaten, Vargas said, he called his friends simply
to retrieve him and not to exact revenge, as some have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called them and said, `Get me outta here,''' said Vargas,
whose friends had his car. ``(The woman) called a taxi. I was gonna
take whichever got there first.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, was the extent of his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the full story comes out, you'll see that I did nothing
wrong,'' he said. ``I was in the wrong place at the wrong time, if
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I put myself in that position. Now, I'm more careful. I'm
more careful about where I go alone, what time I stay out 'til, who
I'm out with if I'm out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I have to be more careful. I can't get into any
type of problems anymore. I have too much to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Those he DOES go out with are a key issue.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe some of his friends from his rough Oxnard
neighborhood are bad influences, that they lead him to trouble.
Vargas, fiercely loyal to those who are good to him, bristles at
such a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends who were there have no type of records
whatsoever,'' he said. ``The most is a traffic ticket. I hate to
say it, but if this happened to four white guys, no one would
probably mention their friends. Obviously, because they're Latino,
Mexican, this happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that concern, but the bottom line was my friends
were there to aid me. They're my friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have friends who have been in trouble. But you know what?
I know who to associate with and who not to. I give them a
high-five, say `What's up, bro?' and I'm out.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Vargas has been lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers will be surprised if he spends time in prison,
particularly because he has no record. He managed to maintain his
corporate sponsorships, including Miller beer. And, as he said,
he's intelligent enough to use this experience to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a young person who makes mistakes,'' he said, ``but I'm
also a smart person who LEARNS from his mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!De La Hoya watch:!off! Oscar De La Hoya, who couldn't
make a deal to fight Felix Trinidad again, probably will face
Derell Coley for the WBC welterweight title in February or March if
Trinidad is stripped of the belt.
</P>
<P>
   If somehow Trinidad retains the 147-pound championship, which is
unlikely because he has moved up to 154 to fight David Reid, De La
Hoya could face WBO champ Ahmed Kotiev of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, De La Hoya will fight either on Feb. 26 at Madison
Square Garden in New York or on March 11 at Staples Center, said
Bob Arum, his promoter.
</P>
<P>
   If Arum can reach an agreement with Staples, he should have De
La Hoya fight there. The only intrigue with either matchup would be
if De La Hoya were to fight for a title in front of his hometown
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there might be more intrigue around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   If De La Hoya wins his next bout, he would then fight Shane
Mosley of Pomona on June 17, possibly at Staples, according to
Arum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Staples Center has that date open and they really
want the fight. It's a great story, two L.A. fighters,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``... It would be huge, huge, huge in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly would be interesting and a way for De La Hoya to
reclaim some of the credibility he lost against Trinidad. However,
he needs to get Trinidad back into the ring to make full amends.
Unfortunately, it might be a while before it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the biggest obstacle that scuttled negotiations for
the rematch was weight. Trinidad, who has had difficulty making 147
pounds, insisted the fight be at 154 while De La Hoya said he's not
ready to move up from 147.
</P>
<P>
   Arum was asked whether that was the deal breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, no question about that,'' he said. ``... Oscar makes 147
easily and he walks around less than (the 154) limit. He's not
going to fight anyone serious at fifty-four for at least another
year.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Forum Boxing:!off! Forum Boxing lives, only in a
different form.
</P>
<P>
   John Jackson, longtime head of Forum Boxing, and KCAL will team
with Arum to stage occasional shows in California and Nevada, Arum
said. Arum said he also will help promote the Forum's stable of
fighters. He added that he will soon announce plans to expand the
number of Latino-oriented shows he will promote.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Rabbit punches:!off! The 850,000 pay-per-view buy rate
for the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield fight on Nov. 13 doesn't
bode well for boxing considering the undisputed heavyweight title
was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   That figure pales next to the 1.2 million the fighters drew in
March.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, 850,000 isn't a disaster and proves that
boxing has a committed core of fans. If they'll buy that fight
after the first controversial meeting, they'll buy anything....
</P>
<P>
   Lewis says he wants to fight Mike Tyson, which is wise for more
than just monetary reasons.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over the former champion would boost his image after
his so-so performance against Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   However, it might be a while before Tyson accepts such a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He's scheduled to fight Jan. 15 in either Great Britain or
Germany against what likely will be a hand-picked, non-threatening
opponent. A possibility is British Commonwealth champ Julius
Francis of England, who is 35.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, so inactive over the past few years, will need time to
prepare for the Lewises of the world.... Michael Grant showed some
heart in his 10th-round victory over Andrew Goltoa on Saturday. By
all accounts, he also showed that he's still developing and very
beatable.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a heavyweight out there destined to control the
division, it's unclear who he is....
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited bout between popular and entertaining Mexicans
Erik Morales and Marco Antonio Barrera is set for Feb. 19 in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It might be an exciting fight _ but not for long. Morales, the
WBC junior featherweight champ, is a step above Barrera and should
prove it quickly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-CULT-AUCTION-ART-49     11-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CULT-AUCTION-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF MASS SUICIDE VICTIMS' BELONGINGS ATTRACTS DIVERSE BIDDERS
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Many of the items on the block were ordinary enough:
a plastic laundry hamper, card tables, camping gear, clothes,
tools, cookbooks, a sewing machine. Only a few _ a voluminous
collection of books about UFOs, 20 metal-frame bunk beds, a pair of
black Nike sneakers _ offered a hint of their macabre origins.
</P>
<P>
   The items auctioned by county officials Saturday were the last
earthly possessions of the 39 members of the Heaven's Gate cult who
killed themselves nearly three years ago in hopes of boarding a
spaceship that they believed was trailing the Hale-Bopp comet. It
was one of the largest mass suicides in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The belongings on sale offered no insight on what had led their
former owners to believe that the path to the heavens began with a
lethal mix of barbiturates, vodka and apple sauce. There were 183
lots, which included television sets, videocassette recorders, a
camcorder and three cars.
</P>
<P>
   About 375 people came to bid with a mix of gallows humor,
indifference and ignorance. Their reasons for bidding ranged from
basic need to morbid curiosity to commercial intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to go; this is not for me,'' said David Sauceda, a
40-year-old construction worker who was looking for tools when he
was told the source of the items.
</P>
<P>
   The curators of the Museum of Death, which is expected to open
in Hollywood in January, bought a bunk-bed frame to be used in a
display about cult deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Powell, 34, and his wife, Laura, 29, bought seven bunk beds
that they said they intended to sell on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might go for a couple grand each,'' Powell said. ``You
don't know. There are some weird people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the cult members were discovered on March 26,
1997, in a seven-bedroom house in an affluent suburb, after the
cult's leader, Marshall Herff Applewhite, had sent several people a
videotape in which he said the members would be ``shedding their
containers'' and ``leaving this planet.'' A videotape of the scene
made by investigators from the Sheriff's Department showed the cult
members uniformly dressed in black track suits and black Nike
sneakers, covered with purple shrouds.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was delayed by a probate battle involving two former
members of the group, Mark and Sarah King, who wanted control of
the estate. Though they ultimately lost, the county agreed to sell
them the ``intellectual property'' in the estate _ manuscripts,
artwork, computers and the like, as well as patches bearing the
cult's logo _ for $2,000. Kent W. Schirmer, the chief of San Diego
County's property division, said the Kings wanted to keep the
materials out of the public realm.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the auction will be given to families of the dead
to cover the cost of burial. Schirmer said the crowd was not much
larger than it is for most such auctions and the bidding amounts
were average. By the end of the day the items had fetched nearly
$33,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bidding was heaviest on the books and on the bunk-bed frames,
which generally sold for $110 to $130.
</P>
<P>
   Few in the crowd shared the cult's beliefs or acknowledged a
fascination with death. A man and woman dressed completely in black
and gray determinedly bid several hundred dollars for most, if not
all, of the books in the estate, but refused to speak with
reporters afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Stangeland, a collectibles trader who holds a certificate
in mortuary science, said she bought one of the bed frames because
she was fascinated by cults and the power their leaders exert over
members. But she added: ``I don't want to sound morbid because I'm
really not. If God would alter the universe so people could live
forever, I'd be kicking my heels up.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward C. Songer, 66, a federal telecommunications worker, said
he bid on boxes of crimping tools, wires and phone cards because he
was able to pay $60 for items that would normally cost about $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just for my occupation, it's for my life,'' Songer said.
``It doesn't bother me where they came from.''
</P>
<P>
   But some voiced discomfort with the origin of the items.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Benavides, 25, said he wanted to buy a VCR because his had
broken down, and maybe a piece of memorabilia as well. But his
wife, Jennifer, 21, said she was unsure if she would allow
something like that in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Most people said they bid in the hopes of owning a novel, if
grim, piece of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an odd piece of San Diego history, but it happened here
nonetheless,'' said Andrew Shaw, a 27-year-old college student who
also bought a bed frame. He said he would put it in his guest
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   But would he sleep on it? ``Absolutely not,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
