<SLUG> BC-PA-BUS-CRASH-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 KILLED AND 106 INJURED IN PILEUP OF 4 BUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A caravan of buses carrying hundreds of students back to
Pennsylvania State University after a day in Manhattan collided in
a chain-reaction pileup on a foggy Interstate highway in
northeastern Pennsylvania early Sunday. Two people died and 106
were injured, seven seriously, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the pileup minutes after midnight could not be
immediately determined. But the state police said the crash
occurred in heavy fog on westbound Interstate 80, near White Haven,
Pa., a largely rural stretch south of Wilkes-Barre, about two hours
from the main campus of Penn State at University Park.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses say the first bus may have hit a freeway overpass,
prompting a chain reaction. There were no immediate indications
Sunday of excessive speed or driver impairment, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of six buses carrying 280 passengers, nearly all Penn State
students but also a few parents, were involved in the accident. A
pickup truck and two automobiles were forced off the road by the
pileup, but it was not immediately clear whether passengers from
those vehicles were among the injured.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the second bus in the collision, Robert C. Burge,
50, of Altoona, Pa., was pronounced dead at the scene. Burge, a
former pastor of the Riggles Gap Bible Church in Altoona, Pa., was
an employee of the Blue and White Bus Line in Altoona, which
operated all six buses.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Ice, the pastor of the Riggles Gap church, said Burge
had left a year ago after serving the congregation of 200 for six
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was driving buses to get by,'' Ice said. ``He just felt God
was calling him to a different ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   The other fatality was a Penn State student in the front row of
the third bus, who was also pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Denise R. Orndorff, a 23-year-old biology major
from Ohiopyle, Pa., was with her mother, Linda, who was listed in
satisfactory condition at Geisinger Medical Center in Danville.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce A. Nalesnik, the Carbon County coroner, said autopsies
were scheduled for Ms. Orndorff and Burge.
</P>
<P>
   The injured suffered mainly minor cuts and bruises, and 99 were
treated and released, but six passengers and a bus driver remain
hospitalized, five of them in critical condition, Penn State's
president, Graham Spanier, said at a news conference Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Snee, 20, a Penn State junior majoring in American
Studies who was in the bus where the driver died, said she was
asleep when it collided with the first bus, which had stopped or
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the bus in front of us and I got thrown into the seat
in front of me,'' said Ms. Snee, who had sat in the right window
seat in the second row. ``I was just coming to when I heard a woman
say something like, `Oh my gosh,' then two seconds later, the other
bus hit us from behind.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Snee was pitched forward into the aisle in the front of the
bus, next to Burge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken out of the bus,'' Ms. Snee said. ``Everything
happened so fast and I had just been asleep. But I saw his face
covered later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snee suffered a broken nose and cuts and bruises and was
back at her apartment on campus by Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two buses in the six-bus caravan were not involved
in the accident, and uninjured Penn State students rushed to help,
piling their coats in mounds so the injured could be covered,
providing cell phones so students could call home and applying
makeshift bandages to the injured.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the fog began thickening in New Jersey shortly
after the caravan left Manhattan at about 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snee said that while she was waiting in the emergency ward
of the Poconos Medical Center she compared notes with other
students, who said that the buses had slowed because of the fog,
putting them at least a half hour behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The buses were traveling at up to 40 mph, Ms. Snee said. A
student in the third bus in the collision, the one that hit Ms.
Snee's bus, told her that he had been looking through the
windshield and that all he saw was white fog lit up by the
headlights, then a sudden clearing of fog, followed by the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The students were part of a shopping and sightseeing outing
called ``Spend a Day in New York'' that cost $20 and left campus at
4:30 a.m. on Saturday. The 240-mile trip typically takes
four-and-half hours one way, but the caravan arrived in New York
about an hour late because one of the buses had a flat tire. The
students arrived around 10 a.m. and got off near Rockefeller
Center, just south of Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
