<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-CRACKDOWN-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK POLICE ARREST 23 HOMELESS IN WAKE OF ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Acting on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's declaration that a
civilized city should not tolerate people sleeping on its streets,
police officers arrested 23 homeless people over the weekend, all
for disorderly conduct, and referred another 127 people to shelters
after sweeping through 850 locations across the city that are known
as havens for the homeless, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced on
Friday that the police would redouble efforts to keep the homeless
off the streets in response to the attack last week on a midtown
Manhattan office worker who was struck in the head with a brick.
Police officials said they believe the assailant was a homeless
man, possibly mentally ill, but they have no suspects and have not
made an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   While they announced that the arrests of the homeless had been
made on Friday and Saturday nights, police officials on Sunday
night did not provide a breakdown of where the arrests had taken
place, and said they could not immediately determine to which
shelters they had referred those who were not arrested. They also
did not say how long the crackdown would continue.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by city officials that a crackdown on the
homeless had been launched over the weekend came as Assistant Chief
William Taylor Jr., the commander of Manhattan detectives, said
that the investigation into the attack on 27-year-old Nicole
Barrett seemed to be hitting dead ends, even with 40 to 60
investigators working on the case around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Sunday that six witnesses looking at thousands of
photographs of violent criminals had failed to find one matching
the assailant. He said that tips phoned into the police department
also had produced no leads. ``We have had about 20 calls,'' he
said. ``They have all been checked out, with negative results. We
need more calls. We are going to be looking to talk to anybody and
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief said that detectives were planning to establish a
temporary command post at 42nd Street and Madison Avenue, where the
attack took place, and another at 74th Street and Madison Avenue,
where they believe the paving stone was taken from, in hopes that
more witnesses will come forward. He said all leads were being
followed. ``We have been all over this city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, who moved to New York last year from her hometown
of Athens, Texas, was struck in the back of the head with a 6-pound
paving stone on Tuesday afternoon as she prepared to cross Madison
Avenue. She was unconscious for two days but has since opened her
eyes and spoken a few words. She remained in critical but stable
condition on Sunday at Bellevue Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the attack on Ms. Barrett, The Daily News
published a two-page editorial on Friday headlined ``Get the
Violent Crazies Off Our Streets.'' Giuliani, on his weekly radio
show the same morning, said that the homeless had no right to sleep
on the city's streets and he vowed that the city would step up its
efforts. Later in the day, Safir said those efforts might include
increased arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Streets do not exist in civilized cities for the purpose of
people sleeping there,'' Giuliani said on the radio. ``Bedrooms are
for sleeping, and a society moves as a progressive society as it
convinces more and more people that they shouldn't be sleeping on
its streets.'' He continued, ``You do not have a right to sleep on
the streets of New York City,'' adding, ``The founding fathers
never put that in their constitution.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But on Saturday and through most of Sunday, the police announced
no arrests, and it appeared that the threats of a crackdown on the
homeless might have been overstated. Despite Safir's comments on
Friday, his spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, said the next day that
arrests would not increase. ``There is simply not a crackdown on
the homeless,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mode had said that homeless people would be arrested only
for such violations as violent behavior or disturbing the peace,
and she cited data for 1998 showing that of 64,424 complaints about
people who were described as emotionally disturbed, 24,787 were
taken to hospitals and 551 were arrested. Until the past weekend,
only about 100 homeless people had been arrested all year, a city
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was reason to question whether the mayor's pledge to
``put even more emphasis'' on keeping people from sleeping on the
streets would actually entail additional arrests. On his radio
show, the mayor never threatened to have homeless people arrested.
He urged New Yorkers not to jump to conclusions about the brick
attack and said that more needed to be done to help the mentally
ill homeless.
</P>
<P>
   On the radio show Friday morning, Giuliani first urged people
not to assume that the suspect in the brick attack was mentally
ill. ``We haven't caught the person who did it,'' he said. ``So it
may not be.'' And he warned against stereotyping the mentally ill.
``There are many people that are mentally ill that are treated,
treatable and able to maintain absolutely error-free lives,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the state and local governments should do more to
help the mentally ill. ``If you were going to let people out of the
mental institutions, then there have to be services,'' he said,
vowing to take up the cause. ``You know, for outpatient treatment.
And those services have never been funded at the levels of which
they should.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
