<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-FAMILY-COX     11-21 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR: Pressure runs high for family members
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ Dotti Park sat in a director's chair behind the
No. 1 pit stall. Headphones covered her ears, a scanner in one
hand. She rocked her left foot back and forth, casually off the
ground, as if she were sitting for a manicure.
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't planned to sit there long. She usually watches her
son, Steve, drive a Winston Cup race until his first pit stop. Then
she retreats to the team hauler or motorcoach, where she can pace
around nervously in private.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven, as she likes to call him, was having a remarkable
day during most of Sunday's NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
More than 250 laps in, it was difficult to leave pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get worked up,'' Dotti said. ``It's nerve-wracking. No
matter how old your child gets, it's still your child out there
doing 190 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, though, that when your child is leading 10 different
times for 72 laps and hanging around the front for most of the
race, it can calm a mother's nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, I usually pace a lot,'' Dotti said. ``I try to
walk and keep my blood pressure down. If I'm home, I'll go outside
and walk circles around the house. The neighbors usually know when
Steven's racing.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR of the '90s has evolved as a true family experience.
You see it before the race, when Brooke Gordon, walks hand-in-hand
with husband Jeff to his race car. You heard it Sunday, when the
children of the drivers and crew stood on the track and yelled,
``Gentlemen, start your engines.''
</P>
<P>
   You see it in the pit stalls and on the top of haulers, where
family members perch with their scanners and headsets. They also
serve who watch and worry.
</P>
<P>
   Or they retreat to the quiet comfort of their motor home, parked
at trackside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past standing on the truck or sitting in the pit (to watch
husband Mark),'' Arlene Martin said. ``I'm 46, I'm too old to be
doing that. I did that in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   After she had taken Matt, 7, to the Motor Racing Outreach (MRO)
kids Bible club, she headed for her motorhome, prepared lunch and
sat back to watch the race on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Matt watches the races, too. ''He likes the end of the race the
best,'' Arlene said. ``He wants to see who wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotti Park started bringing her kid to race tracks when he was a
couple of months old. The first date she went on with her husband,
Bob, was at a race track. He still drives Modifieds when he's not
working on transmissions for Steven's boss, Dale Earnhardt. She
runs Steven's Fan Club.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched her son race since he started in go-karts at the
age of 10, Dotti is well aware of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had the conversation once,'' she said. ``He said if
anything should ever happen to him, he wanted me to remember that
this is what he loved to do.''
</P>
<P>
   She was at a Modified race four years ago when her son went
airborne and came down on his roof. ``That was scary,'' she said,
``but he was fine.'' Still, she was a bit uneasy coming to AMS,
where Steven had a terrible crash last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst experience I ever had,'' Dotti said. ``I was
packed and ready to go when he hit the wall last year. I saw it on
television. I didn't know if he was all right. I knew it was bad
when I saw everybody around him. But Dale Earnhardt himself called
me from the care center and made his plane available to my husband
and I and got us down here as quickly as he could. That made things
a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   This time out, it was like a Sunday drive. A bad late pit-stop
cost Park track position, however, and as Dotti left her chair to
pace the asphalt behind the pit, the son faded to 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Jones said it's been difficult being the opinionated
father of a race car driver and his team owner. But he's learned to
back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Buckshot have an agreement: I can have a head phone but
I can't press the button to talk,'' Billy said. ``I let Buckshot
and the crew handle the car.'' He gets tempted to press the button,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I take the mike and fold it in and push it to the
back, so if I do get tempted and push the button I can't say
nothing. It's tough. I've always been a person who wants his hands
on the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy's input used to come in the middle of races when Buckshot
was running All-Pros. ``I was bad,'' he said. Then the son sat the
father down for a chat as they were graduating to the Busch series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I disrupted him and what the team had in mind to do.
He felt like it would be better if I let them do it even though I
was paying the bills,'' Billy said. ``He felt like if I wanted to
say anything I should do it prior to the race or wait till the race
ended and then talk about it. So that's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he visited his team. ``I shake their hand, hug their
neck, tell them what a great job they've done.'' Then he busied
himself welcoming his 376 family and business guests at the two
condos and three trackside suites he had rented.
</P>
<P>
   Then he found a quiet place to watch the race by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very emotional guy,'' Billy said. ``If he's running dead
last and he starts passing cars, I get very excited about it. And
anytime he gets around the front I'm definitely that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emotional business. Let's face it, what other business
do you know of that one minute you can be on top and in one second
you're at the bottom?''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the entire Jones clan was up on the penthouse level.
Billy joked that he had assigned an employee named Brett, who is
big enough to be a nightclub bouncer, to watch Buckshot's sister.
``To keep her out of somebody else's garage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this time Buckshot comes to me and he says `D,
(short for Dad) you need to talk to Laytona. Every time somebody
bumps me on the race track, she's down there ready to fight them. I
told her every time somebody hits me out there, it doesn't mean
it's deliberate. This is the business, you rub each other.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little talk with her and she said, `D, I don't care
what Buckshot said, that guy deliberately done it and when I see
him I'm gonna whip him. I would have whipped him that day but he
got away.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Laytona _ ``No, I wasn't named after Daytona,'' she said _
laughed in embarrassment about having to explain this family
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was back in his Lanier (Speedway) days, and I didn't know
that's how racing was,'' Laytona said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first race I'd ever been to. I don't do that
anymore, I know better now. I usually try to stay in the condo, the
bleachers, wherever I can be out of the way. I get a little bit
upset sometimes. But, hey, that's my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
