<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS CATCH BUFFALO WITH THEIR GUARD DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It's too soon to tell whether the New
York Jets' 17-7 victory over the Buffalo Bills on Sunday will have
any significance, but the Jets continue to surprise everyone but
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Who believed a few weeks ago that a punchless team with a 1-6
record would put together a three-game winning streak that at least
mathematically keeps their playoff possibilities alive?
</P>
<P>
   The Bills had arrived at the Meadowlands with a 7-3 record,
including one convincing victory over the Jets already this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Doug Flutie was almost as perplexed Sunday by Bill
Belichick's defense as the Patriots' Drew Bledsoe was last Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bills Coach Wade Phillips admitted his offense was not
prepared for the Jets' surprises on defense: blitzing at unexpected
times; alternating a 4-3 alignment with a 3-4; deflecting four
passes at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The mixing and matching led to a second-quarter touchdown by the
defense when Ray Mickens, who at 5 feet 8 is even smaller than the
5-foot-10 Flutie, blitzed the Buffalo quarterback in the end zone,
bowled him over and knocked the ball loose. The second-year
defensive end Eric Ogbogu pounced on the ball for a touchdown that
gave the Jets command of the game with a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to blitz our spread package, which surprised
us,'' Phillips said, adding that the blitzing bothered Flutie
throughout the game _ one of the few times in his second coming to
the league that a team has been able to capitalize on the
quarterback's stature.
</P>
<P>
   These Jets are suddenly and dramatically different from the team
that lost to Buffalo in the second game of the season, a game in
which the Bills piled up 224 rushing yards. Ray Lucas is now the
up-tempo quarterback in place of the ineffective Rick Mirer, and
nose tackle Jason Ferguson is back after missing that first
meeting. So is wide receiver Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the early season Jets by any stretch. Their
defense didn't fold late in the game (or early, for that matter).
The Bills converted only 29 percent of their third downs (less than
half of what they managed in the first meeting). Their rushing
total was barely a quarter of what they managed in the first game;
they gained a mere 60 yards Sunday _ and almost half of that came
on one Flutie scamper.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets said their switching defensive alignment helped account
for the change. By playing much of the game with four defensive
linemen instead of three, the Jets made it more difficult for
Flutie to see downfield or escape on the run while rolling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to keep it tight enough so that he couldn't
scramble,'' Jets Coach Bill Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so scared the first game that Flutie would take off,''
Ferguson said. ``The 4-3 keeps him honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills made it to the Jets' side of the field three times in
the opening half and came away with nothing. (Steve Christie twice
missed field-goal attempts.) In the second half they crossed
midfield only twice, scoring their lone touchdown and then losing
the ball on an interception _ the Bills' third turnover of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Parcells' beaming endorsement of his Jets: ``I'm really
proud of them _ as proud of a team as I've been in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Are they stronger now than they were earlier?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Parcells said. ``I just keep telling the team
it's too soon to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lucas is now 2-1 as a starter, he did not propel the
Jets' offense to a scoring spree. The only touchdown the offense
produced came on his 9-yard run early in the second quarter. But it
was the fourth first-half touchdown the Jets have scored in his
last two starts; Mirer directed touchdown drives in the opening
half in only three of his six starts.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after Lucas' scoring run, Tom Tupa launched a punt
that was headed for the end zone. Instead, Chris Hayes came
charging downfield, intent on batting it back in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Dwight Stone in front of me and I yelled, `Stone, get
out of the way,''' Hayes said. He jumped over the goal line and
while still in mid-air pushed the ball toward the field. Parmalee
downed it on the 3 _ for Hayes' third major play on special teams
in the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Backed up at their goal line, the Bills were vulnerable to
Mickens' blitz, which probably was the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas did keep the Jets moving, connecting on his first eight
passing attempts. He particularly was fond of Keyshawn Johnson on
third down and Curtis Martin any time. In fact, Martin led all Jets
receivers with seven catches _ compared with only one in the first
Jets-Bills meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who studied the Bills since that game, concluded that
although the Bills were one of the best in pro football in stopping
the run, they were vulnerable to a runner coming out of the
backfield to catch a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't always account for him,'' left tackle Jumbo
Elliott said of Martin. ``Once he got out there as a receiver, he
could make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were making things happen in other areas. In one drive
they tried a few tricks. Early in the third quarter, Lucas handed
the ball to Johnson on an apparent reverse, but Johnson stopped and
unloaded a long pass goalward toward Chrebet. It went just beyond
Chrebet's reach. Three players later, John Hall lined up for a
53-yard field-goal attempt _ and instead punted the ball to the
Bills' 2, where it was downed by Fred Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   Two drives later Hall did attempt a field goal, converting a
36-yarder. On the ensuing drive, the Bills produced their only
score _ a Flutie-to-Peerless Price 2-yard touchdown pass play.
</P>
<P>
   But the next two Buffalo drives were over in less than 95
seconds each, and then the Jets punctuated the performance when
Ernie Logan, 5 inches taller than Flutie, raised his arms, batted a
pass that ricocheted off the Jets' rookie Jason Wiltz, onto the
back of a Bills lineman, and back into Wiltz's hands for an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great honor,'' Wiltz said later.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas feels like a rookie himself, at least as a quarterback,
but he said he now felt like the Jets' starter. ``After your first
play, a rookie's basically over being a rookie,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
