<HEADER>
A7153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-REDSKINS-N     11-21 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-REDSKINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO DEFENDING THE GIANTS' OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Where there was a late drive, there was also a
late fumble. Where there was a late stop, there was also a late
penalty. Where there were defensive heroics, there were also gaping
holes. Where the offense looked rejuvenated under a new leader, it
also scored just one touchdown against the worst defense in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   For every positive these New York Giants create, their penchant
is to match it with a negative. And so, 10 games into the 1999
season, the Giants have won five and lost five. The story of this
persistently inconsistent team remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 23-13 loss to the Washington Redskins was a season in
microcosm. Although sparked by the backup quarterback Kerry
Collins, who entered the game in the second quarter when Kent
Graham sustained a concussion, the offense committed five
turnovers; one fumble was returned for a Redskins touchdown. The
Giants rushed for only 72 yards and they were whistled for 7
penalties totaling 97 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the proud Giants defense gave up 183 rushing yards to
Stephen Davis, the most by a running back in the NFL this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way too many self-inflicting wounds,'' Giants Coach Jim Fassel
said. ``I can't fault effort or desire. But the mistakes are
killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Redskins (6-4) never trailed, the game's outcome
hinged on two sequences in the final five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington leading, 20-13, Collins had the Giants on the
move and at the Redskins' 27-yard line. On first down, Collins,
whose practice time with the first-string center Brian Williams has
been limited, fumbled the snap.
</P>
<P>
   Collins missed one chance to recover the bouncing ball, as did
fullback Charles Way. It was recovered by Washington's Kenard Lang
_ a stunning blow to the Giants, who had already scored one
fourth-quarter touchdown and had advanced the ball 53 yards on the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure we were going to score,'' running back Tiki Barber
said. ``We had them on their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who completed 13 of 21 passes for 221 yards with one
interception, took the blame for the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexcusable,'' he said. ``I pulled out early, trying to
play fast. That's all on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Giants had time to salvage a victory. Collins' fumble
came with four minutes left in the game, and on third-and-3 at the
Washington 46-yard line with 3 minutes 8 seconds left, the Giants
tackled Washington quarterback Brad Johnson short of a first down.
</P>
<P>
   After the play, Washington tackle Jon Jansen collided with
Giants safety Percy Ellsworth and Ellsworth retaliated by falling
on Jansen with his arms striking Jansen in the helmet.
</P>
<P>
   It drew a 15-yard unsportsmanlike conduct penalty. Six plays and
nearly three minutes later, the Redskins' Brett Conway kicked a
37-yard field goal that sealed their victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Percy thought he got hit late and maybe he did,'' Fassel said.
``But you can't make that mistake. You just can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth said: ``I hurt my team. I can't do that. I apologize
to my teammates, no matter what he did to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would not have had a late chance to tie the game if
Conway had successfully converted any of the three field goals he
missed. Conway almost singlehandedly kept the Giants in the game,
missing from 38 yards early in the second quarter, from 50 yards in
the third quarter and from 27 yards with 6:07 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants were barely able to capitalize. Collins, who will
most likely remain the starting quarterback given Graham's injury
and ineffectiveness Sunday, did lead the Giants on a nine-play,
71-yard drive early in the fourth quarter. Two passes to David
Patten, another to Barber and an 18-yard pass to Amani Toomer on
third-and-16 put the Giants on the 3-yard line. Two plays and a
penalty later, Way scored on a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in that drive, it appeared that Collins had completed a
21-yard touchdown pass in the corner of the end zone to the rookie
running back Sean Bennett. But the officials ruled that Bennett had
juggled the ball as he was falling to the grass, where it was
knocked from his hands. The Giants challenged the ruling through
the new instant-replay system, then discovered that an official's
judgment that a pass was juggled cannot be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught it,'' Bennett said. ``I had it trapped against my
right shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would score a few minutes later to get back in the
game. But the game-winning play came in the opening minutes of the
fourth quarter, when Collins was stripped of the football as he
waited to pass in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Ndukwe Kalu beat Giants left tackle Roman Oben,
racing around Oben to slap the ball out of Collins's right hand. It
popped into the hands of Washington's Marco Coleman, who sprinted
42 yards for a touchdown that gave the Redskins a 20-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Redskins' touchdowns, in the first quarter,
followed a questionable pass interference call in the end zone on
the Giants' Phillippi Sparks. Sparks was covering Washington wide
receiver Albert Connell and appeared to make a good deflection of a
Johnson pass when he was whistled for the penalty. On the next
play, Davis scored on a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   After another fruitless Giants series, Ellsworth, who was
playing for the first time in a month because of a broken foot,
intercepted a Johnson pass. Ellsworth's return brought the football
to the Redskins' 30-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   In four plays, the Giants' offense advanced the football just 4
yards. That was enough for Cary Blanchard to make a 44-yard field
goal, cutting Washington's lead to 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants could not enjoy that for long. Davis got loose for a
49-yard run up the sideline that led to a 24-yard Conway field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   After Graham, who completed 3 of 10 passes for 36 yards and two
interceptions, left the game, Collins did lead the Giants on a
stirring drive at the end of the half, moving the Giants 71 yards
in 1:40 to set up another 44-yard Blanchard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   As demoralizing as Sunday's loss was to the Giants, they are,
remarkably, not out of the playoff chase or even the race for the
National Football Conference East title. They trail Washington by
just one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky we're in a division where everybody is
faltering,'' said cornerback Jason Sehorn. ``We've got six games.
Washington will lose again. We've got time. It's not like we're in
the AFC East. And that's a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
