u p BC-MRSCLINTON-ISRAEL-480     11-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-ISRAEL-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S PRIME MINISTER DEFENDS HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel offered an
unprompted defense on Sunday of Hillary Rodham Clinton, who stirred
up a political contretemps on a trip to the Middle East when she
sat silent as Palestinian leaders verbally attacked Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's comments were in sharp contrast to critical statements
issued by some Jewish groups in the United States who became
enraged earlier this month after Suha Arafat, the wife of Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, accused Israel of poisoning
Palestinian air and water and using cancer-causing toxic gas in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who sat silently during speeches by Mrs. Arafat
and other Palestinians but later issued a statement denouncing
their accusations, returned to the United States with the possible
prospect of losing support for her exploratory Senate campaign
among some New York Jewish voters, who are likely to be important
in next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's comments by Barak could temper at least some of
that criticism. Barak spoke at the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations, the largest umbrella
organization of American Jewish groups, at the Helmsley Park Lane
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked about reports that he had called Yasser Arafat
to complain about Mrs. Arafat's comments, he responded that Mrs.
Arafat's remarks were ``baseless'' and ``kind of damaging.'' Such
rhetoric, he said, should be suppressed by Palestinian leaders as
the peace process moves into a crucial stage.
</P>
<P>
   Barak then volunteered that he had read ``a lot of criticism''
of Mrs. Clinton in the aftermath of her visit to the West Bank. He
wanted to make clear, he said, that her trip to the Middle East was
``a highly successful, highly moving visit'' that had drawn
attention to youth violence in Israel. During her trip to the
Middle East, Mrs. Clinton met with emotionally troubled adolescents
who are counseled in a program headed by Nava Barak, the prime
minister's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the first lady's visit to Israel contributed to the
peace process in spite of this incident,'' he said, and added,
``May I tell you frankly as prime minister of Israel that myself
and all my successors will always wish to have two such friends as
the Clintons in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   While Barak's statement of support may not have been surprising
_ he has close ties to the Clintons and has shared a campaign
consultant, James Carville, with them _ it came at an important
period for Mrs. Clinton, who has sometimes had disputes with Jewish
voters over her views. Last year, for example, she was criticized
for saying she believed that the creation of a Palestinian state
was critical to achieving a Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   And she already faced the difficult prospect of wooing Jewish
voters away from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is expected to run
against her for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory
Senate campaign committee, said Sunday that he was gratified by
Barak's statement. ``We appreciate the prime minister's comments,''
he said. ``It speaks volumes about the first lady's commitment to a
safe and secure Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's speech was warmly received. As expected, he extensively
discussed the peace process, reiterating his commitment to moving
forward with negotiating a ``final status'' agreement with Israel's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything must be put on the table,'' he said. ``Settlements,
borders, refugees, the nature of the Palestinian entity, economic
relations, security relations, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said such an agreement could not be based on documents
alone, but ``should be based on the military might of the Israeli
Defense Force, our strategic capability, a unique alliance with the
United States and a growing economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to broaden the dialogue with American
Jews beyond the peace process, Barak dwelt on the need to expand
Israel's economy, and on the country's socioeconomic stresses.
Recent statistics revealed record unemployment in Israel, and a gap
between rich and poor second only to that in the United States in
the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also visited Cardinal John O'Connor at his residence
Sunday, traveling down Fifth Avenue in a security-laden motorcade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
