<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VASSAR-BUDDHISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT VASSAR, A LESSON IN THE VANITY OF HUMAN WISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Utah, Ind.)  (mk) 
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Amid battered picnic tables and grimy
barbecue stands, nine Tibetan monks stood in a park on a rainy
night and cast millions of grains of consecrated sand into the
Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   What they were throwing into the murky waters below the
Mid-Hudson Bridge was the product of 20 hours of careful work over
four days on the Vassar College campus, colored sand in a design so
impossibly intricate that one student said it reminded him of an
infinitely detailed computer-generated design.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mandala, a circular icon that Buddhists use as an aid
to meditation and consider an enlightened vision of the universe.
The monks who made it were at Vassar as part of Tibetan Awareness
Week on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, the Drepung Loseling monastery in southern India has
been sending its monks on tours of America, where they make sand
mandalas and perform traditional music and dance to raise awareness
of their culture and the political situation in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   These nine monks have been in America for six months and will
stay through next year. Before they came to Vassar, sponsored by
the Students for a Free Tibet, they had been in Utah and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   All week, as the monks poured the sand into the 3-feet-wide
circular design on a table in a large assembly hall in Main
Building, the college's e-mail system had been buzzing. Students
clutching cups of coffee came by on their way to class, ogling the
glistening pinks and greens of the mandala, and the monks in their
long red robes.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, when the design was complete, the monks chanted,
blew horns, clashed cymbals and pushed their extraordinarily
beautiful design into paper soda cups. Then they drove off to pour
it into the river and pray that it would send its healing energies
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would just leave it here,'' said Shree Starkman,
an English major from West Virginia watching the monks at work
earlier in the week. ``Wouldn't it be so cool if we could keep it
here in the Vassar archives?''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Taylor, a psychology major, said, ``I just can't
believe their patience.'' She whispered as she watched them pour
their sand out of steel cones with holy precision. ``To spend so
much time working on something that you're not going to keep,'' she
said, sighing with a disbelief that verged on horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got an A on my German paper,'' said her friend, Lizzy
Tuckerman. Despite her preoccupation with her own achievement, Ms.
Tuckerman, also a psychology major, instantly recognized what the
monks were all about. She recalled that a Tibetan monk who was on
campus the year before said he had been held in prison for 33 years
and tortured. ``But he had no hatred for the people who tortured
him,'' she said. ``It's the same way they're making this. They can
just sweep it away, let it go. I'm not like that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' she said, urging her friends to look over what the
monks were selling. The students ambled away from the mandala to
inspect a table of jewelry and embroidered purses that the monks
had brought to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, money _ Vassar students had raised nearly $7,000 to pay
for the monks' visit _ was one of many surprising aspects of the
Tibetans' monastic reality.
</P>
<P>
   The monks' comfort with American ways was perhaps most evident
at mealtimes. ``I like American food!'' said one monk, grinning as
he sat in front of a towering plate of french fries in the Vassar
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the monks had become quite taken with American culture
during their time here, buying digital watches and L.L. Bean
jackets to wear over their long robes. In Poughkeepsie they ate
pizza, played pool and talked about Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The monks are also working, they say, to promote individual and
global spiritual healing, something that was quite attractive to
Vassar students.
</P>
<P>
   Pondering students' interest in the Tibetan cause, E.H. Rick
Jarow, an Eastern religion teacher at Vassar, said: ``Let's face
it, most of these kids come from upper-middle-class families where
all the goals have been achieved, and yet there's still something
missing. It's not the '60s. They're not going to go off and become
monks themselves, but they're very interested in the way that
tradition crosses over to Western culture.''
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed perfectly logical to Jim Contelmo, a groundsworker
at Vassar who stopped in to watch the mandala being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing lasts forever, I guess that's what it symbolizes,'' he
said, shrugging. ``And beauty is fleeting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
