<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LUCAS IS IN CHARGE OF A REBORN DREAM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There is a large opening at the west end
of Giants Stadium. On game days, the area just inside the opening
is an intersection of hustle and bustle as players scramble to get
on buses, greet family and friends and begin the process of
digesting a tough loss or a heady victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie stood just outside the
intersection and spoke with a group of friends. About 20 yards
away, Jets quarterback Ray Lucas was surrounded by television
cameras. The contrast between Flutie with friends and Lucas with
cameras told the story of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 27, led his surging Jets to a 17-7 victory in the third
start of his pro career. This was a victory that kept the Jets'
slim playoff hopes alive. Lucas completed 16 of 20 passes for 142
yards. More than his passes, Lucas' presence _ Sunday and last
Monday against New England _ provided the Jets with a missing
spark.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, last season's miracle worker, failed to produce a
miracle Sunday. He threw two crucial interceptions, one in the
second quarter with Buffalo on the Jets' 11-yard line, one in the
fourth quarter. Flutie had three passes batted away in crucial
situations. In the fourth quarter, with a first-and-goal play at
the Jets' 10-yard line, Jason Wiltz, the Jets rookie defensive end,
intercepted a batted ball to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the end of this day, Lucas and Flutie were more
kindred spirits than competitors. A part of Flutie cheers Lucas and
a part of Lucas identifies with Flutie _ a player doubted because
of his size, exiled to the Canadian Football League, who finally
enjoyed a renaissance last year with the Bills. The 6-foot-3-inch
Lucas, undrafted in 1997, used as a novelty item and a special
teams star, was finally forced into action this season. He has
become the rhythm and blues the Jets have sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   As Lucas headed down the corridor after the game he spotted
Flutie, they hugged and shook hands. Flutie looked at Lucas as he
walked away and said that perseverance goes a long way. ``If you
don't believe in your own ability and yourself,'' Flutie said,
``you get stepped on.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is stepping on Lucas; not the Bills, not even Keyshawn
Johnson. ``Ray brings that sense of urgency to us,'' Johnson said.
On a second-down play in the fourth quarter Sunday, Lucas tried to
hit Johnson with a slant pass but bounced the ball into the turf.
Johnson came back to the huddle cursing. ``What are you doing?
Don't do that again,'' Johnson said. Without blinking, ``Lucas
swore right back as he called the play,'' Johnson said ```Here's
the play. Run it.''' Lucas proceeded to roll right and zip a
16-yard pass to Wayne Chrebet in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of Lucas, the Jets' transformation between Sept.
19 _ when they lost, 17-3, to the Bills in an uninspired
performance _ and Sunday is stunning. A month ago they were
passive, injured and demoralized. The Jets are still hurting, but
all traces of uncertainty have vanished. On Sunday they pulled out
all stops.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Hall, lined up as if to attempt a field goal, instead
lofted a punt that was downed on the 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   _ On a critical punt coverage, Chris Hayes sprinted downfield,
jumped up and threw the punted ball out of the end zone while he
was in midair. The ball was downed at the Buffalo 3-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Frank Mickens blitzed Flutie in the end zone, stripped the
ball, then Eric Ogbogu, the rookie defensive end, fell on it for a
Jets touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about as proud as I've ever been of a team,'' Parcells
said. Checking his enthusiasm he added: ``It's certainly been a
long time. We'll see what happens now.''
</P>
<P>
   Where do the Jets go from here? After a summer that saw the Mets
turn a nose-dive into a run for the National League championship,
the Jets are hanging on by fingernails and hope. From now until the
dream is crushed, the Jets and their fans will be doing the math
and weighing the possibilities. The Jets are 4-6; Buffalo slipped
to 7-4. Sunday , Parcells and Buffalo coach Wade Phillips talked
about the math.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many losses is this for that team?'' Parcells said,
referring to Buffalo. ``How many do we have? Six? And six games to
go. I'm not all that good in math; it's not probable but it's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, when asked about the Jets' playoff chances, said: ``It
will be hard, but as long as they win every game they're a factor.
I can do the math.'' More than likely the Jets will have to beat
out Buffalo or New England for the final wild card slot. Buffalo is
7-4, New England is 6-4; New England plays Buffalo on Sunday,
guaranteeing that one team will come away with five losses.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo then plays the Giants, at Arizona, at New England and
Indianapolis. New England plays Dallas, at Indianapolis at
Philadelphia, Buffalo and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guesswork for the Jets: they have to win the rest of
their games and finish 10-6 to even have a chance. They play at
Indianapolis on Sunday, then the Giants, Miami, at Dallas, at Miami
and Seattle. From this point on the Jets are playing on emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling them it's too soon to quit,'' Parcells said
Sunday. ``Now you know why I talk like that: because it is, it
really is. There's a lot of football left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
