<SLUG> BC-MA-CAMPUS-ASSAULTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT WALKOUT PLANNED AT UNIVERSITY OF MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ Some University of Massachusetts at Amherst
students are planning a walkout Monday to protest what they
consider to be the university's inadequate response to a recent
series of attacks on women on campus.
</P>
<P>
   They say UMass has not boosted campus security sufficiently and
has instead focused on asking women to protect themselves by not
walking alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're putting responsibility on women rather than on the
school or on the men doing these rapes,'' said Adrien Hilton, a
junior from South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   However, a UMass spokeswoman, Kay Scanlan, said the school has
done everything possible to protect students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university has been trying to beef up all these security
issues, and you understand it takes a while to put this together,''
said Scanlan. ``It's straining our services, and I think we've done
a lot in just 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, four women have been assaulted near a pond at
the center of campus, according to school officials. Two rapes
reportedly took place, one Nov. 2 and one Nov. 9. Three men
attacked a woman with a chemical spray and beat her on Nov. 14, and
a man cut a woman's face on Nov. 16, just as 500 people were
demonstrating against incidents of violence on this campus of
25,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   While most students continue to express distress over the
possibility of future attacks, at least a few in the community are
ridiculing the state of alarm and questioning the veracity of the
women's reports of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Students preparing for Monday's walkout were angry Sunday when
they found crude graffiti on a bulletin board at the student union,
which sits next to the pond.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin board, devoted to ``Pondwatch,'' an ad-hoc student
organization patrolling the pond area, included a sign-up sheet for
patrol time slots. The slots had been filled in with such names as
``Ray Pist'' and ``Pete Prowler.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bulletin board, someone had also called reports of the
four assaults a ``scam,'' and compared them to ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' a horror movie.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of Monday's walkout said they expect hundreds of
students to leave classes at 12:30 Monday and join a ``hands around
the pond'' rally.
</P>
<P>
   They are demanding more walking and van escorts, parking lot
patrols, guards on every floor of every campus library, more call
boxes and more dorm security.
</P>
<P>
   Before the recent attacks, UMass had a one-van escort service,
which did not operate 24 hours a day, Scanlan said. Presently, the
campus has four vans operating 24 hours. This weekend, officials
began handing out 10,000 ``shriek alarms,'' and a three-day rape
defense class began Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The university is temporarily allowing students to excuse
themselves from classes if they do not feel safe outdoors. But
Hilton said women would be better served if UMass, instead of
making normal academic obligations optional, would guarantee a safe
passage to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has infringed on my right to a free and safe education,''
Hilton said. ``I want to go to class. That's why I'm here, and
that's what I'm paying money for. It's up to them to find a way for
me to get there safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the walk-out are also demanding that the
administration hold a forum to present to the student body
everything officials know about the four attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As they proclaim the importance of women's rights and safety,
many students say they are troubled by the sense of helplessness
women feel on campus. Women, they say, should not need men to walk
them to the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that the attacks are a way to try to isolate
women and make them feel afraid,'' said Chauncy Young, who is
between his junior and senior years. ``They're trying to push
people to a very traditional, patriarchal way of life, where women
shouldn't be independent.''
</P>
<P>
   While a few students said Sunday that some of the tension on
campus has been defused, many women are still living in a state of
anxiety. They say that they eat junk food for dinner in their rooms
rather than walk to the dining hall, take different routes to
class, and travel only in packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday, I walked to class alone, and I felt physically ill,
I was so nervous,'' said freshman Thea Gallis, who has not walked
alone since then.
</P>
<P>
   A large chunk of the student population has already left for
Thanksgiving break, Scanlan said. Students said Sunday that many of
their friends departed early just because of the attacks. Gallis
said she has decided to leave for Thanksgiving on Tuesday, rather
than Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be home where I feel safe and I know what's
going on,'' Gallis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
