<HEADLINE>
LASSITER INSISTS INJURY TO FRASER WAS NO FOUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ D.C. United striker Roy Lassiter left Foxboro
Stadium on Sunday in denial. He also left with an MLS championship
after United beat the Galaxy 2-0 to claim its third MLS title in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, Lassiter denied Galaxy defender Robin Fraser an
opportunity to play in the biggest match of the season. And at age
32, Fraser might not have many more chances.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter insisted that it was innocent contact that sent Fraser
to the turf, knocking the MLS defender of the year out of the match
in the fifth minute with a broken collarbone. But replays of the
incident show Lassiter throwing an unnecessary forearm to Fraser's
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether I'm there, we still have a good team on
that field,'' Fraser said. ``But it's disappointing for me not to
be able to play against that high-powered offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The play started when Lassiter was looking for a pass down the
right flank. Fraser was a step ahead of him with the ball going
toward the endline. When it appeared Lassiter had no chance of
making a play, he shoved a deliberate forearm to Fraser's back.
Fraser, running full-steam, was knocked off balance, falling to the
turf.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, no call was whistled as Fraser lay helplessly on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both going for the ball and hit each other's arms. He
just ended up falling,'' Lassiter explained. ``When he fell I
didn't think it was that hard. I didn't think it was too much of
anything. The referee didn't think it was anything and the linesman
didn't think it was anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wasn't going in with the intention of fouling
anybody. I was just going in for the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That explanation was interesting to Fraser. ``When he pushed me
from behind, he didn't think I was going to fall?'' asked Fraser.
``That's interesting. That's his perspective. Mine was that I beat
him to the ball, he had no chance to play it and he pushed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a freak accident. You don't expect to fall and
break your collarbone, but it was clear he shoved me.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there an apology from Lassiter?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Fraser. ``But I'll see him again.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be one of the key match-ups of the game.
Lassiter's speed against the experience and smarts of the the
four-time MLS all-star.
</P>
<P>
   With Fraser in a sling on the sideline, Paul Caligiuri moved
back to sweeper as Steve Jolley moved to stopper as Fraser's
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you rely on somebody as heavily as we have Robin the
entire year, to have him drop out and have to throw in Jolley, who
hasn't played in a long time, is a difficult task for all of us,''
Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman said. ``Not only for Jolley to
figure out, but Cal has to be sweeping. It's a matter of almost
relearning how to play the game after that. You're going to have
people step up, but it's definitely not the same cast we had the
entire playoff series.''
</P>
<P>
   The change also meant midfield stopper Danny Pena had to drift
back more than he anticipated. But more than anything, it was a
shock to the backline to lose a player of Fraser's caliber so early
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our back and it was tough to lose him,''
Pena said. ``In a game like this, you can't lose focus, but when
you lose your captain five minutes into the game, obviously, that
takes some steam out of you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
