<HEADLINE>
CSUN SPORTS NOTEBOOK: FRESHMAN CATCHES COACH'S EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A quick glance at the box score indicated nothing
special about Craig Calloway's debut for the Cal State Northridge
men's basketball team against USC last week.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway, a freshman point guard, made a 3-pointer, had one
assist, one turnover and one foul in just seven minutes. But he
impressed CSUN head coach Bobby Braswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with Craig,'' Braswell said. ``He's
struggled a little bit in practice. But he came in . . . and got us
in our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 Calloway was an All-Moore League selection at Long
Beach's Jordan High last season. That's no small feat; the league
is considered one of the best in the state.
</P>
<P>
   So a five-point debut, in a 73-59 loss to the Trojans, wasn't
too bad for Calloway. That doesn't bode well for Markus Carr, the
Matadors' starting point guard who had five turnovers and was just
1 of 7 from the field in the opener. Carr, a sophomore from
Palmdale, did have a team-high four assists, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (0-1) don't play again until Saturday, when they
open their home season against Cal State Dominguez Hills at Matador
Gym.
</P>
<P>
   __ No hard feelings: Junior guard Edniesha Curry scored a
game-high 25 points in CSUN's women's basketball 69-62 win over
Pepperdine on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, despite being an All-Golden League selection at Palmdale
in 1996-97, wasn't recruited by Pepperdine. She said she doesn't
mind being snubbed by the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't hold any personal grudges,'' Curry said. ``I
just go out there and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   __ She's fast: The women's swimming team has been given a boost
by junior transfer Lisa Andrade, who broke the school record in the
200 breaststroke in her second meet as a Matador.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade was third overall in 2 minutes, 18.49 seconds at the
Southern California Invitational on Oct. 29-30. She was 1.3 seconds
faster than Tina Schnare's time of 2:19.79, set in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade wasn't as fast in the same event Saturday against
Pepperdine, but she won in 2:19.37 and the Matadors beat the Waves
in Malibu 159-158.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's Katie Cartnell won two events Saturday: the 500 freestyle
(5:06.90) and 1,000 freestyle (10:27.40); the Matadors' Nicole
Benson won the 200 backstroke in 2:10.20.
</P>
<P>
   __ No luck: The baseball program, boosted by the news it will be
joining the Big West in 2001, almost landed one of the state's top
recruits: Clovis High shortstop Chris Patrick, who signed with
Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN was a finalist for Patrick, whose older brother Kevin was
the Matadors' second baseman last year. Kevin Patrick is now a
graduate assistant coach at Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fixing the floor: The Matador Gym basketball court was
stripped, cleaned and polished just two days prior to the women's
game against Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   The floor had to be cleaned after a company hired to do work on
the roof of the kinesiology building, which houses the gym, left
the court a blackened mess.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for cleaning the court is undetermined. Mark Adamiak,
CSUN's assistant events manager, was relieved the floor was
refinished before the season began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a window of 55 hours,'' Adamiak said. ``It takes 36
hours. We barely got it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
