<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who wants to be a MULTImillionaire?
</P>
<P>
   If that's the American dream, then Phoenix Coyotes goaltender
Nikolai Khabibulin can live it like not many others who were born
in Syderlovsk, a city _ that we can't even find on a map anymore _
that once existed in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Then why did Khabibulin just reject a three-year, $9 million
deal offered by team general manager Bobby Smith? Khabibulin,
starting his sixth NHL season, said he was offended by the lack of
respect the team showed him with that deal.
</P>
<P>
   And that apparently offended Bob Miller, the Kings' play-by-play
man on Fox Sports Net telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good, let him go back to Russia and see what respect he
gets,'' Miller said when he brought up the contract dispute during
Thursday's telecast against the Coyotes. ``It won't be nine million
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jim Fox was, like many viewers, somewhat stunned that
Miller's opinion was offered up so forcefully during a telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strong believer in the American system, supply and
demand,'' said Fox, the Canadian-born former Kings star. ``He has
that right (to test the market).''
</P>
<P>
   Answered Miller: ``If you don't like $9 million here, go get it
in Moscow . . . stand in line for sausage and cabbage every day and
see how you like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Offsides on Miller? Is he pulling a Chick Hearn before our ears?
</P>
<P>
   That might be the PC reaction. Just think about if the contract
situation was Rumun Ndur, the first Nigerian player who recently
held out with the New York Rangers before signing. Or Owen Nolan,
the Belfast, Ireland-born star who also held out with Phoenix. How
would Miller have equated their disputes with the dreaded
situations in their native homelands without making it sound like a
cultural slur?
</P>
<P>
   Asked about it the next day, all Miller could say was that the
more he thought about it, in the context of the conversation, with
Khabibulin's quick NHL success and the fact so many athletes these
days come to the U.S. from abroad and adopt this twisted value
system where money is equated with respect, the more he wouldn't
take it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just irks me when I hear people who have that opportunity
claim they get no respect,'' said Miller, in his 27th season with
the Kings. ``It bugs me when someone is given this kind of
lifestyle doesn't appreciate it. I have no sympathy for guys who
think it's a one-way street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't speak out like that very often. I'm not like Don
Cherry. I had no intention of slurring Russians. I could have said
`stand in line for meat and potatoes.' That's just the way it is
there. But I think I had to make a statement. It's almost more than
you can take sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way, we can respect Khabibulin's stance _ he countered
with a five-year, $22 million deal that the team passed on, and he
likely won't even play this season because of the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was the great Russian philosopher Yakov Smirnoff,
working regularly in Branson, Mo., who coined the phrase: ``What a
country!''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, we have more respect for Miller's opinion.
After all, he !ital!has earned that.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Regis Philbin will someday, but Miller won't be
working in Branson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Today's quiz: With Stanford's Pac-10 football championship
locked up, there's a realistic chance the Cardinal will also win
the conference title in basketball and baseball. What was the last
university to win the Pac-10 title in the three major sports during
the same school year? . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ We give: It was UCLA in 1975-76. The football team actually
shared the Pac-10 title with Cal but went to the Rose Bowl . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Lauren Sanchez has signed to work, incredibly as a news
anchor, at KCOP-Channel 13 starting in January after Fox Sports
News let her go. Meanwhile, John Terenzio, the exec who hired
Sanchez, among others, to work at Fox, has left to pursue other
ventures . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Dave Baldwin, the former Cal State Northridge coach currently
raking in the dough at San Jose State, said it when asked the
boxers-or-briefs question in a Fox Sports feature: ``I don't wear
either.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
