<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDLIGHT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED-LIGHT RUNNERS REAP TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CLAY THOMPSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Watch the arrow,'' Officer Tim Gaffney said, waiting on his
motorcycle at the corner of McKellips and Gilbert roads in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The left-turn arrow went from green to yellow and red. One, two,
three cars made the turn on red. Gaffney bounced off the curb and
sped down McKellips, lights flashing, in pursuit of the third car.
</P>
<P>
   The $105 ticket Gaffney wrote the driver was one of hundreds of
citations for red-light violations handed out in Phoenix and Mesa
since August as the cities crack down on red-light runners.
</P>
<P>
   The special enforcement effort continues into January and is
funded by grants from the Governor's Office of Highway Safety _
$150,000 to Phoenix and $50,000 in Mesa. Tucson also received
$50,000 for a similar crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   It is money well-spent. Phoenix leads the nation in red-light
accidents with about 3,000 a year, according to the Insurance
Institute for Highway Safety. Mesa, despite its use of red-light
cameras at some intersections, was third in the country and Tucson
was fourth. Phoenix is considering the use of red-light cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The funds pay to post officers at about 50 intersections in
Phoenix and 15 in Mesa during the morning and evening rush hours,
and the pickings are easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can easily write eight to 15 tickets in a two-hour period,''
Gaffney said. And that's just him.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty-corner across the intersection, Officer Tim Lafferty was
waiting in a marked patrol car, citation book at the ready. His
first catch of the day was a man who indignantly demanded to know
why Lafferty wasn't out chasing ``the real criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   The real criminals do their own damage, but running a red isn't
exactly a victimless crime. Nationally, about 750 people are killed
annually in red-light accidents, about 25 in the Phoenix area,
according to the Governor's Office of Highway Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not targeting any particular group,'' Gaffney said.
``We've done school buses, old people, young people.``
</P>
<P>
   He says the red-light problem ``is a perception thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people think if they are in the crosswalk,
they're committed'' to continuing through the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The crosswalk doesn't count. The deciding point is the
invisible line from curb to curb. If you cross that mark when the
light goes yellow, you're just another easy target for Gaffney and
his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming up on that yellow light and trying to make it
through, and they're so intent on that that they don't even see us
sitting out here,'' Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half of them admit they're wrong and about half of them
deny it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that you are late for work or that everyone else
does it isn't going to cut it. The rule, as far as Gaffney and
Lafferty are concerned, is zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have just given me a warning,'' a tearful Chantal
Paris said after Gaffney politely handed her a ticket for failure
to yield.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by getting her first ticket in more than 20 years behind
the wheel, Paris maintained that she had done nothing wrong when
she turned left off Gilbert onto McKellips across the path of an
oncoming van on a decidedly yellow light.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney saw it differently. The van had to slow markedly to
avoid Paris' pickup, which was enough for him to pull her over.
</P>
<P>
   Paris' ticket was just another one on the pile in city courts in
Phoenix and Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Since the special enforcement effort began in Phoenix in August,
officers have written 1,129 moving-violation tickets, including
more than 900 red-light violations, said Sgt. Jeff Halstead, a
police spokesman. And while they were at it, they wrote 1,003
tickets for drivers' other shortcomings, such as no seat belts or
no child-safety seats.
</P>
<P>
   Comparative figures for the months before the crackdown were not
available.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa, officers handed out 334 tickets for red-light
violations at 15 intersections in the month of September, police
Sgt. Andy Reinhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably a 90 percent increase'' over normal
enforcement levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the effort has been well-publicized in both cities
and even though many of the targeted intersections have signs
warning of the zero-tolerance policy and even though it's kind of
hard to miss a pair of cops sitting at an intersection, there
does't seem to be any ebbing in the flow of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Based on experience with cameras and photo radar at other
intersections, Reinhardt said, it can take a couple of years for
drivers to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's something as simple as red, yellow, green. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
