<HEADLINE>
THE COURTSHIP OF ANNA'S FODDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After dozens of fan Web sites churning out thousands of pages
and attracting millions of clicks worldwide have put her in the
category of cybervixen, Anna Kournikova finally has an official
home on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Athlete Direct will launch the tennis player's site
(www.kournikova.com), promising to include more of what she wants
and less of what other shrines have been celebrating for the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine how popular she'll be if she ever wins a pro
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   __ The odds that Ken Griffey Jr. will end up back with the
Seattle Mariners when the 2000 season starts? How 'bout 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Following the team's futile attempt to trade him during the
recent winter meetings, online-betting site Intertops.com has
established that line for Griffey staying put. It does, however,
think a trade is more likely, because the Atlanta Braves have been
made 5-2 favorites to get the All-Star outfielder, followed by the
New York Mets (7-2), New York Yankees (4-1) and Cincinnati Reds
(6-1). The field bet is 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   __ A guy in Indiana, Jerry Palm, has figured out the Bowl
Championship Series ranking formula and posts the number for all
114 Division I football teams each week on his Web site
(www.collegeRPI.com/fb) before they're officially released each
Monday night. The BCS lists only its top dozen spots.
</P>
<P>
   USC is 60th and UCLA is 67th after Saturday's game. As for
strength of schedule, UCLA's was calculated on the site at 15th;
USC's was 56th with one to play.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's forte is with the college basketball RPI (Ratings
Percentage Index), which the NCAA uses to measure strength of
schedule before it picks its final 64 teams for the men's
tournament in March.
</P>
<P>
   __ The CBS Sports-sponsored site, recently renamed
SportsLine.com, probably helped the network clinch the new $6
billion NCAA men's college basketball tournament contract
extension. Speculation is the site will eventually provide live
radio Webcasts of every tournament game and provide additional
real-time statistical information for contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first sports deal in history to extend beyond our
traditional platforms into the world of new media,'' CBS president
Les Moonves said when the contract was signed late last week.
</P>
<P>
   CBS owns 20 percent of the publicly shared site and has a
partnership deal with the Fort Lauderdale-based company through
2006.
</P>
<P>
   __ The ESPN2 Cable in the Classroom ``Sports Figures'' series,
designed to help kids understand math and physics principles by
using examples found in sports, has developed a supplemental Web
site (http://sportsfigures.espn.go.com/) that's just as educational
as the TV series.
</P>
<P>
   __ A new site launched this week called SportsUniversity.com
(www.sportsuniversity.com), a branch of powerstudent.com, is
dedicated to using students and student-athletes to deliver the
sports news from campuses nationwide. The site is owned by
Snowball.com, a San Francisco-based company geared toward the
12-to-29 age demographic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
