<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-TEMPE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TO RE LEASE MEDICAL RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 and CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an attempt to defuse an alleged ``whisper campaign'' about
his emotional fitness, Arizona Sen. John McCain said Sunday that he
will release hundreds of pages of medical records.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's &QL; 
campaign said the decision to release the documents was intended to
dispel rumors that he is too unstable to serve as commander in
chief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On Sunday evening, a second presidential candidate said he
would release his medical records. Steve Forbes told ``The Arizona
Republic'' &UR; that his campaign would make public all of his records
in time for the Iowa GOP caucus in January.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, &QL; 
whose campaign has been surging in New Hampshire and South Carolina
in recent weeks, was asked by television journalist Bob Schieffer
during an appearance on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' Sunday morning
about allegations that his Republican foes are spreading rumors
about his fitness to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race, at least in New Hampshire and now in South Carolina,
is getting closer, and things get tough,'' McCain said. ``But I am
sure the American people will view my passionate advocacy as simply
that. Have I gotten angry? Sure, I get angry.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who spent five years in a prisoner of war camp in
Vietnam and suffered numerous beatings during his time there, said
he is ``absolutely qualified'' to be president.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for McCain said the candidate is pulling together
the records, which are voluminous because of many injuries
sustained as a pilot and prisoner of war, over the next few days,
but he would not name a date.
</P>
<P>
   The records, which include documents kept both by McCain's Navy
and personal doctors, will put to rest any notion that the senator
is unfit for office, McCain communications director Dan Schnur told
``The Republic'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's been quite a bit of reporting, there's been
quite a bit of coverage of the injuries he suffered in Vietnam, and
he believes it important for the voters to be familiar with his
physical well-being,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told Schieffer that he was not personally aware of any
whisper campaign by fellow senators to suggest that his war
experience in Vietnam had left him too emotionally unstable to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   However, the national co-chairman of McCain's campaign has
stated that McCain is a victim of just such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 13, Washington columnist Mark Shields quoted Sen. Chuck
Hagel, R-Neb., as saying, ``Some powerful individuals do not want
John McCain to be elected president. . . . I will not stand by
while a guy like McCain, a hero who has contributed so much, is
subjected to the lowest, most reprehensible sewer politics and
whisper campaign I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain said he had no real evidence of such a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no direct information except hearsay that this kind of
thing is going on,'' McCain told Shieffer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain repeatedly sought to make light of the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Bob, you have to be half-nuts to run for
president,'' McCain said. ``So I accept the charge. I don't know
anything about it. Of course, you hear rumors, you hear things that
are said, you hear quotes in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm sorry this has happened. I have many close and dear
friends in the Senate, and people who I have known and served with
for many years, who I'm sure spring to my defense regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer noted that ``Washington Post'' columnist Elizabeth
Drew on Friday had identified several Senate Republicans, among
them members of the GOP leadership and supporters of Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, who she maintained were spreading the rumors about
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The senators named by Drew have denied they engaged in a whisper
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told Shieffer, ``I take them at their word, and there's
no reason for me not to.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. Rep. J.D. Hayworth told a reporter Sunday evening that he
thought McCain's gesture to release the records was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful way to defuse it (the temper issue). It is
such a contrast to President Clinton, who never rleased his medical
records,'' Hayworth said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vinay Gunnala, 17, of Phoenix, who wore a McCain T-shirt, said
he did not believe that McCain's temper should be a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is passionate about things, and this is the right way to be
for a president,'' Gunnala said.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidential candidates in town for a debate at Arizona
State University on Sunday said they believe McCain's mental health
is best left to the voters to assess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters have to gauge that, and I don't think it's going to
come down to just temper,'' Steve Forbes told ``The Republic.''
``It's going to be about a person's entire character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to release, at some point, the basics on
your health,'' Forbes said, noting that Franklin Delano Roosevelt,
Dwight Eisenhower and John Kennedy all had physical disabilities
that could have affected their performance in the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes agreed that voters, not candidates, must decide
whether McCain's temper is a valid campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the folks who have to handle it,'' he said. ``They
make the judgment to decide whether it is relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's decision to release his medical records does not give
the issue any added weight, Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone raises questions about your fitness, you do that to
prove that they are mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said the release of his medical records has not been an
issue in his campaign and he has made no decision on whether they
will be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Flint, spokesman for Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, agreed with
Forbes that voters, not candidates, will decide whether McCain's
sometimes volatile temper makes him unfit to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters decide pretty darn quick if someone is not mentally fit
for the job, and I don't think that is anywhere near the case for
Senator McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint said McCain's passion could be explained by his years as a
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John McCain has a temper,'' Flint said, ``it just sounds
like he is a fighter pilot. People with edgier tempers make good
fighter pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint added that if some GOP senators have launched a whisper
campaign against McCain, the Bush camp could be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Flint added that Hatch would be willing to release his medical
records, ``but no one has asked for them.'' &QL; 
The New York Times and Bloomberg News contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
