<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-TRADEMARK-LADN     11-21 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-TRADEMARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKS IN BADGE? POLICE MIGHT BILL STUDIOS FOR USING LAPD EMBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES -- To protect and to serve _ and profit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you cherish or dislike the Los Angeles Police
Department, officials believe the global reputation of L.A's Finest
is worth millions _ and a new business venture: trademarking the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   If policy makers approve this unique proposal, film and
television productions using the LAPD's emblems _ such as badges,
logos, patches and the department seal _ will be shelling out cash
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And retailers selling LAPD hats, shirts, coffee mugs and model
squad cars also would pay a license fee or face being sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great commercial benefit for the LAPD and the city,
and through royalties we stand to do reasonably well,'' said Los
Angeles Police Commissioner Dean Hansell, who launched the
campaign. ``The Police Department and taxpayers would greatly
benefit from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys working pro bono for the LAPD already have filed the
paperwork with the federal government. The revenue would be put
into a special fund, controlled by the Los Angeles Police
Commission, for police equipment, training and community programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funds would be used to purchase things for the LAPD that
aren't in the budget or that would take years to get approval
for,'' LAPD Deputy Chief Dave Gascon said. ``I see a major benefit
_ to upgrade department computers and technology and to fund
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials have no fear the move would degrade the LAPD by
creating the notion its image is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for profit. We're looking to make our money
go further to provide service,'' Hansell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not businessmen; we are law enforcement officers,''
Gascon said. ``But when we can get into an entrepreneurial
situation where officers and taxpayers benefit by enhanced
services, everyone wins.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Police Commission approves the plan, the LAPD would be
the only large U.S. police agency to have all its symbols
trademarked. Trademarking brings in about $2million a year for the
Royal Canadian Mounted Police, Hansell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Police Department is the only major city police
agency in the United States to own a trademark, and that is only
for its badge, Dallas police Sgt. Jim Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD would not do the licensing itself. A licensing and
marketing agent would be hired for a percentage of the royalty fees
_ not any city salary or fringe benefits, Hansell said.
</P>
<P>
   Trademark attorney Rami Yanni of the law firm of Graham and
James said there is no immediate estimate of how much studios and
others would pay for a license to use LAPD-trademarked emblems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would depend greatly on how much they would use it or how
prominently it would be displayed in a project. It's really
unquantifiable right now,'' said Yanni, who is handling the federal
registration for the LAPD. ``There is no industry standard.
Realistically, they could charge what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Paying royalties probably would not deter productions based on
the LAPD, according to officials at Warner Bros., which distributed
the LAPD-based films ``L.A. Confidential'' and ``Heat''; Sony
pictures, which distributed ``Blue Streak''; and New Line Cinema,
now producing ``Magnolia,'' a film featuring an LAPD officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have to look at the situation, but I really can't see
it being a big problem,'' said New Line spokesman Steve Elser.
</P>
<P>
   Gascon also believes the move would not upset the LAPD's
relationship with the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work very closely with them, giving them technical advice
to help support realism,'' Gascon said. ``This will continue to be
mutually beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers selling items like LAPD coffee mugs and hats would
have to sign a license agreement to share profits with the
department. An average royalty on retail items ranges from 5
percent to 10 percent of the wholesale price, Yanni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would even open the doors for creating an LAPD product
store,'' Yanni said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also could refuse to license products when they
considered use of the LAPD emblem inappropriate. Trademarking
symbols would not, however, give the LAPD editorial control over
controversial films or books mentioning the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's protected by the First Amendment,'' Gascon said. ``We
just realize that the LAPD, despite our problems, is popular
worldwide, and we have the best of images throughout the world, and
we should benefit from that.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to vote on the issue later this
month, Hansell said.
</P>
<P>
   XX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
