<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 11/21/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- E-COMMERCE-POLITICS,
11-21 -- Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., who championed the first
comprehensive Internet deregulation bill, the Internet Tax Freedom
Act, says most of the Internet legislation pending in the 106th
Congress was premature. ``Government simply doesn't have the answer
at the moment,'' says Cox, noting that evolving technology could
eliminate the need for rules over domain name disputes and
problems.'' (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- TOGETHER-THEATER-REVIEW,
11-21 -- Cocktails and parlor games: From left, Carol Burnett,
Bronson Pinchot, Ruthie Henshall, George Hearn and John Barrowman
in ``Putting It Together,'' a revue of Stephen Sondheim songs at
the Barrymore Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CHICAGO -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING, 11-21 --
Scott Turow, who gave up writing for a law career and then removed
himself, is pleased with his final choice. ``As individuals we can
only dig toward our ruling passions, uncover them and desperately
hope, as we fall, to be heard,'' says Turow. (Todd Buchanan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- E-COMMERCE-PRICING, 11-21
-- Jorgen Wahlsten, left, Cheyenne Ehrlich and Peter Kamali of
ClickTheButton.com have more than 100,000 users of their
comparison-shopping software, which scans pricing information from
233 of the most visited online retailers. Several companies have
developed a new breed of so-called agents, software tools that work
with Web browser software, offering shoppers better deals on
whatever merchandise they happen to be viewing on a Web page.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- CENTRALPARK-TRANSFORM, 11-21 -- By passing
the hat among its neighbors, who happen to be America's most
densely packed bunch of rich people, Central Park has harvested the
largest haul of private dollars ever raised for a public park. As
is obvious to the 20 million people who enter the park every year,
this bumper crop of philanthropy, $233 million so far, has done a
world of good. The graffiti-smeared ruin that was an international
embarrassment two decades ago has been reborn as a meticulously
restored greensward where bronze-preservation specialists each year
polish and wax all 50 of the park's statues. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- TEN-CHASE, 11-21 -- Lindsay
Davenport celebrates after defeating top-ranked Martina Hingis on
Sunday at Madison Square Garden. Davenport wielded her racquet like
a deadly weapon in a shockingly one-sided 6-4, 6-2 victory in the
final of the Chase Championships, and Hingis, who usually thinks
her way out of intimidating situations, never came close to
escaping. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAN DIEGO -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- CULT-AUCTION-2, 11-21 -- A
voluminous collection about UFO's and a pair of black Nike sneakers
similar to those worn by the 39 people whose bodies were found in
the Heaven's Gate house were among items auctioned off by county
officials in San Diego on Saturday. The items were the last earthly
possessions of the 39 members of the Heaven's Gate cult who killed
themselves nearly three years ago in hopes of boarding a spaceship
that they believed was trailing the Hale-Bopp comet. It was one of
the largest mass suicides in U.S. history. (Dave Gatley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAN DIEGO -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- CULT-AUCTION-1, 11-21 --
Bunk-bed frames that belonged to members of the Heaven's Gate cult,
were among items auctioned off in San Diego on Saturday. The items
auctioned by county officials were the last earthly possessions of
the 39 members of the Heaven's Gate cult who killed themselves
nearly three years ago in hopes of boarding a spaceship that they
believed was trailing the Hale-Bopp comet. It was one of the
largest mass suicides in U.S. history. (Dave Gatley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- KENNEDY-PROFILE, 11-21 --
Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. Kennedy, 32, has no qualms, no
doubts, no complaints about the dirty business of fund raising.
``I'm prepared to devote all my time, energy and assets, which
include the family name, toward retaking the House,'' says Kennedy,
the youngest of three children of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) FORT BENNING, Ga. -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL-3, 11-21 -- Col. Glenn R. Weidner, commandant
of the School of the Americas, the nation's main training center
for Latin American military and police officers for more than 50
years, congratulating graduates at Fort Benning on Friday. Over the
weekend, thousands of protesters led by a Roman Catholic priest
gathered at the school's main gate for what has become an annual
protest to demand the closing of the school. (Robin Trimarchi/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) FORT BENNING, Ga. -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL-2, 11-21 -- Protesters demonstrating over the
School of the Americas, the nation's main training center for Latin
American military and police officers for more than 50 years, in
Fort Benning on Sunday. Recent protests demanding the closing of
the school have surfaced over the debate about how the United
States will work with Central and South American militaries after
the tumultuous, sometimes violent engagements of the past. (Robin
Trimarchi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) FORT BENNING, Ga. -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
ARMY-TRAINING-SCHOOL-1, 11-21 -- A Georgia police officer lifting a
protester up at a demonstration over the School of the Americas,
the nation's main training center for Latin American military and
police officers for more than 50 years, in Fort Benning on Sunday.
Recent protests demanding the closing of the school have surfaced
over the debate about how the United States will work with Central
and South American militaries after the tumultuous, sometimes
violent engagements of the past. (Robin Trimarchi/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) GUDERMES, Russia -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA,
11-21 -- After chasing militants into nearby hillsides this month,
Russian soldiers now patrol the streets of Gudermes, Chechnya's
bleak but strategically important second largest city. As the
Russian army closes in on Chechnya's besieged capital, Grozny, it
is using a fresh strategy: promising Chechens that their bedraggled
towns will be spared a relentless bombardment if they surrender to
Russian forces, then attempting to secure loyalty by restoring
services like gas and electricity. (Michael R. Gordon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CHAOS-2,
11-21 --Pristina's main market bustling with activity on a recent
weekday. Though foreign aid workers give food and other help to
Kosovo's people, most of the energy comes from the Albanians
themselves, with access to money of their own or of relatives
abroad, and not from international efforts. Five months after NATO
forces moved in to take absolute control of Kosovo, there is little
electricity and an inconstant water supply, the streets are full of
garbage, traffic is in chaos, and no one has new identity papers.
(Thomas Dworzak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Nov. 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CHAOS-1,
11-21 --An Albanian man walks past buildings strewn with graffiti
showing the initials of KLA in Albanian. Months after Kosovo came
under the control of NATO and the United Nations, Pristina's
streets are filthy, public services are sporadic at best, serious
crimes go unpunished, traffic is in chaos, and Serbs' homes are
still being burned. (Thomas Dworzak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) INDIANAPOLIS -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
WRESTLING-WRITERS-MEDIA-4, 11-21 -- Professional wrestlers from the
World Championship Wrestling organization battle on a recent
``Monday Nitro,'' a live wrestling match with more plot twists than
an Italian opera. Wrestling can no longer be left to vague plot
lines and the whims of the wrestlers themselves. The shows are
surging in popularity and the industry has come to regard
scriptwriters as the magic bullet that makes wrestling programs
among the fastest-growing shows on television. (Mary Ann Carter/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) INDIANAPOLIS -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
WRESTLING-WRITERS-MEDIA-3, 11-21 -- Some of the 11,000 fans at a
recent ``Monday Nitro'' World Championship Wrestling match at
Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis. The shows are surging in
popularity and the industry has come to regard scriptwriters as the
magic bullet that makes wrestling programs among the
fastest-growing shows on television. Wrestling programs have moved
beyond the cable channels into broadcast television and are even
attracting mainstream advertisers like Coca-Cola and Pfizer. (Mary
Ann Carter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) INDIANAPOLIS -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
WRESTLING-WRITERS-MEDIA-2, 11-21 -- Scriptwriter Vince Russo, far
left, and Bob Mould, a director, with headset, during a recent
``Monday Nitro'' World Championship Wrestling match in
Indianapolis. Professional wrestling is surging in popularity and
the industry has come to regard scriptwriters as the magic bullet
that makes wrestling programs among the fastest-growing shows on
television. During it all, Russo and Mould monitor the battles of
their repertory players, offering advice to the wrestlers just
before they ventured on stage and going over lines at the last
minute. (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) INDIANAPOLIS -- Nov. 21, 1999 --
WRESTLING-WRITERS-MEDIA-1, 11-21 -- Professional wrestlers from the
World Championship Wrestling organization battle on a recent
``Monday Nitro,'' a live wrestling match with more plot twists than
an Italian opera. Wrestling can no longer be left to vague plot
lines and the whims of the wrestlers themselves. The shows are
surging in popularity and the industry has come to regard
scriptwriters as the magic bullet that makes wrestling programs
among the fastest-growing shows on television. (Mary Ann Carter/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
