<DOCNO> NYT19991121.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-21 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CONTEST-INTERNET-SFCH     11-21 1965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEST-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB SITES LURE USERS WITH CHANCE TO WIN CASH  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Berkeley resident Tom Church isn't among the
one-third of Americans who believe that hitting a jackpot is their
best chance at wealth. But when he saw a Web site giving away
$10,000 a day, he thought, ``It's free, so what the heck?''
</P>
<P>
   He entered iWon.com's sweepstakes on a Friday last month. That
Monday, he received an e-mail informing him that he was among the
CBS-backed company's early $10,000 winners.
</P>
<P>
   IWon.com is a portal with Web search, e-mail and other
functions, much like Yahoo, Lycos, AltaVista and other portals.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the others, this Web site gives away $10,000 every
day, $1 million once a month, and plans to give $10 million to one
winner on Tax Day, April 17, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Church entered during iWon.com's first week, when the site only
got an average of 27,000 visitors a day, so his chances of winning
were better than they are for those playing iWon.com today. By the
second week of November, an average of 350,000 people were visiting
iWon.com daily, according to Media Metrix, an Internet rating firm.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet sweepstakes offer odds that are similar or better
than the odds of winning the California Lottery _ but the Web sites
are all free. So what's in it for them?
</P>
<P>
   For iWon, giving away bulging handfuls of cash is a tactic to
win Internet users' attention in a portal market crowded with
more-established brands. Once the firm becomes a major player,
executives plan to make money just like Yahoo does _ through
advertising, sponsorship and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, we expect the bulk of our revenues to be
generated through advertising and sponsorship,'' said Jon Brod,
iWon vice president of marketing. ``With the exponential growth of
e-commerce, we expect iWon shopping, and its network of 450
affiliated merchants, to be a more significant contributor in the
longer term.''
</P>
<P>
   LuckySurf.com and TreeLoot, two other online sweepstakes,
concentrate on driving players to advertisers' Web sites. Launched
September 1, LuckySurf.com promises to give $1 million to anyone
who can match seven out of seven numbers in its daily drawing. So
far, the closest anyone has come is six numbers, for a $1,000
prize.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: In order to validate an entry, a player must click a
banner and visit an advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing our members into the advertiser's store instead
of having them just window-shop,'' said co-founder and CEO Daniel
J. Laury. ``Our advertisers have been very happy so far.'' Clients
have reported to LuckySurf.com that the conversion rate, or the
number of visitors who register or make a purchase, seems to be the
same for ``forced clicks'' as it is for those who voluntarily click
on banners.
</P>
<P>
   If the player actually buys something on the Web site that
LuckySurf.com sent her or him to, LuckySurf.com gets a cut of the
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Laury's partner, Pierre M. Achach, said that future revenue
possibilities include syndicating the game to other Web sites, or
perhaps partnering with a portal to give iWon.com a run for its
money.
</P>
<P>
   One online giveaway that's actually making a profit is TreeLoot,
a site that rewards visitors who find money hidden in a graphic of
a tree. Its banner ad shows a moving monkey and challenges viewers
to ``Catch the monkey and win $20.'' The Kansas City company's
president, 19-year-old Scott Lynn, says that his site started
making money three months after he founded it in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to exceed $10 million in gross revenue next year. We
have no venture capital. We don't even have a bank loan,'' said
Lynn. His site was listed 59th in popularity among all Web sites by
Nielsen/NetRatings in October. Its banner ad, which shows a moving
monkey and challenges viewers to ``Punch the monkey and win $20,''
was the 14th most-viewed ad on the entire Internet during the same
month.
</P>
<P>
   Both LuckySurf.com and TreeLoot conduct surveys to find out more
about their customers; the results of the surveys are then used to
sell targeted advertising. TreeLoot doles out hints on prize
location to players who fill out a detailed questionnaire
indicating Internet use, buying habits and income. Visiting enough
sponsors can land the player the chance to play in a special bonus
round.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn paid the prizes, ranging from $20 to more than $1,000, out
of his own pocket until the advertising revenue started rolling in.
Now the site offers a $25,000 grand prize, but no one has won it
yet, probably because players have to click two points,
consecutively and in the right order, to get the jackpot. There are
170,000 points on the tree to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   In the chat room hosted by TreeLoot, the consensus among players
is that the big prizes are all but impossible to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play but I don't know why,'' complained a player who goes by
the screen name Strongbow. ``They just want you to visit their
sponsors and make them money.''
</P>
<P>
   With new sweepstakes sites appearing every week, Henry Blodget,
a senior analyst at Merrill Lynch, says that the field will soon be
so crowded that the prizes may have to get even bigger to garner
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will put pressure on the business model,'' Blodget said.
``As long as you make more money than you give away, there's
nothing wrong with this business model. But very few of them will
work because there will be so much competition that they will have
a hard time making enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they don't charge money to play, the people behind these
sites believe they're operating within the law. Sweepstakes are
legal in California, and in most of the United States, as long as
they don't require the player to make a purchase, pay a fee, or
provide anything else of value. Florida initially refused to
register sweepstakes that could only be entered online, but has
since reversed its position.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the information players provide through registration
forms and surveys is worth plenty to marketers. Sandra Michioku, a
spokesperson for the California attorney general, said that she did
not believe these things constitute ``consideration,'' or payment.
</P>
<P>
   That idea is due for re-examination, according to John P.
Feldman, a lawyer for Arent Fox, a Washington, D.C., law firm that
maintains a cyberspace law practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't assume that simply because a person doesn't pay
money that they aren't giving up valuable consideration,'' Feldman
said. ``What's going on here is that the law has not caught up with
the plethora of offerings on the Internet.'' Arent Fox gets at
least two calls a day from clients who want to start new online
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On the Internet) some of the most important consumer dynamics
are in relationship building. Owning the customer's attention and
online experience _ that type of interactivity _ is worth a
tremendous amount to an online company,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent Internet giveaway sites are scrupulous in
following sweepstakes laws, and go out of their way to show that
they are legitimate. They post the odds of winning, and they engage
independent auditors to conduct drawings. Some allow mail-in
entries as an alternative to visiting the Web site. They post
winners' first names and photos. TreeLoot even shows scanned images
of canceled prize checks.
</P>
<P>
   These Web sites promise the opportunity to win anywhere from $20
to $1 million every day. Their methods of producing the cash vary.
</P>
<P>
   LuckySurf.com holds an insurance policy with Lloyd's of London.
If a player is lucky enough to guess all seven numbers, Lloyd's
comes up with the million bucks. LuckySurf.com pays a premium that
increases with player volume.
</P>
<P>
   IWon benefits from the deep pockets of CBS and other backers who
have faith in the idea. Co-founders Jonas Steinman, then a general
partner at Chase Capital Partners, and Bill Daugherty, who was
senior vice president of business development for the National
Basketball Association, felt that the portal was a great business
concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were almost starting to get commoditized,'' Steinman
said. So the two friends threw in the cash incentive to set their
portal apart from the pack and create ``the ultimate loyalty
program.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS is the last network to have its own portal; ABC has the Go
Network and NBC has Snap.com. CBS Vice President of Communications
Dana McClintock said the investment is about extending CBS's brand
and content onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not venture capitalists,'' McClintock said. While CBS
hasn't stamped its name on iWon.com's front door, he said, ``We
feel it has the possibility of being the CBS portal and aggregating
our sites down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Laury sees LuckySurf.com as an improvement on existing reward
programs, like AllAdvantage.com, which pay users up to $1 an hour
to surf the Net while viewing targeted banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to spend a tremendous amount of time to be able to
get a little bit of money,'' Laury said. ``We are on the opposite
end. You spend very little time on our site'' _ he estimates it
takes 25 seconds a day to enter seven numbers and submit the entry
_ ``and you have the chance to win a huge sum of money.''
</P>
<P>
   At iWon.com, on the other hand, the chance of winning increases
if the user spends more time exploring the site. Clicking on a CBS
news story might earn the user seven entries in the daily, monthly
and annual drawings, while personalizing the page earns more
entries. However, there is a daily limit of 100 entries.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Snyder, who plays during downtime at work, said that she
can collect 100 entries in about two minutes. ``There's really no
reason to stay longer than that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after winning $10,000 at iWon.com, Church says he doesn't
use the site as his main Internet navigation tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I click a few things to get my entries, and then I go back to
Yahoo,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------JACKPOT SITES &QL; 
 &QL; 
iWon.com: CBS-backed portal offers typical features _ Inktomi
Internet search, news, weather, free e-mail _ plus one major bonus:
drawings for $10,000 daily, $1 million monthly and $10 million on
Tax Day. The more a visitor uses the site, the more drawing entries
she amasses. CBS put up $70 million in free TV ads, plus an
undisclosed amount of cash for a majority stake; Chase Capital
Partners is expected to invest soon. October ranking from
Nielsen/NetRatings: 196th most-viewed site.
</P>
<P>
   Chance of winning: Depends on how many people enter.
</P>
<P>
   LuckySurf.com: Awards $1 million to anyone who can match seven
out of seven numbers in a daily drawing. Jackpot insured by Lloyd's
of London. Started September 1 after raising $10 million from Ridge
Ventures, Alta Partners, Vantage Point, Dassault Development,
Technologieholding and private investors, including CKS Group
co-founder Bill Cleary. October ranking from Nielsen/NetRatings:
1,265th most-viewed site.
</P>
<P>
   Chance of winning: 1 in 99.9 million. So far, no big winner, but
several people have won $1,000 for picking six out of seven
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   TreeLoot.com: Hides prizes ranging from $20 to $25,000 in a
picture of a tree. October ranking from Nielsen/NetRatings: 59th
most-viewed site.
</P>
<P>
   Chance of winning: Combination of how many people play per day
and set odds. To win the big prizes, you have to pick two unique
spots out of 170,000 pixels. Gave away $10,620 in October to 49
winners.
</P>
<P>
   FreeLotto.com: Promises $1 million for picking six out of six
numbers. October ranking from Nielsen/ NetRatings: 152nd
most-viewed site.
</P>
<P>
   Chance of winning: 1 in 25.8 million. The winner's gallery
doesn't show a million-dollar winner, but several people have won
$300 for matching five numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
