<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FDA PANEL'S REJECTION OF AIDS DRUG COULD END FREE TREATMENTS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A few weeks ago, lukewarm support from AIDS
activists helped torpedo a drug application from Gilead Sciences of
Foster City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Now those same activists, who thought Adefovir had too many side
effects, wonder whether Gilead will continue to give away free
doses of the experimental therapy that was rejected by a U.S. Food
and Drug Administration advisory panel.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory panel's rejection of Adefovir shaved 25 percent off
Gilead's share price, since investors can now assume the drug won't
win FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, AIDS activists are putting subtle pressure on
Gilead to continue a program that has given the drug away to 10,000
of the sickest AIDS patients, people who have exhausted other
treatment options and were taking Adefovir as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   The giveaway, which has cost Gilead $10 million during the past
two years, was not entirely altruistic.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS activists have ``persuaded'' many drugmakers to fund such
programs, and companies have considered this a cost of business,
giving them a larger pool of test subjects and helping build a
constituency when seeking FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gilead discovered, such corporate generosity offered no
guarantee of support from AIDS activists.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether the company will continue giving
away a drug that the FDA advisory committee decided wasn't good
enough to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made that decision yet,'' said Gilead Chief
Financial Officer Mark Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Before it does anything, Gilead wants to hear the FDA's final
verdict on Adefovir.
</P>
<P>
   In one likely scenario, the agency would urge Gilead to do more
safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilead might decide to quit all research on Adefovir and
divert some $26 million in R&AMP;D earmarked for that drug toward
development of a safer, more potent AIDS treatment called
Tenofovir.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead is poised to begin Phase III clinical trials of
Tenofovir. Even if those tests go well, it could be a couple of
years before that drug gets approved.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead had hoped to win sales in the interim from Adefovir,
before it stumbled on the last rung of the FDA approval ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Such corporate strategy considerations will influence, but not
determine, the future of the Adefovir giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said Gilead has enough Adefovir on hand to continue
providing the free drug to the roughly 4,500 patients taking it,
assuming that they remain enrolled for nine months _ the length of
time most people stay with the program.
</P>
<P>
   The tougher decision will be whether Gilead continues to accept
new applicants who have been applying to get Adefovir at the rate
of 50 to 100 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said Gilead's costs are front-loaded. The company pays
$1,500 to enroll each new  &LR; patient in the program and incurs only
incidental expenses thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that we will be under pressure from the FDA and
activist groups to continue,'' Perry said, adding that the company
will have to ask ``whether it makes sense from a corporate point of
view to invest in a drug that might not result in a product.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AIDS activists watch and wait. ``We're all just
waiting for Gilead to provide some guidance,'' said Martin Delaney
with Project Inform in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Look for BioScope every Monday in the San Francisco Chronicle
Business section. Send your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail at
abate &LR; sfgate.com; fax (415) 543-2482, phone (415) 777-6213.
</P>
</TEXT>
