<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INSIDER TRADES ARE EASY TO FIND ON THE INTERNET  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Would you buy shares in a company if you knew
the CEO had just dumped all of his or her stock? Not me. I prefer a
firm whose officers are loading up, instead of selling their
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   High-level executives usually know when sales are exceeding
expectations, or if development of that important new widget is
lagging behind schedule. They are insiders, and this is inside
information. It's legal for insiders to buy or sell their company's
stock based on this kind of information _ as long as they follow
the rules. One of those rules is that they have to report their
trades to the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Once reported, the information is public knowledge, and these
days anything public finds its way onto the Web. Insider trading
information is available, in different formats, on a variety of
sites. I'll show you two of my favorites.
</P>
<P>
   I picked three companies to use as examples: Russell Corp., an
athletic apparel-maker in Alabama; Conseco Inc., an insurance
company based in Carmel, Ind.; and Verity Inc., a Silicon Valley
software company.
</P>
<P>
   Market Guide (www.marketguide.com) offers a quick way to look at
insider trading: a simple tabulation of purchases and sales.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with Russell. Type Russell's ticker symbol (RML)
into the Search For box on the left, near the top of Market Guide's
home page. You can enter the company name if you don't know the
symbol; just be sure to select Name above the entry box.
</P>
<P>
   From the Snapshot view, click on Performance on the menu on the
left, and scroll past Price Performance to Insider Trading. Market
Guide tells us how many buy and sell transactions took place in the
past six months, and the number of shares traded. When I looked
last week (week of November 15), Market Guide showed 12 insider
buys and zero sells. Insiders purchased 12,000 shares collectively,
or 1,000 each on average.
</P>
<P>
   Stay on the Performance page and type Conseco's ticker symbol,
CNC, into the Search For box. When I did, I saw 16 insider buys and
no sells, not much different from Russell. But here is what was
different: The purchases totaled 3.088 million shares. I used my
calculator to figure out that the 16 insiders, on average, bought
193,000 shares each. That is serious buying.
</P>
<P>
   Next, use ticker symbol VRTY to display the insider trading
history for Verity. Here is a different story. There were nine
insider sales totaling 272,000 shares, and no purchases. That means
nine insiders, on average, sold 30,222 shares each.
</P>
<P>
   These are interesting facts, but I wouldn't act on the
information before looking at the insider trading in more detail.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out exactly who sold what on Market Guide by
selecting Insider Trading from the menu on the left. However, I
prefer Quicken (www.quicken.com).
</P>
<P>
   Quicken shows you more detail about each trade and lists more
trading history than Market Guide.
</P>
<P>
   We'll look at Russell first by typing its symbol into the Get
Quotes &AMP; Research box near the top righthand corner on Quicken's
home page, and then selecting Insider Trading from the menu on the
left.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken shows all reported insider trades going back 13 months.
We can see the name and title of each insider making a trade, the
trade date, action (type of trade), number of shares, the trade
share price and more.
</P>
<P>
   The Action column shows whether the stock was bought or sold on
the open market or acquired by exercising a stock option.
</P>
<P>
   Another entry you'll often see in the Action column is Planned
Sale, a notice of intent to sell required by the SEC under certain
conditions. The planned sale notice by itself is not a trade.
Sometimes the insider doesn't end up selling any or all of the
shares specified.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to Russell, you see that quite a few insiders
bought relatively small numbers of shares on the open market in
recent months. You can hone in on the transactions for each insider
by clicking on individual names.
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably notice inconsistencies in names and titles
because the information comes from reports filed with the SEC.
Sometimes the same person will list a different title on different
reports, for instance, ``chief executive officer'' on one report,
and simply ``officer'' on another. He may use his full name one
time and initials another time.
</P>
<P>
   Let's move on to Conseco by typing its ticker symbol into the
Symbol(s) box above the insider trades list. Here's a surprise! I
expected most of the trades would be exercises of options at a
fraction of the current share price. Instead, officers and
directors are buying hundreds of thousands of shares at current
market prices. Many of the trades amounted to several million
dollars. There's a message here, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, let's look at Verity. When I looked, the first 11
entries were planned sale notices, most for substantial amounts, by
officers and directors. But don't jump to conclusions. Maybe they
are planning to sell shares they will be receiving by exercising
options. It is common practice, especially in technology companies,
to reward employees with lucrative stock options, sometimes in lieu
of higher salaries. The employees may consider the options part of
their salary, and as a matter of course, sell the stock the same
day they exercise the option.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what you'll see if you scan down past the planned
sale notices: a series of sales and exercises, on the same date,
and for the same number of shares. I think you'll find it
interesting to compare the option exercise price to the
corresponding sale price.
</P>
<P>
   What conclusions can we draw from our insider trading analysis
of Russell, Conseco, and Verity?
</P>
<P>
   Most of Russell's insider buying is penny ante. I don't know
what to make of a company whose CEO only owns 2,000 shares.
Verity's insider trading is innocuous; it's all related to the
exercise of options and is not significant. As for Conseco . . .
excuse me while I call my broker.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., and publishes the Winning
Investing newsletter. You can read his columns at
www.winninginvesting.com or contact him at
hdomash &LR; winninginvesting.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
